{"title_page": "2002 Austrian Grand Prix", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix race report\n|Type          = F1\n|Country       = Austria\n|Grand Prix    = Austrian\n|Details ref   = <ref name=CF1Overview>{{cite web|title=2002 Austrian GP: XXXI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von Osterreich|url=http://www.chicanef1.dyndns.org/racetit.pl?year=2002&gp=Austrian%20GP|publisher=Chicane F1|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717203039/http://www.chicanef1.dyndns.org/racetit.pl?year=2002&gp=Austrian%20GP|archivedate=14 July 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=GPCOMRace>{{cite web|title=Grand PrIx Results: Austrian GP, 2002|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr686.html|publisher=GrandPrix.com|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021012450/http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr686.html|archivedate=21 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|Date          = 12 May\n|Year          = 2002 \n|Image         = Circuit A1 Ring.svg\n|Official name = XXXI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von \u00d6sterreich<ref name=CF1Overview/>\n|Race_No       = 6\n|Season_No     = 17\n|Location      = [[Red Bull Ring|A1-Ring]], [[Spielberg, Austria|Spielberg]], [[Austria]]\n|Course        = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi     = 2.684\n|Course_km     = 4.326\n|Distance_laps = 71\n|Distance_mi   = 190.564\n|Distance_km   = 307.146\n|Weather       = Clear, Air Temp: 20\u00b0C\n|Attendance    = 81,000\n|Pole_Driver   = [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|Pole_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Pole_Time     = 1:08.082\n|Pole_Country  = Brazil\n|Fast_Driver   = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|Fast_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Fast_Time     = 1:09.298\n|Fast_Lap      = 68\n|Fast_Country  = Germany\n|First_Driver  = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|First_Team    = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|First_Country = Germany\n|Second_Driver = [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|Second_Team   = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Second_Country= Brazil\n|Third_Driver  = [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n|Third_Team    = [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n|Third_Country = Colombia\n|Lapchart      = {{F1Laps2002|AUT}}\n}}\nThe '''2002 Austrian Grand Prix''' (formally the '''XXVI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von \u00d6sterreich''') was a [[Formula One]] motor race held on 12 May 2002 at the [[Red Bull Ring|A1-Ring]] in [[Spielberg, Styria]]. It was the sixth round of the [[2002 Formula One World Championship]] and the 25th Austrian Grand Prix as part of the Formula One World Championship. [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] won the 71-lap race after starting from third position. His teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]] finished second, and [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] took third for the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team.\n\nBarrichello started the race from the [[pole position]] after recording the fastest lap in qualifying; Williams driver [[Ralf Schumacher]] started second, but was passed by Michael Schumacher in the first corner. Barrichello maintained the lead through most of the race until Ferrari invoked [[team orders]] on him to allow Michael Schumacher to win the race on the final lap and improve his standing in the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|World Drivers' Championship]]. It was his first Austrian Grand Prix victory, his fourth in a row in the 2002 season and the 58th of his career. The [[safety car]] was deployed twice during the race, which included a major accident on lap 28 involving [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] driver [[Takuma Sato]] and [[Nick Heidfeld]] of the [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]] team, who both sustained light injuries.\n\nAt the post-race podium ceremony Michael Schumacher implored Barrichello to mount the stand reserved for the race winner and gave his first-place trophy to his teammate. That led the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA; Formula One's governing body) to fine Ferrari, Michael Schumacher and Barrichello $1 million on 26 June; each paid a third immediately, while the remainder was suspended. Following a review, the FIA banned the practice of team orders beginning with the [[2003 Formula One World Championship|2003 season]]; they began again allowing the practice following the [[2010 Formula One World Championship|2010 championship]].\n\nThe win increased Michael Schumacher's lead in the World Drivers' Championship to 27 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]] over Montoya in second place. Ralf Schumacher came fourth to maintain third place, and Barrichello moved past [[David Coulthard]] of the [[McLaren]] team to fourth. In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|World Constructors' Championship]], Ferrari further extended their advantage over Williams to 16 points. McLaren were another 36 points behind in third as [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] and Sauber battled for fourth with eleven races remaining in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Red Bull Ring, April 18, 2018 SkySat.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of the AI Ring, now called the Red Bull Ring, where the race was held | The [[Red Bull Ring|A1 Ring]], now called the Red Bull Ring ''(pictured in 2018)'', where the race was held.]]\n\nThe 2002 [[Austrian Grand Prix]] was the 6th of 17 motor races in the [[2002 Formula One World Championship]],<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /> and the 25th time it formed part of the championship.<ref name=CrashPreview>{{cite web|title=Preview \u2013 Austrian Grand Prix 2002|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/preview/42080/1/preview-austrian-grand-prix-2002|publisher=Crash|date=9 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The 71-lap race was held at the 9-turn {{Convert|4.326|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Red Bull Ring|A1 Ring]] in [[Spielberg, Styria]], on 12 May 2002.<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /><ref name=\"CrashPreview\" /> With very few sections requiring drivers competitors to slow down, the track gives teams an opportunity to push their engines to their full potential. 70 percent of the lap can be driven at full racing speed, although the circuit's relatively high altitude of {{Convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} offers less oxygen to feed the combustion engines, reducing their performance by approximately seven percent.<ref name=\"CrashPreview\" />\n\nHaving won four of the season's five previous races, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] led the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] with 44 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]. [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] and [[Ralf Schumacher]] of the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team were second and third with 23 and 20 points, respectively. Driving for [[McLaren]], [[David Coulthard]] stood in fourth position with nine points, and [[Jenson Button]] for [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] was a further point behind in fifth place.<ref name=\"2002points\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/freepress/F1_guide_2002/Championship.html|title=Drivers' and Constructors' Provisional Standings|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021221123803/http://www.fia.com/freepress/F1_guide_2002/Championship.html|archivedate=21 December 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]], Ferrari led with 50 points, seven ahead of Williams in second place. McLaren with 13 points were third, with Renault and [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]] tied for fourth with eight points apiece.<ref name=\"2002points\" />\n\nMichael Schumacher was strongly considered by the British press,<ref name=STPreview>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85477733/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=ef4faa46|title=Cool Schumacher on cruise control; Motor racing|last=Rae|first=Richard|date=5 May 2002|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=14 September 2019|page=22|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> bookmakers,<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Jamie|title=Odds Fellow: Back Ralf to win this battle of the Schumachers|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85874123/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=04cc6d11|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|page=13|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref> and former drivers [[Gerhard Berger]] and [[Niki Lauda]] the favourite to win the Austrian Grand Prix, an event he had not won in four previous attempts.<ref name=STPreview/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7224/.html|title=Schumacher Will Win in Austria, Says Berger|date=2 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=14 September 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211035738/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7224/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> He said of his chances in Austria, \"We believe we have a very competitive package overall but it's a question of how good the others can be\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/amp/163824/|title=Schumacher looks forward to Austria GP|last=Shortt|first=James|date=4 May 2002|access-date=14 September 2019|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]}}</ref> He expressed confidence he could challenge for victory saying, \"I certainly won't be approaching this race any differently than the others. And with two almost perfect races behind us, I'm obviously looking forward to the Austrian Grand Prix with a lot of confidence.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85577199/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4380caee|title=Motorsport: Schu hopes to end Austrian jinx; Formula One|last=Gordon|first=Ian|date=9 May 2002|work=[[The News Letter]]|access-date=14 September 2019|page=51|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Montoya stated he would be better able to challenge Ferrari at the A1-Ring recalling, \"We showed strongly there last year even though Ralf and I failed to score a single point due to technical problems when we were both running in good positions. I am pretty confident that in Austria we will be quite strong, certainly stronger than in [the prior race in] [[2002 Spanish Grand Prix|Barcelona]], so I am looking forward to it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autoweek.com/article/car-news/williams-bmw-aims-close-gap-ferrari-austrian-grand-prix|title=Williams-BMW aims to close gap on Ferrari at Austrian Grand Prix|date=9 May 2002|website=[[Autoweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn technical developments, Sauber introduced a revised evolution of its Ferrari 050 engine that the team had used in the first five races of the 2002 championship. The team installed a new aerodynamic package that included a revised undertray, front wing and altered bodywork around the cover of the [[Sauber C21|C21]]'s engine. The Ferrari, McLaren and Williams teams brought new [[Intake|air intakes]] installed to the front brakes. Williams also used an upgraded front wing specification for its [[Williams FW24|FW24]], which was characterised by a curved profile <ref name=\"Piola\">{{cite journal|last=Piola|first=Giorgio|date=May 2002|title=Sauber un pieno di novit\u00e0|url=|journal=Autosprint|language=Italian|volume=1420|issue=20|pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n==Practice==\nFour practice sessions were held before the Sunday race, two each on Friday and Saturday. The Friday morning and afternoon sessions each lasted an hour; the third and fourth sessions, on Saturday morning, lasted 45 minutes each.<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jomenvisst.de/fia/2002SportingRegulations/2002_F1_Sporting_Regulations.pdf|title=2002 Formula One Sporting Regulations|date=31 October 2001|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|pages=12\u201314|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017221540/http://www.jomenvisst.de/fia/2002SportingRegulations/2002_F1_Sporting_Regulations.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2014|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> The first practice session was held in cool and overcast weather. Michael Schumacher was fastest with a lap of 1 minute and 11.072 seconds with approximately ten minutes remaining. His teammate Barrichello, [[Felipe Massa]] and [[Nick Heidfeld]] of Sauber, [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] drivers [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] and [[Takuma Sato]], Coulthard, [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]' [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]], and the [[British American Racing]] (BAR) duo of [[Jacques Villeneuve]] and [[Olivier Panis]], were second through tenth.<ref name=AF1FP1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/userlogin?r=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7268/.html|title=Friday First Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Some drivers\u2014including Barrichello, Massa and Fisichella\u2014ran off the dusty, slippery track into a [[Run-off area|gravel trap]] during the session because of a low amount of [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]]; none sustained damage to their vehicles.<ref name=AF1FP1/><ref name=FIAFriday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news1.htm|title=Bulletin No 1 \u2013 Free Practice Session|date=10 May 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020616070255/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news1.htm|archive-date=16 June 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nConditions became warmer and sunnier for the second practice session though rainfall threatened towards the end.<ref name=F1NetFP1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35001|title=Barrichello leads Ferrari whitewash|date=10 May 2002|publisher=F1Racing.net|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041123045910/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35001|archive-date=30 September 2004|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> The fastest times to be recorded within the first 20 minutes since the track temperature was at its warmest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18909|title=Practice 2: Barrichello heads Schuey|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/rHoil|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Barrichello set the day's fastest lap, at 1-minute and 10.549 seconds. His teammate Michael Schumacher was three-hundredths of a second slower in second position. Montoya, [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]] of the McLaren team, [[Allan McNish]] for [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]], Arrows driver [[Enrique Bernoldi]], [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]'s [[Pedro de la Rosa]], Panis, Coulthard and Sato were third to tenth.<ref name=AF1FP2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/userlogin?r=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7270/.html|title=Friday Second Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Some drivers, including Michael and Ralf Schumacher, and McNish, again lost control of their cars and ran off to the side of the track during the session.<ref name=F1NetFP1/><ref name=AF1FP2/> Heidfeld's track time was curtailed after 20 minutes due to an [[Alternator (automotive)|alternator]] fault.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9404.html|title=Practice report: Barrichello leads on Friday|date=10 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021003055037/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9404.html|archive-date=3 October 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Frentzen lost a quarter of an hour to familiarise himself with the track after he spun over a [[Curb|kerb]] and damaged his car's undertray.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nThe third practice session took place in clear and dry weather; no drivers ventured off the less slippery circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9418.html|title=Practice report: Ferrari dominant early on Saturday|date=11 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020810030231/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9418.html|archive-date=10 August 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher used low track and ambient temperatures to become the first driver to go below 70 seconds all weekend with a lap of 1 minute and 9.001 seconds that he recorded half an hour in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18927|title=Practice 3: Schuey's stunning pace|date=11 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/olhvu|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=DF1FP3>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/news/news.php?id=1126|title=Schumacher blitzes third free|last=Raman|first=Nick|date=11 May 2002|publisher=Daily F1|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101015821/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/news/news.php?id=1126|archive-date=1 November 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> His teammate Barrichello was second-fastest and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen third. Frentzen, Massa, Coulthard, Heidfeld, Panis, Button and Bernoldi followed in positions four through ten.<ref name=DF1FP3/>\n\nThe ambient and track temperatures had increased by the start of the fourth practice session.<ref name=F1NetFP4>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35045|title=Ferrari dominate but Williams close in|date=11 May 2002|publisher=F1Racing.net|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041123045934/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35045|archive-date=23 November 2004|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Several competitors made driver errors that sent them into a gravel trap.<ref name=AutosportFP4>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18928|title=Practice 4: No stopping Schumacher|date=11 May 2002|website=Autosport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HmnP8|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher set the track record, with a lap of 1 minute and 8.433 seconds. Barrichello was second, and Ralf Schumacher improved to third. Montoya, Frentzen, Massa, Heidfeld, R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen, Panis and Villeneuve completed the top ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7294/.html|title=Saturday Second Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=11 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050201004749/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7294/.html|archive-date=1 February 2005|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Bernoldi missed 25 minutes due to a malfunctioning gearbox. He later lost control of the rear of his car at turn two and beached in a gravel trap before the session ended.<ref name=F1NetFP4/><ref name=AutosportFP4/>\n\n==Qualifying==\n[[File:Barrichello_2002.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Rubens Barrichello in a red racing suit | [[Rubens Barrichello]] took his second [[pole position]] of the 2002 season and the fifth of his career]]\n\nSaturday's afternoon one-hour qualifying session saw each competitor limited to twelve laps, with the starting order decided by their fastest laps. The [[107% rule]] was in effect during this session, requiring each driver set a time within 107 per cent of the quickest lap to qualify for the race.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Conditions were clear with warm air and track temperatures.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news2.htm|title=Bulletin No 2 \u2013 Free Practice and Qualifying|date=11 May 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020817101112/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news2.htm|archivedate=16 June 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DTQuali\" /> Barrichello took his second [[pole position]] of the season and the fifth of his career with a lap of 1 minute and 8.082 seconds.<ref name=\"UPIPole\">{{cite news|title=Barrichello on pole for Grand Prix|url=https://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/05/11/Barrichello-on-pole-for-Grand-Prix/83391021140456/?st_rec=4929582004800&ur3=1|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was joined on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row by Ralf Schumacher, who took his best starting position of the year.<ref name=\"UPIPole\" /> Michael Schumacher was third; he said he lost speed due to a brake problem, and that traffic baulked him.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\">{{cite web|title=Team and Driver comments \u2013 Saturday|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/2002season/results/06/quotes-sat.phtml|publisher=Daily F1|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615112230/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/2002season/results/06/quotes-sat.phtml|archivedate=15 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> He switched to the spare Ferrari for his final timed lap in an unsuccessful attempt to claim pole position,<ref name=\"AutosportQuali\">{{cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18932|title=Qualifying: Rubens takes pole|date=11 May 2002|work=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/gISII|archive-date=15 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DTQuali\">{{cite news|title=Brazilian halts procession|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3027580/Brazilian-halts-procession.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508124126/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3027580/Brazilian-halts-procession.html|archive-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> and did not earn a front-row start for the first time since the [[2001 Italian Grand Prix]] eight races earlier.<ref name=\"ObserverQuali\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/12/formulaone.theobserver|title=Barrichello charge puts rivals on red alert|last=Hamilton|first=Maurice|date=12 May 2002|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007220211/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/12/formulaone.theobserver|archive-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> A misfiring engine prompted Montoya in fourth to switch to the spare car [[Racing setup|setup]] for his teammate Ralf Schumacher; he made a minor tyre-pressure adjustment to record his fastest lap.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> Heidfeld took fifth, claiming he could have improved had Button not slowed his final timed lap. A lack of speed restricted the McLaren duo of R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Coulthard to sixth and eighth; they were separated by Massa who made two driver errors in an unbalanced car through high-speed turns. Panis set the ninth-fastest time as de la Rosa slowed his final timed lap. Toyota's [[Mika Salo]] in tenth had a minor [[Understeer and oversteer|understeer]].<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" />\n\nFrentzen in 11th spun on oil and removed some bodywork components from his car in a gravel trap. His vehicle was later repaired to continue driving.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AutosportQuali\" /> His Arrows' teammate Bernoldi followed in 12th and expressed satisfaction with his car's balance.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" /> Traffic slowed Button on his four timed laps and left him 13th.<ref name=\"SundayTimesQuali\">{{cite news|last=Rae|first=Richard|title=Cap that, partner; Motor racing|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85906722/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=b47018b2|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|page=18|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription|url-status=dead}}</ref> McNish and Toyota located a car setup tailored to suit him, and took 14th.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" /> Fisichella ran a new engine in qualifying and took 15th with a car setup suited for used front and new rear tyres.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> [[Jarno Trulli]] had a major engine failure through turn nine and lost control of his Renault on the leaked oil from the engine failure.<ref name=\"AutosportQuali\" /> The session was stopped for 11 minutes for [[Motorsport marshal|track marshals]] to dry it.<ref name=\"ObserverQuali\" /> Trulli returned to his garage and used the spare Renault setup for his teammate Button and took 16th after minor braking problems. Villeneuve used a new set of tyres for qualifying; he was uncomfortable with his car's setup and was 17th. A handling imbalance created an unbalanced car for Sato in 18th. Jaguar's de la Rosa and [[Eddie Irvine]] filled the grid's tenth row: de la Rosa had a rear suspension fault caused by an [[Exhaust system|exhaust]] overheating it and Irvine removed his front wing in a collision with the rear of Bernoldi's vehicle into turn one. [[Minardi]] drivers [[Mark Webber]] and [[Alex Yoong]] started from the eleventh row: Webber optimised his [[Minardi PS02|PS02]]'s balance so it ran without any issues on its tyres during the session, and intermittent rear brake locking destabilised Yoong's car causing him to spin after he exited the pit lane.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" />\n\n===Qualifying classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable  sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver \n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor \n! scope=\"col\" | Lap \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Gap|Gap to the fastest driver in seconds}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:08.082\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:08.364\n| +0.282\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:08.704\n| +0.622\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:09.118\n| +1.036\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:09.129\n| +1.047\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 1:09.154\n| +1.072\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Felipe Massa]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:09.228\n| +1.146\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 1:09.335\n| +1.253\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Olivier Panis]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:09.561\n| +1.479\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 24\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n| [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 1:09.661\n| +1.579\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 20\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:09.671\n| +1.589\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 21\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Enrique Bernoldi]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:09.723\n| +1.641\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| 15\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n| [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 1:09.780\n| +1.698\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| 25\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Allan McNish]]\n| [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 1:09.818\n| +1.736\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:09.901\n| +1.819\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| 14\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n| [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 1:09.980\n| +1.898\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| 11\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:10.051\n| +1.969\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Takuma Sato]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:10.058\n| +1.976\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 17\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:10.553\n| +2.471\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:10.741\n| +2.659\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| 23\n| {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Mark Webber]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 1:11.388\n| +3.306\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22\n| 22\n| {{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[Alex Yoong]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 1:12.336\n| +4.254\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |[[107% rule]]: 1:12.848\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"|{{center|Sources:<ref name=DTQuali/><ref>{{cite web|title=Austria 2002: Qualifications|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/qualification.aspx|publisher=Stats F1|accessdate=18 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717225750/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/qualification.aspx|archive-date=17 July 2017}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nA half hour warm-up session took place on Sunday morning,<ref name=\"regulations\" /> in clear and warm weather conditions. All drivers fine-tuned their race setups for the weather and drove their spare cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news3.htm|title=Bulletin No 3 \u2013 Warm-Up|date=1 November 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101093606/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news3.htm|archive-date=1 November 2002|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> Barrichello had the fastest lap of 1 minute and 10.876 seconds and his teammate Michael Schumacher was second. Massa, Frentzen, Heidfeld, Bernoldi, Coulthard, Villeneuve, R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Irvine completed the top ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7316/.html|title=Sunday Warm Up \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040028/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7316/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> While the session saw no major incidents, Ralf Schumacher entered the gravel traps at the two of the track's corners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18949|title=Warm-up: Ferrari still on top|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HJp9R|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the warm-up session, Montoya predicted several drivers would run wide on a [[rumble strip]] located to the outside of the circuit, which extended from turn one to the first portion of the [[Straight (racing)|straight]] driving towards turn two, to increase the top speed of their cars.{{refn|group=N|name=\"WhitingSatMeeting\"|[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] race director [[Charlie Whiting]] told drivers in a meeting on Saturday afternoon they would be permitted to use the [[rumble strip]] to the outside of turn one.<ref name=MontoyaPreRace/>}}<ref name=MontoyaPreRace>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7317/.html|title=Montoya Predicts Eventful First Corner|date=12 May 2002|website=Atlas F1|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=18 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040032/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7317/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005}}</ref> [[Ron Dennis]], the team principal of McLaren, argued Ferrari should allow their drivers to race each other without the imposition of [[team orders]] favouring one driver over the other as had happened in the [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix|2001 race]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Let the Ferraris race, says Dennis|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18955|work=[[Autosport]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|archive-url=https://archive.is/EGnZd|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\nThe race began at 14:00 local time;<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /> the weather was clear and dry. The air temperature was {{Convert|20|C|F|abbr=}} and the track temperature ranged from {{Convert|27|to|29|C|comma=}}.<ref name=F1NetRace>{{cite web|title=Cynical Ferrari rob Rubens of victory|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35091|publisher=F1Racing.net|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040930004806/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35091|archivedate=30 September 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=F1COMRace>{{cite web|title=2002: Round 6: Austria: A1-Ring|url=http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews02/austria/race.html|publisher=[[Formula1.com]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809230856/http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews02/austria/race.html|archivedate=9 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> Barrichello made a brisk start to maintain the lead into the first turn.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\">{{cite web|title=Lap by lap: Austrian GP|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1982854.stm|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021213619/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1982854.stm|archivedate=21 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> While he provided room for drivers to pass him, none did.<ref name=\"DF1Review\">{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Chris|last2=Raman|first2=Nick|title=Ferrari's farcical finish|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/features/feature.php?id=35|publisher=Daily F1|date=May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021017113858/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/features/feature.php?id=35|archivedate=17 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> Behind Barrichello, his teammate Michael Schumacher made a fast start to slot into second position and Heidfeld rose from fifth to third having overtaken Ralf Schumacher on the outside.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\">{{cite web|title=Bulletin N\u00b04 \u2013 Race Facts and Incidents|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news4.htm|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020817091625/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news4.htm|archivedate=17 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Massa, meanwhile, drew alongside and Massa steered onto the grass<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> dropping to tenth. Further back, Bernoldi made contact with the rear of his teammate Frentzen;<ref name=\"Auto1Race\">{{cite web|last=Cipolloni|first=Mark|title=Disgrace in Austria as Barrichello hands win to Schuey|url=http://autoracing1.com/htmfiles/2002/F1/0512AustriaRace.asp|publisher=AutoRacing1|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018090142/http://autoracing1.com/htmfiles/2002/F1/0512AustriaRace.asp|archivedate=18 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> both cars continued as Bernoldi entered the pit lane after the first lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> At turn two, an increase in speed led de la Rosa's [[throttle]] pick-up to start to cut out.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> He slowed, and retired in the pit lane at the end of the lap. In the meantime, Villeneuve experienced a minor loss of car control and hit Frentzen's car on the inside.<ref name=\"CrashRace\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/f1/racereports_others.asp?feature_id=1809&language_id=1&championship_id=1|title=Austrian GP 2002 \u2013 Rubens robbed|date=12 May 2002|publisher=Crash|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805093156/http://www.crash.net/f1/racereports_others.asp?feature_id=1809&language_id=1&championship_id=1|archivedate=5 August 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> The collision sent Frentzen into a gravel trap from which he slowly extricated himself.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"CrashRace\" />\n\n[[File:Juan Pablo Montoya (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Juan Pablo Montoya dressed in white looking to his left | [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] ''(pictured at the [[United States Grand Prix]] later in 2002)'' finished in third position]]\n\nAt the end of the first lap, Barrichello led his teammate Michael Schumacher, Heidfeld, Ralf Schumacher, Montoya and Coulthard.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Heidfeld ran wide at Castrol Kurve at the beginning of the second lap and the Williams pair of Ralf Schumacher and Montoya demoted him to fifth.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> Barrichello and Michael Schumacher began to pull away from the rest of the field.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> There were overtakes further down the field. On lap two, Salo passed Button for eighth position.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Villeneuve overtook his teammate Panis for 14th position and Frentzen passed Webber on lap three.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> During the next lap Yoong lost two places to his teammate Webber, and Frentzen.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Bernoldi retired from the race with a broken front wing and front brake pipe.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen in seventh retired at the side of the track with an engine failure on lap six.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\">{{cite web|title=Team orders rob Barrichello of Austrian GP win|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/team-orders-rob-barrichello-of-austrian-gp-win/92031/|publisher=[[motorsport.com]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On lap seven Villeneuve passed McNish for tenth place, then lost it as he ran wide. He made a second, successful attempt on the eighth lap, passing McNish who opted against a challenge.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nThat same lap, Massa entered the pit lane to join the list of retirees with a failed left-rear [[Car suspension|suspension]] bracket; it failed in turn two, causing the Sauber C21's right-front wheel to lift from the tarmac surface and its undertray to scrape along it. Villeneuve made a pass on Fisichella for ninth place on lap ten.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Not long after Villeneuve overtook Button for eighth position. By the same lap, Barrichello led by a second over his teammate Michael Schumacher, who in turn was 17 seconds ahead of Ralf Schumacher. Further down the order, Frentzen put a rear wheel on the grass at the final corner on lap 16. He lost control of his car, spun through 180 degrees and rolled backwards in front of the race leaders. Frentzen fell to 18th position, behind the Minardi cars of Webber and Yoong. He passed Yoong to return to 17th position on the 18th lap.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> One lap later, Villeneuve overtook Salo on the inside for seventh place and blocked his attempted counter-move.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" />\n\nAs the Ferraris extended their lead over Ralf Schumacher, the stewards informed the BAR team on the 23rd lap that Villeneuve had incurred a [[Formula One regulations#Penalties|drive-through penalty]] as they deemed him at fault for the collision with Frentzen on lap one.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Lap 24 saw the [[safety car]]'s first deployment: Panis' engine failed without warning on the start/finish straight.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> His rear wheels locked, spun to the centre of the track and avoided colliding with a barrier.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /><ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Track marshals removed Panis' car from the circuit as he returned to the pit lane.<ref name=\"IHTRace\">{{cite news|last=Spurgeon|first=Brad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/14/sports/IHT-formula-one-barrichello-ushers-schumacher-to-first.html|title=Formula One : Barrichello ushers Schumacher to first|date=14 May 2002|newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]]|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409063533/https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/14/sports/IHT-formula-one-barrichello-ushers-schumacher-to-first.html|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Ferrari and Williams' teams employed different pit stop strategies\u2014the Ferrari team planned for  two stops whereas the Williams team planned one.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> The Ferrari team called Barrichello and Michael Schumacher into the pit lane for their first [[pit stop]]s; Schumacher drove more slowly than Barrichello to allow their mechanics to service the latter's car first. Barrichello retained the lead as Michael Schumacher yielded second to Ralf Schumacher. The safety car was withdrawn at the conclusion of the 27th lap and Barrichello led at the restart.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" />\n\n[[File:Takuma Sato.jpg|left|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Takuma Saot seated behind a table with a pen in hand | [[Takuma Sato]] ''(pictured in 2002)'' was involved in a heavy accident that caused soft-tissue damage to his right thigh]]\n\nSoon after, a major accident prompted the safety car's second deployment on lap 28.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\">{{cite web|last=Mauk|first=Eric|title=Ferrari Orders Barrichello To Give Up Austrian Win To Schumacher|url=http://speedtv.com/auto/?lvl=3a&cat=17&id=1440|publisher=[[Speed (TV network)|Speed]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020607115755/http://speedtv.com/auto/?lvl=3a&cat=17&id=1440|archivedate=7 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> As the field entered turn two,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Heidfeld noticed smoke coming from Yoong's Minardi and applied his cold brakes heavily. This locked the Sauber's rear wheels and sent him out of control about {{Convert|100|yd|m|abbr=on}} from the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#A|apex]].<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> He veered into the grass as his car spun 180 degrees;<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> the grass did not slow him,<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> and he was launched over the crest of a hill.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Montoya on the inside was about to lap Sato's slower car at turn two, with the latter ahead of him at the turn's apex.<ref name=\"SatoCrash\">{{cite web|title=Do you remember... Sato's 'miracle' escape in Austria|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2015/6/do-you-remember----satos-miracle-escape-in-austria.html|publisher=Formula One|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421021549/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2015/6/do-you-remember----satos-miracle-escape-in-austria.html|archive-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> At high speed,<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> Heidfeld narrowly avoided a collision with Montoya's front wing,<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> and the rear of his Sauber sustained a [[side collision]] against the right-hand sidepod of Sato's car,<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"DawnRace\">{{cite news|title=Schumacher ends jinx in controversial finish|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/33649/schumacher-ends-jinx-in-controversial-finish|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916091632/https://www.dawn.com/news/33649/schumacher-ends-jinx-in-controversial-finish|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> causing heavy damage to both vehicles and littering carbon fibre and titanium debris on a wide area of track.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Heidfeld's rear structure and titanium gearbox punctured a hole in Sato's car; his knees struck the steering column breaking it in half.<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/feature/42267/1/taku-grateful-for-safety-advances|title=Taku grateful for safety advances|date=23 May 2002|publisher=Crash|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062412/https://www.crash.net/f1/feature/42267/1/taku-grateful-for-safety-advances|archive-date=9 April 2020|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> Both drivers were sent into a gravel trap and came to a stop there.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nA visibly shaken Heidfeld was extricated from his car by track marshals with a heavily bruised left leg.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> Sato remained in his car with soft-tissue damage to his right thigh<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> but did not lose consciousness;<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" /> a section of the Sauber's rear crash structure penetrated the side of the Jordan's monocoque just below Sato's right knee and his [[Racing helmet|helmet]] was squeezed between the car's [[head restraint]], both of which prevented him from leaving his car.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" /> The [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA, Formula One's governing body) safety and medical delegate [[Sid Watkins]] and his team took ten minutes to remove Sato from the car and treated him at the crash site before transporting him by ambulance to the track's medical centre.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> From there,<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Sato and Heidfeld were flown by helicopter to [[Medical University of Graz|Graz University Hospital]],<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> for overnight observation and precautionary x-ray scans.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Under safety car conditions, every team except for Ferrari and Williams brought their drivers to the pit lane for additional fuel and a set of tyres.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> After 20 minutes,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> the race restarted at the end of the 36th lap when the safety car entered the pit lane. Barrichello led Ralf Schumacher, Michael Schumacher, Montoya, Coulthard and Fisichella. On lap 37, Webber passed his teammate Yoong for 13th position.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nVilleneuve passed Fisichella for sixth place at the start of the 38th lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> On the same lap, Irvine entered the pit lane to retire with a hydraulics failure.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Two laps later, Villeneuve caught and overtook Coulthard at turn one for fifth position.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Coulthard lost sixth place to Fisichella after he drove on oil and off the circuit on the 45th lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> On the same lap Trulli pulled over at the end of the pit lane wall on the start/finish straight to retire from with a loss of [[Pressure regulator|fuel pressure]].<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Yoong retired with fire visible from the rear of his Minardi not long after.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Green flag pit stops began on lap 47. Ralf Schumacher made a pit stop and dropped to fifth position. His teammate Montoya remained on the track for another four laps and used more fuel in an attempt to overtake Ralf Schumacher.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Montoya entered the pit lane for tyres on the 51st lap.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> He returned to the race in fourth position, ahead of his teammate Ralf Schumacher.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Villeneuve was elevated to third position until a pit stop on lap 53 demoted him to ninth. Montoya and Ralf Schumacher returned to third and fourth positions respectively.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\n[[File:2002 Austrian GP.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph showing Rubens Barrichello making way to allow Michael Schumacher to cross the finish line ahead of him | Ferrari invoked [[team orders]] to allow [[Michael Schumacher]] past his teammate Rubens Barrichello to win the race and earn the maximum number of points towards the World Drivers' Championship.]]\n\nBarrichello entered the pit lane for the second time on the 61st lap. His fuel stop took 6.2 seconds and he exited in second place. His teammate Michael Schumacher led lap 62 and made his second pit stop at the end of the lap. He returned to the race in second position; Barrichello returned to first.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> On the 63rd lap,<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Ferrari team principal [[Jean Todt]] invoked team orders on Barrichello to relinquish the victory to his teammate Michael Schumacher.<ref name=\"LaStampaTodt\">{{cite news|last=Mancini|first=Stefano|title=Todt: \"Ferrari tradita dai nervi Sembrava impossibile perdere\"|url=https://www.lastampa.it/sport/motori/2010/11/18/news/todt-ferrari-tradita-dai-nervi-br-sembrava-impossibile-perdere-1.36992867|newspaper=[[La Stampa]]|language=Italian|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916182037/https://www.lastampa.it/sport/motori/2010/11/18/news/todt-ferrari-tradita-dai-nervi-br-sembrava-impossibile-perdere-1.36992867|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=N|name=\"TeamOrders\"|It was the second year in succession that Barrichello had been asked to relinquish a position to his teammate Michael Schumacher on the start/finish straight on the last lap, as he had done so for second position in the [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix|2001 race]].<ref name=\"DawnRace\" />}} This would improve Schumacher's position in the World Drivers' Championship with a win earning him ten points. Ferrari advised Barrichello they would terminate his contract if he failed to do so.<ref name=\"TerraBAR\">{{cite news|title=Rubinho diz que foi amea\u00e7ado para dar posi\u00e7\u00e3o a Schumacher em 2002|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/motor/formula-1/noticia/2012/05/rubinho-diz-que-foi-ameacado-para-dar-posicao-schumacher-em-2002.html|publisher=[[Rede Globo]]|language=Portuguese|date=9 May 2012|accessdate=16 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512021344/http://globoesporte.globo.com/motor/formula-1/noticia/2012/05/rubinho-diz-que-foi-ameacado-para-dar-posicao-schumacher-em-2002.html|archivedate=12 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Barrichello reminded Todt over the radio of a promise he made not to relinquish a victory to a driver. This prompted Todt to reply to Barrichello that he was required to obey his instruction to preserve Ferrari's \"best interests\".<ref name=\"TODisobey\">{{cite web|title=Barrichello Reveals He Queried Team Orders in Austria|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jun/report.php/id/7677/.html|work=Atlas F1|date=20 June 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041221112526/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jun/report.php/id/7677/.html|archive-date=21 December 2004}}</ref> Personnel on the Ferrari pit gantry observed the television screens and noticed Michael Schumacher could not get close enough to pass Barrichello in the final seven laps.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" />\n\nAt the start of the final lap, Barrichello led his teammate Michael Schumacher by one second.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> As Barrichello entered the final corner,<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> Ferrari technical director [[Ross Brawn]] informed Michael Schumacher over the radio his teammate would yield to him.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> When Barrichello braked in the final {{Convert|100|to|50|yd|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Michael Schumacher slowed more than his teammate because he had hoped that no team orders would be applied as Barrichello did the same to comply with Ferrari's instruction.<ref name=\"IERace\">{{cite news|last=Quigley|first=Declan|title=Hollow win for Schumacher as Sato makes 'miracle' escape|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hollow-win-for-schumacher-as-sato-makes-miracle-escape-26047923.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=13 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916083321/https://www.independent.ie/sport/hollow-win-for-schumacher-as-sato-makes-miracle-escape-26047923.html|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> Schumacher passed Barrichello for his first victory in Austria, his fourth in a row in 2002, and the 58th of his career in a time of 1 hour, 33 minutes and 51.562 seconds at an average speed of {{Convert|196.334|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> Barrichello was 0.182 seconds behind in second position with Montoya 17.7 seconds adrift in third. Montoya's teammate Ralf Schumacher finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Fisichella was fifth and took the first two points of the season for the Jordan team. Coulthard took the final point in sixth position, ahead of Button's Renault and the Toyota cars of Salo and McNish.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> A loss of hydraulic pressure caused Villeneuve's engine to fail on the final lap; he was classified tenth.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Frentzen and Webber for the Arrows and Minardi teams were the final finishers, albeit two laps behind the race winner.<ref name=\"DawnRace\" />\n\n==Post-race==\nThe Ferrari team were booed, jeered, whistled at and given a thumbs down signal by the crowd in ''[[parc ferm\u00e9]]'' and on the podium.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Michael Schumacher insisted Barrichello to mount the first position on the podium, as \"[[Deutschlandlied]]\" was played.<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Schumacher then stood next to his teammate during the composition of [[Il Canto degli Italiani]] <ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> When [[Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel]], the [[Chancellor of Austria]], presented the winner's trophy to Schumacher, the latter gave it to Barrichello.<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Later, in the press conference, where loud boos were heard,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Barrichello said of the situation, \"I'm going through a period of a very good time of my life. I'm becoming a better person, a better driver, so there's no point in arguing. I think my determination will bring me a lot more wins, so that's the way I see it, so there's no point arguing.\"<ref name=PressConf>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7334/.html|title=Post-Race Press Conference \u2013 Austrian GP|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064312/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7334/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher said he understood Ferrari's decision, \"the team is investing a lot of money for one sort of target and imagine in the end it wouldn't be enough by this amount of points, how stupid would we look?\"<ref name=PressConf/> Montoya said the two safety car periods allowed him to pass his teammate Ralf Schumacher, \"Ralf was quite quick out of the pits as well, but I managed to get a few laps in really quick right before the stop and that was enough.\"<ref name=PressConf/>\n\nSato and Heidfeld were deemed fit to compete at the next race of the season, the [[2002 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]] two weeks later, after they passed fitness tests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/19098|title=Sato and Heidfeld pass fitness tests|date=22 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/SPLU3|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Sid Watkins told [[Eddie Jordan]], the owner of the Jordan team, that Sato had \"a miraculous escape\", leading Jordan to remark, \"Somebody up there likes him\".<ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> Sato said he had not observed Heidfeld approaching him, \"When I opened my eyes I could see my legs were squashed by the damaged monocoque and I could see the ground through the hole. Although there was some pain, I knew nothing was broken. The car did a great job of saving me \u2013 I hear there was nothing left of it.\"<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> Heidfeld admitted he was at fault for causing the crash, \"I saw a cloud of tyre smoke as [Alex] Yoong braked really hard and early ahead of us, and maybe I pressed the pedal too hard as a result while the brakes were still cool. The car got away from me and next thing I knew I was going backwards down the grass.\"<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> That the injuries Sato sustained in the accident were minor was cited as a consequence of improved safety standards undertaken by the FIA, racing teams and medical experts since the 1970s.<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" />\n\nRalf Schumacher praised his car for allowing him to finish fourth, \"Due to the action packed race and the different strategies it is difficult to say how big Ferrari's advantage really was here on the A1-Ring. We have to continue to work hard, this much is clear.\"<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Fisichella commented on his fifth-place finish, \"It's been a very, very good day for me, as I didn't expect to score points. But, the most important thing is that Takuma is alright. It felt fantastic when I crossed the line and I would like to say thank you to the team, especially because we made the right pit stop decision.\"<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> The race result increased Michael Schumacher's lead in the Drivers' Championship to 27 points over Montoya in second place. Ralf Schumacher was third with 23 points. Barrichello moved past Coulthard for fourth with 12 points.<ref name=\"2002points\" /> In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari further extended their advantage over the Williams team to 16 points. McLaren maintained third position with 14 points. The Renault and Sauber teams continued to hold fourth and fifth places with eleven races left in the season.<ref name=\"2002points\" />\n\n===Team orders===\nThe Ferrari team's use of team orders to determine the finishing order overshadowed the race.<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> ''[[Reuters]]'' cited it as the most \"particularly blatant\" application of team orders applied to favour one driver over another since Coulthard relinquished first position to his McLaren teammate [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] in the final laps of the [[1998 Australian Grand Prix]] to comply with a prior agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7356/.html|title=Analysis: Team Orders Go Back a Long Way in F1|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|date=13 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=17 September 2019|agency=Reuters|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040151/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7356/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nFerrari were heavily condemned by fans on the internet,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18981|title=Autosport.com readers 'anti' Ferrari|date=13 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/tT1Qw|archive-date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns06280.html|title=The flood continues...|date=15 May 2002|publisher=GrandPrix.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020611070646/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns06280.html|archive-date=11 June 2002|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> some members of the Formula One community,<ref name=\"GuardianRace\">{{cite news|last=Henry|first=Alan|authorlink=Alan Henry|title=Fury over stitch-up for Schumacher victory; Barrichello is told to hand over the lead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/13/formulaone.formulaone2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909140321/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/13/formulaone.formulaone2002|archive-date=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=TheAgePress>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/14/1021002446562.html|title=Brazilians cry foul over Ferrari tactics|date=15 May 2002|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021022111326/http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/14/1021002446562.html|archive-date=22 October 2002}}</ref> the world's press, and [[President of Brazil|President]] [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]] of Brazil.{{refn|group=N|name=\"BetsOff\"|An Italian online betting company and the Swedish public lottery [[Svenska Spel]] paid out those who bet on Barrichello to win the Grand Prix.<ref name=TheAgePress/>}}<ref name=TheAgePress/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/13/1021002432326.html|title=Ferrari blasted worldwide for Grand Prix gaffe|date=14 May 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020815000322/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/13/1021002432326.html|archive-date=15 August 2002}}</ref> Some Formula One figures held different views, including the Williams pair of Montoya and Ralf Schumacher, and Irvine, who all stated their belief Michael Schumacher should not be apportioned blame for winning the Grand Prix via team orders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7370/.html|title=Montoya Defends Michael Schumacher|date=14 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064420/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7370/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/schumi-not-to-blame/|title='Schumi not to blame'|date=15 May 2002|website=[[Car (magazine)|Car Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062744/https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/schumi-not-to-blame/|archive-date=9 April 2020|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85940422/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=db2dcac5|title=Support for Schumacher|last=Gray|first=Will|date=15 May 2002|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=17 September 2019|page=03|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Jody Scheckter]], the [[1979 Formula One season|1979 world champion]] and Ron Dennis defended Ferrari's application of team orders as a means of enhancing Michael Schumacher's position in the championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9511.html|title=Dennis: don't ban team orders|date=19 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805231648/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9511.html|archive-date=5 August 2002|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/19009|title=Scheckter on Ferrari's side|date=16 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/3IqGN|archive-date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe day after the race, the FIA summoned Ferrari and its drivers to a meeting of the [[FIA World Motor Sport Council]] to be held in Paris on 26 June to explain why the team ordered Barrichello to yield the victory to Michael Schumacher and their actions on the podium.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/ferrari-schumi-barrichello-summoned-by-fia-511410|title=Ferrari, Schumi, Barrichello summoned by FIA|date=13 May 2002|work=[[Cape Argus]]|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062630/https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/ferrari-schumi-barrichello-summoned-by-fia-511410|archive-date=9 April 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> During a press conference on 24 May, FIA president [[Max Mosley]] stated Ferrari had not transgressed any regulations on team orders and the meeting would establish the appropriate punishment in the event a panel deemed if any rules were broken, \"There are rules about interfering with competition but we established a long time ago that team orders are allowed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7448/.html|title=Mosley: No Long-Term Damage to F1 after Austria|last=Young|first=Byron|date=24 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064656/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7448/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> That same day, Mosley revealed on behalf of the FIA he wrote a letter of apology to Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7450/.html|title=FIA Apologises to Austrian Chancellor|date=24 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=18 September 2019|agency=Reuters|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040504/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7450/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the meeting, the FIA deemed Ferrari to have transgressed series regulations when Michael Schumacher chose not to mount the first position on the podium and handed the trophy given to him by the Chancellor of Austria to his teammate Barrichello. The council also determined the team had not committed any violation when it invoked team orders on Barrichello to relinquish the victory to Michael Schumacher.<ref name=$1MilliionFineCNN/> It imposed a fine of $1 million on Ferrari, Michael Schumacher and Barrichello, half of which was paid immediately and divided into equal amounts between the trio; the remainder was suspended for one year on the condition a similar offence did not occur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A87880652/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=cf29ad9d|title=Ferrari happy to pay the price for Austria farce; Motor racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=27 June 2002|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=18 September 2019|page=40|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Neither a points deduction nor a race ban were imposed.<ref name=$1MilliionFineCNN>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/06/26/ferrari.fine/index.html|title=Ferrari and drivers fined $1m|date=26 June 2002|access-date=18 September 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018203630/http://www.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/06/26/ferrari.fine/index.html|archive-date=18 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response Mosley established a four-member working group to discuss team orders and invited the public to lend their opinion on the practice on the FIA's website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2067911.stm|title=F1 sets up team orders probe|date=26 June 2002|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040109090334/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2067911.stm|archive-date=9 January 2004|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> The FIA accepted feedback from 5 July to 1 September, which was passed on to the working group. They reviewed it and gave their recommendations to the governing body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jul/report.php/id/7853/.html|title=FIA Requests Public Suggestions on Team Orders|date=5 July 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211034449/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jul/report.php/id/7853/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> At a meeting of the 26-member Formula One Commission on 28 October, it was confirmed \"team orders that interfere with the race result\" would be barred from the [[2003 Formula One World Championship|2003 season]] onwards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683417190.html|title=Changes steer towards more open Formula One|date=30 October 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101213713/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683417190.html|archive-date=1 November 2002}}</ref> During the [[2010 German Grand Prix]] at the [[Hockenheimring]], Ferrari employed a \"coded message\"<ref name=\":0\" /> to invoke team orders to allow driver [[Fernando Alonso]] to pass Felipe Massa late on; Alonso went on to win the event. The parallels between how Michael Schumacher and Alonso won those races led the FIA to rescinding the regulation barring team orders in December 2010 because it was deemed difficult to enforce.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/9275796.stm|title=F1 chiefs drop the ban on team orders in new rules|date=10 December 2010|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-53494420101210|title=Team orders can come out of hiding now|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|date=10 December 2010|access-date=18 September 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nTodt admitted to ''[[La Stampa]]'' in December 2010 he should have avoided using team orders on Barrichello due to his subsequent belief Michael Schumacher would have won the championship without significant competition.<ref name=\"LaStampaTodt\" /> Brawn reiterated his colleague's opinion to British magazine ''[[Autosport]]'' seven years later and stated the negative consequences for Formula One outweighed the positives, calling it \"on reflection ... it was a mistake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gptoday.net/en/news/f1/221987/austria-gp-2002-decision-was-a-mistake-brawn|title=Austria GP 2002 decision was a mistake \u2013 Brawn|last=Walsh|first=Fergal|date=6 February 2017|publisher=GPToday.net|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918081155/https://www.gptoday.net/en/news/f1/221987/austria-gp-2002-decision-was-a-mistake-brawn|archive-date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Race classification===\nDrivers who finished in the top six points-scoring positions are denoted in '''bold''' and by a {{double dagger}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Laps|Laps completed}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Time/Retired\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Grid|Final grid position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 1\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Michael Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'''\n| 71\n| 1:33:51.562\n| 3\n|'''10{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 2\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} '''[[Rubens Barrichello]]'''\n|'''[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'''\n| 71\n|  +0.182\n| 1\n|'''6{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 6\n|{{flagicon|Colombia}} '''[[Juan Pablo Montoya]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 71\n|  +17.730\n| 4\n|'''4{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 5\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Ralf Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 71\n|  +18.448\n| 2\n|'''3{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 9\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} '''[[Giancarlo Fisichella]]'''\n|'''[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]'''\n| 71\n|  +49.965\n| 15\n|'''2{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 3\n|{{flagicon|UK}} '''[[David Coulthard]]'''\n|'''[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]'''\n| 71\n|  +50.672\n| 8\n|'''1{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 15\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n|[[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 71\n|  +51.229\n| 13\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 24\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n|[[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 71\n|  +1:09.425\n| 10\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 25\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Allan McNish]]\n|[[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 71\n|  +1:09.718\n| 14\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 11\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 70\n| Engine\n| 17\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 20\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 11\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 23\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Mark Webber]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 21\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 14\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n|[[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 44\n| Fuel pressure\n| 16\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 22\n|{{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[Alex Yoong]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 42\n| Engine\n| 22\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 16\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 38\n| Hydraulics\n| 20\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 7\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 27\n| Collision\n| 5\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 10\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Takuma Sato]]\n|[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 26\n| Collision\n| 18\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 12\n|{{flagicon|France}} [[Olivier Panis]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 22\n| Engine\n| 9\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 8\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Felipe Massa]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 7\n| Suspension\n| 7\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 4\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 5\n| Engine\n| 6\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 21\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Enrique Bernoldi]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 2\n| Collision\n| 12\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 17\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 0\n| Throttle\n| 19\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref name=GPCOMRace/>''}}}}\n|}\n\n==Championship standings after the race==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \u2013/+\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 54\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n| align=\"right\"| 27\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 23\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 1\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| align=\"right\"| 12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1downarrow red.svg|10px]] 1\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| align=\"right\"| 10\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"2002points\" /><ref name=\"champ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/championnat.aspx|title=Austria 2002 \u2013 Championship|publisher=Stats F1|access-date=8 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321144247/https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/championnat.aspx|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n;Constructors' Championship standings\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \u2013/+\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| align=\"right\"| 66\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| align=\"right\"| 50\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| align=\"right\"| 14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"2002points\" /><ref name=\"champ\"/>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n*<small>'''Note''': Only the top five positions are included for both sets of standings.</small>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Official 2002 Austrian Grand Prix results from [http://www.fia.com/archive/F1/2002/006.html FIA website] and [http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2002/10/ Formula1 website].\n* Formula One Database > 2002 Austrian Grand Prix \u2013 Qualifying [http://www.f1db.com/exec/section/grandprix/action/result/id/20020512#race_startgrid]\n\n{{Commons category|2002 Austrian Grand Prix}}\n\n{{F1 race report\n| Name_of_race            = [[Austrian Grand Prix]]\n| Year_of_race            = 2002\n| Previous_race_in_season = [[2002 Spanish Grand Prix]]\n| Next_race_in_season     = [[2002 Monaco Grand Prix]]\n| Previous_year's_race    = [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_year's_race        = [[2003 Austrian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n\n{{F1GP 00-09}}\n{{Portal bar|Austria|Formula One|Sports}}\n\n{{coord|47|13|11|N|14|45|53|E|source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2002 Formula One races|Austrian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:2002 in Austrian sport|Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:Austrian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:May 2002 sports events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix race report\n|Type          = F1\n|Country       = Austria\n|Grand Prix    = Austrian\n|Details ref   = <ref name=CF1Overview>{{cite web|title=2002 Austrian GP: XXXI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von Osterreich|url=http://www.chicanef1.dyndns.org/racetit.pl?year=2002&gp=Austrian%20GP|publisher=Chicane F1|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060717203039/http://www.chicanef1.dyndns.org/racetit.pl?year=2002&gp=Austrian%20GP|archivedate=14 July 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=GPCOMRace>{{cite web|title=Grand PrIx Results: Austrian GP, 2002|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr686.html|publisher=GrandPrix.com|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021012450/http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr686.html|archivedate=21 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|Date          = 12 May\n|Year          = 2002 \n|Image         = Circuit A1 Ring.svg\n|Official name = XXXI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von \u00d6sterreich<ref name=CF1Overview/>\n|Race_No       = 6\n|Season_No     = 17\n|Location      = [[Red Bull Ring|A1-Ring]], [[Spielberg, Austria|Spielberg]], [[Austria]]\n|Course        = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi     = 2.684\n|Course_km     = 4.326\n|Distance_laps = 71\n|Distance_mi   = 190.564\n|Distance_km   = 307.146\n|Weather       = Clear, Air Temp: 20\u00b0C\n|Attendance    = 81,000\n|Pole_Driver   = [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|Pole_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Pole_Time     = 1:08.082\n|Pole_Country  = Brazil\n|Fast_Driver   = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|Fast_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Fast_Time     = 1:09.298\n|Fast_Lap      = 68\n|Fast_Country  = Germany\n|First_Driver  = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|First_Team    = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|First_Country = Germany\n|Second_Driver = [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|Second_Team   = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Second_Country= Brazil\n|Third_Driver  = [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n|Third_Team    = [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n|Third_Country = Colombia\n|Lapchart      = {{F1Laps2002|AUT}}\n}}\nThe '''2002 Austrian Grand Prix''' (formally the '''XXVI Gro\u00dfer A1 Preis von \u00d6sterreich''') was a [[Formula One]] motor race held on 12 May 2002 at the [[Red Bull Ring|A1-Ring]] in [[Spielberg, Styria]]. It was the sixth round of the [[2002 Formula One World Championship]] and the 25th Austrian Grand Prix as part of the Formula One World Championship. [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] won the 71-lap race after starting from third position. His teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]] finished second, and [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] took third for the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team.\n\nBarrichello started the race from the [[pole position]] after recording the fastest lap in qualifying; Williams driver [[Ralf Schumacher]] started second, but was passed by Michael Schumacher in the first corner. Barrichello maintained the lead through most of the race until Ferrari invoked [[team orders]] on him to allow Michael Schumacher to win the race on the final lap and improve his standing in the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|World Drivers' Championship]]. It was his first Austrian Grand Prix victory, his fourth in a row in the 2002 season and the 58th of his career. The [[safety car]] was deployed twice during the race, which included a major accident on lap 28 involving [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] driver [[Takuma Sato]] and [[Nick Heidfeld]] of the [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]] team, who both sustained light injuries.\n\nAt the post-race podium ceremony Michael Schumacher implored Barrichello to mount the stand reserved for the race winner and gave his first-place trophy to his teammate. That led the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA; Formula One's governing body) to fine Ferrari, Michael Schumacher and Barrichello $1 million on 26 June; each paid a third immediately, while the remainder was suspended. Following a review, the FIA banned the practice of team orders beginning with the [[2003 Formula One World Championship|2003 season]]; they began again allowing the practice following the [[2010 Formula One World Championship|2010 championship]].\n\nThe win increased Michael Schumacher's lead in the World Drivers' Championship to 27 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]] over Montoya in second place. Ralf Schumacher came fourth to maintain third place, and Barrichello moved past [[David Coulthard]] of the [[McLaren]] team to fourth. In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|World Constructors' Championship]], Ferrari further extended their advantage over Williams to 16 points. McLaren were another 36 points behind in third as [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] and Sauber battled for fourth with eleven races remaining in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Red Bull Ring, April 18, 2018 SkySat.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph of the AI Ring, now called the Red Bull Ring, where the race was held | The [[Red Bull Ring|A1 Ring]], now called the Red Bull Ring ''(pictured in 2018)'', where the race was held.]]\n\nThe 2002 [[Austrian Grand Prix]] was the 6th of 17 motor races in the [[2002 Formula One World Championship]],<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /> and the 25th time it formed part of the championship.<ref name=CrashPreview>{{cite web|title=Preview \u2013 Austrian Grand Prix 2002|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/preview/42080/1/preview-austrian-grand-prix-2002|publisher=Crash|date=9 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The 71-lap race was held at the 9-turn {{Convert|4.326|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Red Bull Ring|A1 Ring]] in [[Spielberg, Styria]], on 12 May 2002.<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /><ref name=\"CrashPreview\" /> With very few sections requiring drivers competitors to slow down, the track gives teams an opportunity to push their engines to their full potential. 70 percent of the lap can be driven at full racing speed, although the circuit's relatively high altitude of {{Convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} offers less oxygen to feed the combustion engines, reducing their performance by approximately seven percent.<ref name=\"CrashPreview\" />\n\nHaving won four of the season's five previous races, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] led the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] with 44 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]. [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] and [[Ralf Schumacher]] of the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team were second and third with 23 and 20 points, respectively. Driving for [[McLaren]], [[David Coulthard]] stood in fourth position with nine points, and [[Jenson Button]] for [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]] was a further point behind in fifth place.<ref name=\"2002points\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/freepress/F1_guide_2002/Championship.html|title=Drivers' and Constructors' Provisional Standings|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021221123803/http://www.fia.com/freepress/F1_guide_2002/Championship.html|archivedate=21 December 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]], Ferrari led with 50 points, seven ahead of Williams in second place. McLaren with 13 points were third, with Renault and [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]] tied for fourth with eight points apiece.<ref name=\"2002points\" />\n\nMichael Schumacher was strongly considered by the British press,<ref name=STPreview>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85477733/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=ef4faa46|title=Cool Schumacher on cruise control; Motor racing|last=Rae|first=Richard|date=5 May 2002|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=14 September 2019|page=22|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> bookmakers,<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Jamie|title=Odds Fellow: Back Ralf to win this battle of the Schumachers|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85874123/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=04cc6d11|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|page=13|via=Gale General OneFile|url-access=subscription|url-status=live}}</ref> and former drivers [[Gerhard Berger]] and [[Niki Lauda]] the favourite to win the Austrian Grand Prix, an event he had not won in four previous attempts.<ref name=STPreview/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7224/.html|title=Schumacher Will Win in Austria, Says Berger|date=2 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=14 September 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211035738/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7224/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> He said of his chances in Austria, \"We believe we have a very competitive package overall but it's a question of how good the others can be\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/amp/163824/|title=Schumacher looks forward to Austria GP|last=Shortt|first=James|date=4 May 2002|access-date=14 September 2019|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]}}</ref> He expressed confidence he could challenge for victory saying, \"I certainly won't be approaching this race any differently than the others. And with two almost perfect races behind us, I'm obviously looking forward to the Austrian Grand Prix with a lot of confidence.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85577199/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4380caee|title=Motorsport: Schu hopes to end Austrian jinx; Formula One|last=Gordon|first=Ian|date=9 May 2002|work=[[The News Letter]]|access-date=14 September 2019|page=51|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Montoya stated he would be better able to challenge Ferrari at the A1-Ring recalling, \"We showed strongly there last year even though Ralf and I failed to score a single point due to technical problems when we were both running in good positions. I am pretty confident that in Austria we will be quite strong, certainly stronger than in [the prior race in] [[2002 Spanish Grand Prix|Barcelona]], so I am looking forward to it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autoweek.com/article/car-news/williams-bmw-aims-close-gap-ferrari-austrian-grand-prix|title=Williams-BMW aims to close gap on Ferrari at Austrian Grand Prix|date=9 May 2002|website=[[Autoweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn technical developments, Sauber introduced a revised evolution of its Ferrari 050 engine that the team had used in the first five races of the 2002 championship. The team installed a new aerodynamic package that included a revised undertray, front wing and altered bodywork around the cover of the [[Sauber C21|C21]]'s engine. The Ferrari, McLaren and Williams teams brought new [[Intake|air intakes]] installed to the front brakes. Williams also used an upgraded front wing specification for its [[Williams FW24|FW24]], which was characterised by a curved profile <ref name=\"Piola\">{{cite journal|last=Piola|first=Giorgio|date=May 2002|title=Sauber un pieno di novit\u00e0|url=|journal=Autosprint|language=Italian|volume=1420|issue=20|pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n==Practice==\nFour practice sessions were held before the Sunday race, two each on Friday and Saturday. The Friday morning and afternoon sessions each lasted an hour; the third and fourth sessions, on Saturday morning, lasted 45 minutes each.<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jomenvisst.de/fia/2002SportingRegulations/2002_F1_Sporting_Regulations.pdf|title=2002 Formula One Sporting Regulations|date=31 October 2001|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|pages=12\u201314|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017221540/http://www.jomenvisst.de/fia/2002SportingRegulations/2002_F1_Sporting_Regulations.pdf|archive-date=17 October 2014|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> The first practice session was held in cool and overcast weather. Michael Schumacher was fastest with a lap of 1 minute and 11.072 seconds with approximately ten minutes remaining. His teammate Barrichello, [[Felipe Massa]] and [[Nick Heidfeld]] of Sauber, [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] drivers [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] and [[Takuma Sato]], Coulthard, [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]' [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]], and the [[British American Racing]] (BAR) duo of [[Jacques Villeneuve]] and [[Olivier Panis]], were second through tenth.<ref name=AF1FP1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/userlogin?r=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7268/.html|title=Friday First Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Some drivers\u2014including Barrichello, Massa and Fisichella\u2014ran off the dusty, slippery track into a [[Run-off area|gravel trap]] during the session because of a low amount of [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]]; none sustained damage to their vehicles.<ref name=AF1FP1/><ref name=FIAFriday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news1.htm|title=Bulletin No 1 \u2013 Free Practice Session|date=10 May 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020616070255/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news1.htm|archive-date=16 June 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nConditions became warmer and sunnier for the second practice session though rainfall threatened towards the end.<ref name=F1NetFP1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35001|title=Barrichello leads Ferrari whitewash|date=10 May 2002|publisher=F1Racing.net|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041123045910/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35001|archive-date=30 September 2004|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> The fastest times to be recorded within the first 20 minutes since the track temperature was at its warmest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18909|title=Practice 2: Barrichello heads Schuey|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/rHoil|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Barrichello set the day's fastest lap, at 1-minute and 10.549 seconds. His teammate Michael Schumacher was three-hundredths of a second slower in second position. Montoya, [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]] of the McLaren team, [[Allan McNish]] for [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]], Arrows driver [[Enrique Bernoldi]], [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]'s [[Pedro de la Rosa]], Panis, Coulthard and Sato were third to tenth.<ref name=AF1FP2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/userlogin?r=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7270/.html|title=Friday Second Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=10 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Some drivers, including Michael and Ralf Schumacher, and McNish, again lost control of their cars and ran off to the side of the track during the session.<ref name=F1NetFP1/><ref name=AF1FP2/> Heidfeld's track time was curtailed after 20 minutes due to an [[Alternator (automotive)|alternator]] fault.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9404.html|title=Practice report: Barrichello leads on Friday|date=10 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021003055037/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9404.html|archive-date=3 October 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Frentzen lost a quarter of an hour to familiarise himself with the track after he spun over a [[Curb|kerb]] and damaged his car's undertray.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nThe third practice session took place in clear and dry weather; no drivers ventured off the less slippery circuit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9418.html|title=Practice report: Ferrari dominant early on Saturday|date=11 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020810030231/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9418.html|archive-date=10 August 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher used low track and ambient temperatures to become the first driver to go below 70 seconds all weekend with a lap of 1 minute and 9.001 seconds that he recorded half an hour in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18927|title=Practice 3: Schuey's stunning pace|date=11 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/olhvu|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=DF1FP3>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/news/news.php?id=1126|title=Schumacher blitzes third free|last=Raman|first=Nick|date=11 May 2002|publisher=Daily F1|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101015821/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/news/news.php?id=1126|archive-date=1 November 2002|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> His teammate Barrichello was second-fastest and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen third. Frentzen, Massa, Coulthard, Heidfeld, Panis, Button and Bernoldi followed in positions four through ten.<ref name=DF1FP3/>\n\nThe ambient and track temperatures had increased by the start of the fourth practice session.<ref name=F1NetFP4>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35045|title=Ferrari dominate but Williams close in|date=11 May 2002|publisher=F1Racing.net|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041123045934/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35045|archive-date=23 November 2004|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Several competitors made driver errors that sent them into a gravel trap.<ref name=AutosportFP4>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18928|title=Practice 4: No stopping Schumacher|date=11 May 2002|website=Autosport|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HmnP8|archive-date=15 September 2019|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher set the track record, with a lap of 1 minute and 8.433 seconds. Barrichello was second, and Ralf Schumacher improved to third. Montoya, Frentzen, Massa, Heidfeld, R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen, Panis and Villeneuve completed the top ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7294/.html|title=Saturday Second Free Practice \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=11 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050201004749/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7294/.html|archive-date=1 February 2005|access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> Bernoldi missed 25 minutes due to a malfunctioning gearbox. He later lost control of the rear of his car at turn two and beached in a gravel trap before the session ended.<ref name=F1NetFP4/><ref name=AutosportFP4/>\n\n==Qualifying==\n[[File:Barrichello_2002.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Rubens Barrichello in a red racing suit | [[Rubens Barrichello]] took his second [[pole position]] of the 2002 season and the fifth of his career]]\n\nSaturday's afternoon one-hour qualifying session saw each competitor limited to twelve laps, with the starting order decided by their fastest laps. The [[107% rule]] was in effect during this session, requiring each driver set a time within 107 per cent of the quickest lap to qualify for the race.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Conditions were clear with warm air and track temperatures.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news2.htm|title=Bulletin No 2 \u2013 Free Practice and Qualifying|date=11 May 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020817101112/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news2.htm|archivedate=16 June 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DTQuali\" /> Barrichello took his second [[pole position]] of the season and the fifth of his career with a lap of 1 minute and 8.082 seconds.<ref name=\"UPIPole\">{{cite news|title=Barrichello on pole for Grand Prix|url=https://www.upi.com/Sports_News/2002/05/11/Barrichello-on-pole-for-Grand-Prix/83391021140456/?st_rec=4929582004800&ur3=1|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was joined on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row by Ralf Schumacher, who took his best starting position of the year.<ref name=\"UPIPole\" /> Michael Schumacher was third; he said he lost speed due to a brake problem, and that traffic baulked him.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\">{{cite web|title=Team and Driver comments \u2013 Saturday|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/2002season/results/06/quotes-sat.phtml|publisher=Daily F1|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615112230/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/2002season/results/06/quotes-sat.phtml|archivedate=15 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> He switched to the spare Ferrari for his final timed lap in an unsuccessful attempt to claim pole position,<ref name=\"AutosportQuali\">{{cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18932|title=Qualifying: Rubens takes pole|date=11 May 2002|work=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/gISII|archive-date=15 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DTQuali\">{{cite news|title=Brazilian halts procession|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3027580/Brazilian-halts-procession.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=11 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508124126/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3027580/Brazilian-halts-procession.html|archive-date=8 May 2019}}</ref> and did not earn a front-row start for the first time since the [[2001 Italian Grand Prix]] eight races earlier.<ref name=\"ObserverQuali\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/12/formulaone.theobserver|title=Barrichello charge puts rivals on red alert|last=Hamilton|first=Maurice|date=12 May 2002|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=15 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007220211/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/12/formulaone.theobserver|archive-date=7 October 2017}}</ref> A misfiring engine prompted Montoya in fourth to switch to the spare car [[Racing setup|setup]] for his teammate Ralf Schumacher; he made a minor tyre-pressure adjustment to record his fastest lap.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> Heidfeld took fifth, claiming he could have improved had Button not slowed his final timed lap. A lack of speed restricted the McLaren duo of R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Coulthard to sixth and eighth; they were separated by Massa who made two driver errors in an unbalanced car through high-speed turns. Panis set the ninth-fastest time as de la Rosa slowed his final timed lap. Toyota's [[Mika Salo]] in tenth had a minor [[Understeer and oversteer|understeer]].<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" />\n\nFrentzen in 11th spun on oil and removed some bodywork components from his car in a gravel trap. His vehicle was later repaired to continue driving.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AutosportQuali\" /> His Arrows' teammate Bernoldi followed in 12th and expressed satisfaction with his car's balance.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" /> Traffic slowed Button on his four timed laps and left him 13th.<ref name=\"SundayTimesQuali\">{{cite news|last=Rae|first=Richard|title=Cap that, partner; Motor racing|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85906722/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=b47018b2|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=15 September 2019|page=18|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription|url-status=dead}}</ref> McNish and Toyota located a car setup tailored to suit him, and took 14th.<ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" /> Fisichella ran a new engine in qualifying and took 15th with a car setup suited for used front and new rear tyres.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> [[Jarno Trulli]] had a major engine failure through turn nine and lost control of his Renault on the leaked oil from the engine failure.<ref name=\"AutosportQuali\" /> The session was stopped for 11 minutes for [[Motorsport marshal|track marshals]] to dry it.<ref name=\"ObserverQuali\" /> Trulli returned to his garage and used the spare Renault setup for his teammate Button and took 16th after minor braking problems. Villeneuve used a new set of tyres for qualifying; he was uncomfortable with his car's setup and was 17th. A handling imbalance created an unbalanced car for Sato in 18th. Jaguar's de la Rosa and [[Eddie Irvine]] filled the grid's tenth row: de la Rosa had a rear suspension fault caused by an [[Exhaust system|exhaust]] overheating it and Irvine removed his front wing in a collision with the rear of Bernoldi's vehicle into turn one. [[Minardi]] drivers [[Mark Webber]] and [[Alex Yoong]] started from the eleventh row: Webber optimised his [[Minardi PS02|PS02]]'s balance so it ran without any issues on its tyres during the session, and intermittent rear brake locking destabilised Yoong's car causing him to spin after he exited the pit lane.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"DF1Quotes\" />\n\n===Qualifying classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable  sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver \n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor \n! scope=\"col\" | Lap \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Gap|Gap to the fastest driver in seconds}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:08.082\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:08.364\n| +0.282\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:08.704\n| +0.622\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:09.118\n| +1.036\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:09.129\n| +1.047\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 1:09.154\n| +1.072\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Felipe Massa]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:09.228\n| +1.146\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 1:09.335\n| +1.253\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Olivier Panis]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:09.561\n| +1.479\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 24\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n| [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 1:09.661\n| +1.579\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 20\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:09.671\n| +1.589\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 21\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Enrique Bernoldi]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:09.723\n| +1.641\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| 15\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n| [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 1:09.780\n| +1.698\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| 25\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Allan McNish]]\n| [[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 1:09.818\n| +1.736\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:09.901\n| +1.819\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| 14\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n| [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 1:09.980\n| +1.898\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| 11\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:10.051\n| +1.969\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Takuma Sato]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:10.058\n| +1.976\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 17\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:10.553\n| +2.471\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:10.741\n| +2.659\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| 23\n| {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Mark Webber]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 1:11.388\n| +3.306\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22\n| 22\n| {{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[Alex Yoong]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 1:12.336\n| +4.254\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |[[107% rule]]: 1:12.848\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\"|{{center|Sources:<ref name=DTQuali/><ref>{{cite web|title=Austria 2002: Qualifications|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/qualification.aspx|publisher=Stats F1|accessdate=18 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717225750/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/qualification.aspx|archive-date=17 July 2017}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nA half hour warm-up session took place on Sunday morning,<ref name=\"regulations\" /> in clear and warm weather conditions. All drivers fine-tuned their race setups for the weather and drove their spare cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news3.htm|title=Bulletin No 3 \u2013 Warm-Up|date=1 November 2002|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101093606/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news3.htm|archive-date=1 November 2002|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> Barrichello had the fastest lap of 1 minute and 10.876 seconds and his teammate Michael Schumacher was second. Massa, Frentzen, Heidfeld, Bernoldi, Coulthard, Villeneuve, R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Irvine completed the top ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7316/.html|title=Sunday Warm Up \u2013 Austrian GP|last=Gray|first=Will|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040028/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7316/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> While the session saw no major incidents, Ralf Schumacher entered the gravel traps at the two of the track's corners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18949|title=Warm-up: Ferrari still on top|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/HJp9R|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the warm-up session, Montoya predicted several drivers would run wide on a [[rumble strip]] located to the outside of the circuit, which extended from turn one to the first portion of the [[Straight (racing)|straight]] driving towards turn one, to increase the top speed of their cars.{{refn|group=N|name=\"WhitingSatMeeting\"|[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] race director [[Charlie Whiting]] told drivers in a meeting on Saturday afternoon they would be permitted to use the [[rumble strip]] to the outside of turn one.<ref name=MontoyaPreRace/>}}<ref name=MontoyaPreRace>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7317/.html|title=Montoya Predicts Eventful First Corner|date=12 May 2002|website=Atlas F1|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=18 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040032/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7317/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005}}</ref> [[Ron Dennis]], the team principal of McLaren, argued Ferrari should allow their drivers to race each other without the imposition of [[team orders]] favouring one driver over the other as had happened in the [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix|2001 race]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Let the Ferraris race, says Dennis|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18955|work=[[Autosport]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|archive-url=https://archive.is/EGnZd|archive-date=16 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\nThe race began at 14:00 local time;<ref name=\"CF1Overview\" /> the weather was clear and dry. The air temperature was {{Convert|20|C|F|abbr=}} and the track temperature ranged from {{Convert|27|to|29|C|comma=}}.<ref name=F1NetRace>{{cite web|title=Cynical Ferrari rob Rubens of victory|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35091|publisher=F1Racing.net|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040930004806/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=35091|archivedate=30 September 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=F1COMRace>{{cite web|title=2002: Round 6: Austria: A1-Ring|url=http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews02/austria/race.html|publisher=[[Formula1.com]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020809230856/http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews02/austria/race.html|archivedate=9 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> Barrichello made a brisk start to maintain the lead into the first turn.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\">{{cite web|title=Lap by lap: Austrian GP|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1982854.stm|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021213619/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1982854.stm|archivedate=21 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> While he provided room for drivers to pass him, none did.<ref name=\"DF1Review\">{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Chris|last2=Raman|first2=Nick|title=Ferrari's farcical finish|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/features/feature.php?id=35|publisher=Daily F1|date=May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021017113858/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/features/feature.php?id=35|archivedate=17 October 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> Behind Barrichello, his teammate Michael Schumacher made a fast start to slot into second position and Heidfeld rose from fifth to third having overtaken Ralf Schumacher on the outside.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\">{{cite web|title=Bulletin N\u00b04 \u2013 Race Facts and Incidents|url=http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news4.htm|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020817091625/http://www.fia.com/PRESSE/F1-GP-2002/austria/news4.htm|archivedate=17 August 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen and Massa, meanwhile, drew alongside and Massa steered onto the grass<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> dropping to tenth. Further back, Bernoldi made contact with the rear of his teammate Frentzen;<ref name=\"Auto1Race\">{{cite web|last=Cipolloni|first=Mark|title=Disgrace in Austria as Barrichello hands win to Schuey|url=http://autoracing1.com/htmfiles/2002/F1/0512AustriaRace.asp|publisher=AutoRacing1|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018090142/http://autoracing1.com/htmfiles/2002/F1/0512AustriaRace.asp|archivedate=18 October 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> both cars continued as Bernoldi entered the pit lane after the first lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> At turn two, an increase in speed led de la Rosa's [[throttle]] pick-up to start to cut out.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> He slowed, and retired in the pit lane at the end of the lap. In the meantime, Villeneuve experienced a minor loss of car control and hit Frentzen's car on the inside.<ref name=\"CrashRace\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/f1/racereports_others.asp?feature_id=1809&language_id=1&championship_id=1|title=Austrian GP 2002 \u2013 Rubens robbed|date=12 May 2002|publisher=Crash|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805093156/http://www.crash.net/f1/racereports_others.asp?feature_id=1809&language_id=1&championship_id=1|archivedate=5 August 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref> The collision sent Frentzen into a gravel trap from which he slowly extricated himself.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"CrashRace\" />\n\n[[File:Juan Pablo Montoya (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Juan Pablo Montoya dressed in white looking to his left | [[Juan Pablo Montoya]] ''(pictured at the [[United States Grand Prix]] later in 2002)'' finished in third position]]\n\nAt the end of the first lap, Barrichello led his teammate Michael Schumacher, Heidfeld, Ralf Schumacher, Montoya and Coulthard.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Heidfeld ran wide at Castrol Kurve at the beginning of the second lap and the Williams pair of Ralf Schumacher and Montoya demoted him to fifth.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> Barrichello and Michael Schumacher began to pull away from the rest of the field.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> There were overtakes further down the field. On lap two, Salo passed Button for eighth position.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Villeneuve overtook his teammate Panis for 14th position and Frentzen passed Webber on lap three.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> During the next lap Yoong lost two places to his teammate Webber, and Frentzen.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Bernoldi retired from the race with a broken front wing and front brake pipe.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen in seventh retired at the side of the track with an engine failure on lap six.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\">{{cite web|title=Team orders rob Barrichello of Austrian GP win|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/team-orders-rob-barrichello-of-austrian-gp-win/92031/|publisher=[[motorsport.com]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On lap seven Villeneuve passed McNish for tenth place, then lost it as he ran wide. He made a second, successful attempt on the eighth lap, passing McNish who opted against a challenge.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nThat same lap, Massa entered the pit lane to join the list of retirees with a failed left-rear [[Car suspension|suspension]] bracket; it failed in turn two, causing the Sauber C21's right-front wheel to lift from the tarmac surface and its undertray to scrape along it. Villeneuve made a pass on Fisichella for ninth place on lap ten.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Not long after Villeneuve overtook Button for eighth position. By the same lap, Barrichello led by a second over his teammate Michael Schumacher, who in turn was 17 seconds ahead of Ralf Schumacher. Further down the order, Frentzen put a rear wheel on the grass at the final corner on lap 16. He lost control of his car, spun through 180 degrees and rolled backwards in front of the race leaders. Frentzen fell to 18th position, behind the Minardi cars of Webber and Yoong. He passed Yoong to return to 17th position on the 18th lap.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> One lap later, Villeneuve overtook Salo on the inside for seventh place and blocked his attempted counter-move.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" />\n\nAs the Ferraris extended their lead over Ralf Schumacher, the stewards informed the BAR team on the 23rd lap that Villeneuve had incurred a [[Formula One regulations#Penalties|drive-through penalty]] as they deemed him at fault for the collision with Frentzen on lap one.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Lap 24 saw the [[safety car]]'s first deployment: Panis' engine failed without warning on the start/finish straight.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> His rear wheels locked, spun to the centre of the track and avoided colliding with a barrier.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /><ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Track marshals removed Panis' car from the circuit as he returned to the pit lane.<ref name=\"IHTRace\">{{cite news|last=Spurgeon|first=Brad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/14/sports/IHT-formula-one-barrichello-ushers-schumacher-to-first.html|title=Formula One : Barrichello ushers Schumacher to first|date=14 May 2002|newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]]|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409063533/https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/14/sports/IHT-formula-one-barrichello-ushers-schumacher-to-first.html|archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Ferrari and Williams' teams employed different pit stop strategies\u2014the Ferrari team planned for  two stops whereas the Williams team planned one.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> The Ferrari team called Barrichello and Michael Schumacher into the pit lane for their first [[pit stop]]s; Schumacher drove more slowly than Barrichello to allow their mechanics to service the latter's car first. Barrichello retained the lead as Michael Schumacher yielded second to Ralf Schumacher. The safety car was withdrawn at the conclusion of the 27th lap and Barrichello led at the restart.<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" />\n\n[[File:Takuma Sato.jpg|left|thumb|upright|alt=Photograph of Takuma Saot seated behind a table with a pen in hand | [[Takuma Sato]] ''(pictured in 2002)'' was involved in a heavy accident that caused soft-tissue damage to his right thigh]]\n\nSoon after, a major accident prompted the safety car's second deployment on lap 28.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\">{{cite web|last=Mauk|first=Eric|title=Ferrari Orders Barrichello To Give Up Austrian Win To Schumacher|url=http://speedtv.com/auto/?lvl=3a&cat=17&id=1440|publisher=[[Speed (TV network)|Speed]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=14 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020607115755/http://speedtv.com/auto/?lvl=3a&cat=17&id=1440|archivedate=7 June 2002|url-status=dead}}</ref> As the field entered turn two,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Heidfeld noticed smoke coming from Yoong's Minardi and applied his cold brakes heavily. This locked the Sauber's rear wheels and sent him out of control about {{Convert|100|yd|m|abbr=on}} from the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#A|apex]].<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> He veered into the grass as his car spun 180 degrees;<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> the grass did not slow him,<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> and he was launched over the crest of a hill.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Montoya on the inside was about to lap Sato's slower car at turn two, with the latter ahead of him at the turn's apex.<ref name=\"SatoCrash\">{{cite web|title=Do you remember... Sato's 'miracle' escape in Austria|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2015/6/do-you-remember----satos-miracle-escape-in-austria.html|publisher=Formula One|date=16 June 2015|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421021549/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/features/2015/6/do-you-remember----satos-miracle-escape-in-austria.html|archive-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> At high speed,<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> Heidfeld narrowly avoided a collision with Montoya's front wing,<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> and the rear of his Sauber sustained a [[side collision]] against the right-hand sidepod of Sato's car,<ref name=\"F1NetRace\" /><ref name=\"DawnRace\">{{cite news|title=Schumacher ends jinx in controversial finish|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/33649/schumacher-ends-jinx-in-controversial-finish|newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|date=12 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916091632/https://www.dawn.com/news/33649/schumacher-ends-jinx-in-controversial-finish|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> causing heavy damage to both vehicles and littering carbon fibre and titanium debris on a wide area of track.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Heidfeld's rear structure and titanium gearbox punctured a hole in Sato's car; his knees struck the steering column breaking it in half.<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\">{{cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/feature/42267/1/taku-grateful-for-safety-advances|title=Taku grateful for safety advances|date=23 May 2002|publisher=Crash|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062412/https://www.crash.net/f1/feature/42267/1/taku-grateful-for-safety-advances|archive-date=9 April 2020|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> Both drivers were sent into a gravel trap and came to a stop there.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nA visibly shaken Heidfeld was extricated from his car by track marshals with a heavily bruised left leg.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> Sato remained in his car with soft-tissue damage to his right thigh<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> but did not lose consciousness;<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" /> a section of the Sauber's rear crash structure penetrated the side of the Jordan's monocoque just below Sato's right knee and his [[Racing helmet|helmet]] was squeezed between the car's [[head restraint]], both of which prevented him from leaving his car.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /><ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" /> The [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA, Formula One's governing body) safety and medical delegate [[Sid Watkins]] and his team took ten minutes to remove Sato from the car and treated him at the crash site before transporting him by ambulance to the track's medical centre.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> From there,<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Sato and Heidfeld were flown by helicopter to [[Medical University of Graz|Graz University Hospital]],<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> for overnight observation and precautionary x-ray scans.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Under safety car conditions, every team except for Ferrari and Williams brought their drivers to the pit lane for additional fuel and a set of tyres.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> After 20 minutes,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> the race restarted at the end of the 36th lap when the safety car entered the pit lane. Barrichello led Ralf Schumacher, Michael Schumacher, Montoya, Coulthard and Fisichella. On lap 37, Webber passed his teammate Yoong for 13th position.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\nVilleneuve passed Fisichella for sixth place at the start of the 38th lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> On the same lap, Irvine entered the pit lane to retire with a hydraulics failure.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Two laps later, Villeneuve caught and overtook Coulthard at turn one for fifth position.<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /> Coulthard lost sixth place to Fisichella after he drove on oil and off the circuit on the 45th lap.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> On the same lap Trulli pulled over at the end of the pit lane wall on the start/finish straight to retire from with a loss of [[Pressure regulator|fuel pressure]].<ref name=\"F1COMRace\" /><ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Yoong retired with fire visible from the rear of his Minardi not long after.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Green flag pit stops began on lap 47. Ralf Schumacher made a pit stop and dropped to fifth position. His teammate Montoya remained on the track for another four laps and used more fuel in an attempt to overtake Ralf Schumacher.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Montoya entered the pit lane for tyres on the 51st lap.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> He returned to the race in fourth position, ahead of his teammate Ralf Schumacher.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> Villeneuve was elevated to third position until a pit stop on lap 53 demoted him to ninth. Montoya and Ralf Schumacher returned to third and fourth positions respectively.<ref name=\"FIARace\" />\n\n[[File:2002 Austrian GP.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph showing Rubens Barrichello making way to allow Michael Schumacher to cross the finish line ahead of him | Ferrari invoked [[team orders]] to allow [[Michael Schumacher]] past his teammate Rubens Barrichello to win the race and earn the maximum number of points towards the World Drivers' Championship.]]\n\nBarrichello entered the pit lane for the second time on the 61st lap. His fuel stop took 6.2 seconds and he exited in second place. His teammate Michael Schumacher led lap 62 and made his second pit stop at the end of the lap. He returned to the race in second position; Barrichello returned to first.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> On the 63rd lap,<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Ferrari team principal [[Jean Todt]] invoked team orders on Barrichello to relinquish the victory to his teammate Michael Schumacher.<ref name=\"LaStampaTodt\">{{cite news|last=Mancini|first=Stefano|title=Todt: \"Ferrari tradita dai nervi Sembrava impossibile perdere\"|url=https://www.lastampa.it/sport/motori/2010/11/18/news/todt-ferrari-tradita-dai-nervi-br-sembrava-impossibile-perdere-1.36992867|newspaper=[[La Stampa]]|language=Italian|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916182037/https://www.lastampa.it/sport/motori/2010/11/18/news/todt-ferrari-tradita-dai-nervi-br-sembrava-impossibile-perdere-1.36992867|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>{{refn|group=N|name=\"TeamOrders\"|It was the second year in succession that Barrichello had been asked to relinquish a position to his teammate Michael Schumacher on the start/finish straight on the last lap, as he had done so for second position in the [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix|2001 race]].<ref name=\"DawnRace\" />}} This would improve Schumacher's position in the World Drivers' Championship with a win earning him ten points. Ferrari advised Barrichello they would terminate his contract if he failed to do so.<ref name=\"TerraBAR\">{{cite news|title=Rubinho diz que foi amea\u00e7ado para dar posi\u00e7\u00e3o a Schumacher em 2002|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/motor/formula-1/noticia/2012/05/rubinho-diz-que-foi-ameacado-para-dar-posicao-schumacher-em-2002.html|publisher=[[Rede Globo]]|language=Portuguese|date=9 May 2012|accessdate=16 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512021344/http://globoesporte.globo.com/motor/formula-1/noticia/2012/05/rubinho-diz-que-foi-ameacado-para-dar-posicao-schumacher-em-2002.html|archivedate=12 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Barrichello reminded Todt over the radio of a promise he made not to relinquish a victory to a driver. This prompted Todt to reply to Barrichello that he was required to obey his instruction to preserve Ferrari's \"best interests\".<ref name=\"TODisobey\">{{cite web|title=Barrichello Reveals He Queried Team Orders in Austria|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jun/report.php/id/7677/.html|work=Atlas F1|date=20 June 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041221112526/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jun/report.php/id/7677/.html|archive-date=21 December 2004}}</ref> Personnel on the Ferrari pit gantry observed the television screens and noticed Michael Schumacher could not get close enough to pass Barrichello in the final seven laps.<ref name=\"DF1Review\" />\n\nAt the start of the final lap, Barrichello led his teammate Michael Schumacher by one second.<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> As Barrichello entered the final corner,<ref name=\"BBCWebRace\" /> Ferrari technical director [[Ross Brawn]] informed Michael Schumacher over the radio his teammate would yield to him.<ref name=\"CrashRace\" /> When Barrichello braked in the final {{Convert|100|to|50|yd|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /><ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Michael Schumacher slowed more than his teammate because he had hoped that no team orders would be applied as Barrichello did the same to comply with Ferrari's instruction.<ref name=\"IERace\">{{cite news|last=Quigley|first=Declan|title=Hollow win for Schumacher as Sato makes 'miracle' escape|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/hollow-win-for-schumacher-as-sato-makes-miracle-escape-26047923.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=13 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916083321/https://www.independent.ie/sport/hollow-win-for-schumacher-as-sato-makes-miracle-escape-26047923.html|archive-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> Schumacher passed Barrichello for his first victory in Austria, his fourth in a row in 2002, and the 58th of his career in a time of 1 hour, 33 minutes and 51.562 seconds at an average speed of {{Convert|196.334|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> Barrichello was 0.182 seconds behind in second position with Montoya 17.7 seconds adrift in third. Montoya's teammate Ralf Schumacher finished in fourth place.<ref name=\"SpeedRace\" /> Fisichella was fifth and took the first two points of the season for the Jordan team. Coulthard took the final point in sixth position, ahead of Button's Renault and the Toyota cars of Salo and McNish.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> A loss of hydraulic pressure caused Villeneuve's engine to fail on the final lap; he was classified tenth.<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Frentzen and Webber for the Arrows and Minardi teams were the final finishers, albeit two laps behind the race winner.<ref name=\"DawnRace\" />\n\n==Post-race==\nThe Ferrari team were booed, jeered, whistled at and given a thumbs down signal by the crowd in ''[[parc ferm\u00e9]]'' and on the podium.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Michael Schumacher insisted Barrichello to mount the first position on the podium, as \"[[Deutschlandlied]]\" was played.<ref name=\"GPCOMRace\" /> Schumacher then stood next to his teammate during the composition of [[Il Canto degli Italiani]] <ref name=\"DF1Review\" /> When [[Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel]], the [[Chancellor of Austria]], presented the winner's trophy to Schumacher, the latter gave it to Barrichello.<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Later, in the press conference, where loud boos were heard,<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /> Barrichello said of the situation, \"I'm going through a period of a very good time of my life. I'm becoming a better person, a better driver, so there's no point in arguing. I think my determination will bring me a lot more wins, so that's the way I see it, so there's no point arguing.\"<ref name=PressConf>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7334/.html|title=Post-Race Press Conference \u2013 Austrian GP|date=12 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064312/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7334/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Michael Schumacher said he understood Ferrari's decision, \"the team is investing a lot of money for one sort of target and imagine in the end it wouldn't be enough by this amount of points, how stupid would we look?\"<ref name=PressConf/> Montoya said the two safety car periods allowed him to pass his teammate Ralf Schumacher, \"Ralf was quite quick out of the pits as well, but I managed to get a few laps in really quick right before the stop and that was enough.\"<ref name=PressConf/>\n\nSato and Heidfeld were deemed fit to compete at the next race of the season, the [[2002 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]] two weeks later, after they passed fitness tests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/19098|title=Sato and Heidfeld pass fitness tests|date=22 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/SPLU3|archive-date=16 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> Sid Watkins told [[Eddie Jordan]], the owner of the Jordan team, that Sato had \"a miraculous escape\", leading Jordan to remark, \"Somebody up there likes him\".<ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> Sato said he had not observed Heidfeld approaching him, \"When I opened my eyes I could see my legs were squashed by the damaged monocoque and I could see the ground through the hole. Although there was some pain, I knew nothing was broken. The car did a great job of saving me \u2013 I hear there was nothing left of it.\"<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> Heidfeld admitted he was at fault for causing the crash, \"I saw a cloud of tyre smoke as [Alex] Yoong braked really hard and early ahead of us, and maybe I pressed the pedal too hard as a result while the brakes were still cool. The car got away from me and next thing I knew I was going backwards down the grass.\"<ref name=\"SatoCrash\" /> That the injuries Sato sustained in the accident were minor was cited as a consequence of improved safety standards undertaken by the FIA, racing teams and medical experts since the 1970s.<ref name=\"SatoExtraction\" />\n\nRalf Schumacher praised his car for allowing him to finish fourth, \"Due to the action packed race and the different strategies it is difficult to say how big Ferrari's advantage really was here on the A1-Ring. We have to continue to work hard, this much is clear.\"<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> Fisichella commented on his fifth-place finish, \"It's been a very, very good day for me, as I didn't expect to score points. But, the most important thing is that Takuma is alright. It felt fantastic when I crossed the line and I would like to say thank you to the team, especially because we made the right pit stop decision.\"<ref name=\"Auto1Race\" /> The race result increased Michael Schumacher's lead in the Drivers' Championship to 27 points over Montoya in second place. Ralf Schumacher was third with 23 points. Barrichello moved past Coulthard for fourth with 12 points.<ref name=\"2002points\" /> In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari further extended their advantage over the Williams team to 16 points. McLaren maintained third position with 14 points. The Renault and Sauber teams continued to hold fourth and fifth places with eleven races left in the season.<ref name=\"2002points\" />\n\n===Team orders===\nThe Ferrari team's use of team orders to determine the finishing order overshadowed the race.<ref name=\"IHTRace\" /><ref name=\"DawnRace\" /> ''[[Reuters]]'' cited it as the most \"particularly blatant\" application of team orders applied to favour one driver over another since Coulthard relinquished first position to his McLaren teammate [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] in the final laps of the [[1998 Australian Grand Prix]] to comply with a prior agreement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7356/.html|title=Analysis: Team Orders Go Back a Long Way in F1|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|date=13 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=17 September 2019|agency=Reuters|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040151/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7356/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nFerrari were heavily condemned by fans on the internet,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/18981|title=Autosport.com readers 'anti' Ferrari|date=13 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/tT1Qw|archive-date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns06280.html|title=The flood continues...|date=15 May 2002|publisher=GrandPrix.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020611070646/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns06280.html|archive-date=11 June 2002|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref> some members of the Formula One community,<ref name=\"GuardianRace\">{{cite news|last=Henry|first=Alan|authorlink=Alan Henry|title=Fury over stitch-up for Schumacher victory; Barrichello is told to hand over the lead|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/13/formulaone.formulaone2002|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 May 2002|accessdate=16 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909140321/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2002/may/13/formulaone.formulaone2002|archive-date=9 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=TheAgePress>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/14/1021002446562.html|title=Brazilians cry foul over Ferrari tactics|date=15 May 2002|work=[[The Age]]|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021022111326/http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/14/1021002446562.html|archive-date=22 October 2002}}</ref> the world's press, and [[President of Brazil|President]] [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]] of Brazil.{{refn|group=N|name=\"BetsOff\"|An Italian online betting company and the Swedish public lottery [[Svenska Spel]] paid out those who bet on Barrichello to win the Grand Prix.<ref name=TheAgePress/>}}<ref name=TheAgePress/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/13/1021002432326.html|title=Ferrari blasted worldwide for Grand Prix gaffe|date=14 May 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=17 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020815000322/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/13/1021002432326.html|archive-date=15 August 2002}}</ref> Some Formula One figures held different views, including the Williams pair of Montoya and Ralf Schumacher, and Irvine, who all stated their belief Michael Schumacher should not be apportioned blame for winning the Grand Prix via team orders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7370/.html|title=Montoya Defends Michael Schumacher|date=14 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064420/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7370/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/schumi-not-to-blame/|title='Schumi not to blame'|date=15 May 2002|website=[[Car (magazine)|Car Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062744/https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/schumi-not-to-blame/|archive-date=9 April 2020|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A85940422/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=db2dcac5|title=Support for Schumacher|last=Gray|first=Will|date=15 May 2002|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=17 September 2019|page=03|via=Gale OneFile: News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Jody Scheckter]], the [[1979 Formula One season|1979 world champion]] and Ron Dennis defended Ferrari's application of team orders as a means of enhancing Michael Schumacher's position in the championship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9511.html|title=Dennis: don't ban team orders|date=19 May 2002|publisher=Formula1.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805231648/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines02/05/s9511.html|archive-date=5 August 2002|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/19009|title=Scheckter on Ferrari's side|date=16 May 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/3IqGN|archive-date=17 September 2019|access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe day after the race, the FIA summoned Ferrari and its drivers to a meeting of the [[FIA World Motor Sport Council]] to be held in Paris on 26 June to explain why the team ordered Barrichello to yield the victory to Michael Schumacher and their actions on the podium.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/ferrari-schumi-barrichello-summoned-by-fia-511410|title=Ferrari, Schumi, Barrichello summoned by FIA|date=13 May 2002|work=[[Cape Argus]]|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409062630/https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/ferrari-schumi-barrichello-summoned-by-fia-511410|archive-date=9 April 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> During a press conference on 24 May, FIA president [[Max Mosley]] stated Ferrari had not transgressed any regulations on team orders and the meeting would establish the appropriate punishment in the event a panel deemed if any rules were broken, \"There are rules about interfering with competition but we established a long time ago that team orders are allowed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7448/.html|title=Mosley: No Long-Term Damage to F1 after Austria|last=Young|first=Byron|date=24 May 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211064656/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7448/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> That same day, Mosley revealed on behalf of the FIA he wrote a letter of apology to Wolfgang Sch\u00fcssel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7450/.html|title=FIA Apologises to Austrian Chancellor|date=24 May 2002|work=[[Atlas F1]]|access-date=18 September 2019|agency=Reuters|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211040504/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/may/report.php/id/7450/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the meeting, the FIA deemed Ferrari to have transgressed series regulations when Michael Schumacher chose not to mount the first position on the podium and handed the trophy given to him by the Chancellor of Austria to his teammate Barrichello. The council also determined the team had not committed any violation when it invoked team orders on Barrichello to relinquish the victory to Michael Schumacher.<ref name=$1MilliionFineCNN/> It imposed a fine of $1 million on Ferrari, Michael Schumacher and Barrichello, half of which was paid immediately and divided into equal amounts between the trio; the remainder was suspended for one year on the condition a similar offence did not occur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://link.gale.com/apps/doc/A87880652/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=cf29ad9d|title=Ferrari happy to pay the price for Austria farce; Motor racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=27 June 2002|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=18 September 2019|page=40|via=Gale Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Neither a points deduction nor a race ban were imposed.<ref name=$1MilliionFineCNN>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/06/26/ferrari.fine/index.html|title=Ferrari and drivers fined $1m|date=26 June 2002|access-date=18 September 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018203630/http://www.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/europe/06/26/ferrari.fine/index.html|archive-date=18 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn response Mosley established a four-member working group to discuss team orders and invited the public to lend their opinion on the practice on the FIA's website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2067911.stm|title=F1 sets up team orders probe|date=26 June 2002|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040109090334/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2067911.stm|archive-date=9 January 2004|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> The FIA accepted feedback from 5 July to 1 September, which was passed on to the working group. They reviewed it and gave their recommendations to the governing body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jul/report.php/id/7853/.html|title=FIA Requests Public Suggestions on Team Orders|date=5 July 2002|website=[[Atlas F1]]|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050211034449/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2002/jul/report.php/id/7853/.html|archive-date=11 February 2005|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref> At a meeting of the 26-member Formula One Commission on 28 October, it was confirmed \"team orders that interfere with the race result\" would be barred from the [[2003 Formula One World Championship|2003 season]] onwards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683417190.html|title=Changes steer towards more open Formula One|date=30 October 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=18 September 2019|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021101213713/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683417190.html|archive-date=1 November 2002}}</ref> During the [[2010 German Grand Prix]] at the [[Hockenheimring]], Ferrari employed a \"coded message\"<ref name=\":0\" /> to invoke team orders to allow driver [[Fernando Alonso]] to pass Felipe Massa late on; Alonso went on to win the event. The parallels between how Michael Schumacher and Alonso won those races led the FIA to rescinding the regulation barring team orders in December 2010 because it was deemed difficult to enforce.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/9275796.stm|title=F1 chiefs drop the ban on team orders in new rules|date=10 December 2010|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-53494420101210|title=Team orders can come out of hiding now|last=Baldwin|first=Alan|date=10 December 2010|access-date=18 September 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nTodt admitted to ''[[La Stampa]]'' in December 2010 he should have avoided using team orders on Barrichello due to his subsequent belief Michael Schumacher would have won the championship without significant competition.<ref name=\"LaStampaTodt\" /> Brawn reiterated his colleague's opinion to British magazine ''[[Autosport]]'' seven years later and stated the negative consequences for Formula One outweighed the positives, calling it \"on reflection ... it was a mistake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gptoday.net/en/news/f1/221987/austria-gp-2002-decision-was-a-mistake-brawn|title=Austria GP 2002 decision was a mistake \u2013 Brawn|last=Walsh|first=Fergal|date=6 February 2017|publisher=GPToday.net|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918081155/https://www.gptoday.net/en/news/f1/221987/austria-gp-2002-decision-was-a-mistake-brawn|archive-date=18 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Race classification===\nDrivers who finished in the top six points-scoring positions are denoted in '''bold''' and by a {{double dagger}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Laps|Laps completed}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Time/Retired\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Grid|Final grid position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 1\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Michael Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'''\n| 71\n| 1:33:51.562\n| 3\n|'''10{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 2\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} '''[[Rubens Barrichello]]'''\n|'''[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'''\n| 71\n|  +0.182\n| 1\n|'''6{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 6\n|{{flagicon|Colombia}} '''[[Juan Pablo Montoya]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 71\n|  +17.730\n| 4\n|'''4{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 5\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Ralf Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 71\n|  +18.448\n| 2\n|'''3{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 9\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} '''[[Giancarlo Fisichella]]'''\n|'''[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]'''\n| 71\n|  +49.965\n| 15\n|'''2{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 3\n|{{flagicon|UK}} '''[[David Coulthard]]'''\n|'''[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]'''\n| 71\n|  +50.672\n| 8\n|'''1{{double dagger}}'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 15\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n|[[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 71\n|  +51.229\n| 13\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 24\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n|[[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 71\n|  +1:09.425\n| 10\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 25\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Allan McNish]]\n|[[Toyota Racing (Formula One team)|Toyota]]\n| 71\n|  +1:09.718\n| 14\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 11\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 70\n| Engine\n| 17\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 20\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 11\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 23\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Mark Webber]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 21\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 14\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n|[[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| 44\n| Fuel pressure\n| 16\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 22\n|{{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[Alex Yoong]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Asiatech]]\n| 42\n| Engine\n| 22\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 16\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 38\n| Hydraulics\n| 20\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 7\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 27\n| Collision\n| 5\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 10\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Takuma Sato]]\n|[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 26\n| Collision\n| 18\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 12\n|{{flagicon|France}} [[Olivier Panis]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 22\n| Engine\n| 9\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 8\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Felipe Massa]]\n|[[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 7\n| Suspension\n| 7\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 4\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| 5\n| Engine\n| 6\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 21\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Enrique Bernoldi]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 2\n| Collision\n| 12\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 17\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 0\n| Throttle\n| 19\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref name=GPCOMRace/>''}}}}\n|}\n\n==Championship standings after the race==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \u2013/+\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 54\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Juan Pablo Montoya]]\n| align=\"right\"| 27\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 23\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1uparrow green.svg|10px]] 1\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| align=\"right\"| 12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1downarrow red.svg|10px]] 1\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| align=\"right\"| 10\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"2002points\" /><ref name=\"champ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/championnat.aspx|title=Austria 2002 \u2013 Championship|publisher=Stats F1|access-date=8 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321144247/https://www.statsf1.com/en/2002/autriche/championnat.aspx|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n;Constructors' Championship standings\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \u2013/+\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| align=\"right\"| 66\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| align=\"right\"| 50\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n| align=\"right\"| 14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"2002points\" /><ref name=\"champ\"/>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n*<small>'''Note''': Only the top five positions are included for both sets of standings.</small>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* Official 2002 Austrian Grand Prix results from [http://www.fia.com/archive/F1/2002/006.html FIA website] and [http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2002/10/ Formula1 website].\n* Formula One Database > 2002 Austrian Grand Prix \u2013 Qualifying [http://www.f1db.com/exec/section/grandprix/action/result/id/20020512#race_startgrid]\n\n{{Commons category|2002 Austrian Grand Prix}}\n\n{{F1 race report\n| Name_of_race            = [[Austrian Grand Prix]]\n| Year_of_race            = 2002\n| Previous_race_in_season = [[2002 Spanish Grand Prix]]\n| Next_race_in_season     = [[2002 Monaco Grand Prix]]\n| Previous_year's_race    = [[2001 Austrian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_year's_race        = [[2003 Austrian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n\n{{F1GP 00-09}}\n{{Portal bar|Austria|Formula One|Sports}}\n\n{{coord|47|13|11|N|14|45|53|E|source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2002 Formula One races|Austrian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:2002 in Austrian sport|Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:Austrian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:May 2002 sports events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "MWright96", "label": "safe", "comment": "GA fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_Austrian_Grand_Prix"}
{"title_page": "Kurmi", "text_new": "{{short description|Hindu agricultural caste of India}}\n{{About|the Hindu agricultural community|the people of Greater Jharkhand|Kudumi Mahato|the district in Nigeria|Kurmi, Nigeria}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Kurmi''' is a Hindu cultivator [[caste]] of the eastern [[Gangetic plain]] in northern India.<ref name=\"bayly-p41\" /><ref name=\"Bapu2013\">{{citation|last=Bapu|first=Prabhu|title=Hindu Mahasabha in Colonial North India, 1915-1930: Constructing Nation and History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iUFalxUFFWkC&pg=PR14|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-67165-1|pages=xiv\u2013}}  Quote: \"Kurmi: a peasant caste of the eastern Gangetic plain.\"</ref><ref name=\"Gupta2002\">{{citation|last=Gupta|first=C.|title=Sexuality, Obscenity and Community: Women, Muslims, and the Hindu Public in Colonial India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J0KEDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA340|date=30 May 2002|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-10819-6|pages=340\u2013}} Quote: \"Kurmi: a peasant caste of the eastern Gangetic plain.\"</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThere are several late-19th century theories of the etymology of ''Kurmi''. According to [[Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya]] (1896), the word may be derived from an Indian tribal language, or be a [[Sanskrit]] compound term ''krishi karmi'', \"agriculturalist.\"<ref name=\"Bhattacharya1896\">{{cite book|author=Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya|title=Hindu castes and sects: an exposition of the origin of the Hindu caste system and the bearing of the sects towards each other and towards other religious systems / Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya|url=https://archive.org/details/hinducastesands00bhatgoog|year=1896|publisher=Thacker, Spink|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hinducastesands00bhatgoog/page/n20 270]\u2013}}</ref> A theory of [[Gustav Salomon Oppert]] (1893) holds that it may be derived from ''k\u1e5b\u1e63mi'', meaning \"ploughman\".<ref name=\"Oppert1978\">{{cite book|author=Gustav Salomon Oppert|title=On the original inhabitants of Bharatavar\u1e63a or India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kDzXAAAAMAAJ|date=February 1978|publisher=Arno Press}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Eighteenth and nineteenth centuries===\nRecords from the time indicate that within western [[Bihar]], the Kurmis had cultivated an alliance with the ruling [[Ujjainiya]] [[Rajput]]s. Many leaders of the Kurmi community fought side by side with the Ujjainiya king, Kunwar Dhir when he rebelled against the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] in 1712. Among the recorded Kurmi community leaders who joined his revolt were Nima Seema Rawat and Dheka Rawat.<ref name=\"Gopal2017\">{{cite book|author=Surendra Gopal|title=Mapping Bihar: From Medieval to Modern Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCZFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT313|date=22 December 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-03416-6|page=313}}</ref>\n\nWith the continued waning of [[Mughal empire|Mughal rule]] in the early 18th century, the [[Indian subcontinent]]'s hinterland dwellers, many of whom were armed and nomadic, began to appear more frequently in settled areas and interact with townspeople and agriculturists.<ref name=bayly-p41>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=41|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Many new rulers of the 18th century came from such nomadic backgrounds.<ref name=bayly-p41/> The effect of this interaction on India's social organization lasted well into the colonial period. During much of this time, non-elite tillers and pastoralists, such as the Kurmi, were part of a social spectrum that blended only indistinctly into the elite landowning classes at one end, and the menial or ritually polluting classes at the other.<ref name=bayly-p41/>\n\nThe Kurmi were famed as market gardeners.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p478\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=478}}</ref>  In western and northern [[Awadh]], for example, for much of the eighteenth century, the Muslim gentry offered the Kurmi highly discounted rental rates for clearing the jungle and cultivating it.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=101}}</ref>  Once the land had been brought stably under the plough, however, the land rent was usually raised to 30 to 80 per cent above the going rate.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/> Although British revenue officials later ascribed the high rent to the prejudice among the elite rural castes against handling the plough, the main reason was the greater productivity of the Kurmi, whose success lay in superior manuring.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/>  According to historian [[Christopher Bayly]], <blockquote> Whereas the majority of cultivators manured only the lands immediately around the village and used these lands for growing food grains, Kurmis avoided using animal dung for fuel and manured the poorer lands farther from the village (the ''manjha''). They were able, therefore, to grow valuable market crops such as potatoes, melons and tobacco immediately around the village, sow fine grains in the ''manjha'', and restrict the poor millet subsistence crops to the periphery. A network of ''ganjs'' (fixed rural markets) and Kurmi or Kacchi settlements could transform a local economy within a year or two.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/></blockquote>\n\nCross-cultural influences were felt also.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=49}}</ref>  Hindu tillers worshipped at Muslim shrines in the small towns founded by their Muslim overlords.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\"/>  The Hindu Kurmis of [[Chunar]] and [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]], for instance, took up the Muslim custom of [[Cousin marriage|marrying first cousins]] and of burying their dead.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\"/> In some regions, the Kurmis' success as tillers led to land ownership, and to avowals of high status, as noted, for examples, by [[Francis Buchanan]] in the early 19th century among the [[Ayodhya]] Kurmis of the Awadh.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p85\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/85 85]}}</ref>  Earlier, in the late eighteenth century, when [[Asaf-Ud-Dowlah]], the fourth [[Nawab of Awadh]], attempted to grant the kshatriya title of [[Raja]] to a group of influential landed Ayodhya Kurmis, he was thwarted by a united opposition of [[Rajput]]s, who were themselves (as described by Buchanan), \"a group of newcomers to the court, who had been peasant soldiers only a few years before ...\"<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p85\"/>  According to historian William Pinch:  <blockquote> Rajputs of Awadh, who along with [[brahmin|brahman]]s constituted the main beneficiaries of what historian Richard Barnett characterizes as \"Asaf's permissive program of social mobility,\" were not willing to let that mobility reach beyond certain arbitrary socio-cultural boundaries. ... The divergent claims to status in the nineteenth century (and earlier) illustrate the point that for non-Muslims, while varna was generally accepted as the basis for identity, on the whole little agreement prevailed with respect to the place of the individual and the jati within a varna hierarchy.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-pp86-87\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/86 86]\u201387}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough the free peasant farm was the mainstay of farming in many parts of north India in the 18th century, in some regions, a combination of climatic, political, and demographic factors led to the increased dependence of peasant cultivators such as the Kurmi.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|pages=47\u201348}}</ref>  In the Benares division, which had come under the revenue purview of the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] in 1779, the [[Chalisa famine]] of 1783 and the relentless revenue demand from the Company reduced the status of many Kurmi cultivators.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\"/>  A British revenue agent wrote in 1790, \"It unfortunately happened that during the famine aforesaid a great proportion of the Kurmis, Kacchis and Koeris were in this district as well as in others supplanted by Brahmans ... \" and bemoaned the loss of agricultural revenue in part due to, \"this unfavourable mutation amongst the cultivators ...\"<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\"/>\n\nIn the first half of the nineteenth century, economic pressures on the large landowning classes increased noticeably.<ref name=bayly-p200-201>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=200\u2013201|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  The prices of agricultural lands fell at the same time that the East India Company, after acquiring the [[Ceded and Conquered Provinces]] (later the [[North-Western Provinces]]) in 1805, began to press landowners for more [[Company rule in India#Revenue collection|land revenue]].<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  The annexation of Awadh in 1856 created more fear and discontent among the landed elite, and may have contributed to the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]].<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  Economic pressures also opened marginal areas to intensive agriculture and turned the fortunes of the non-elite peasants, such as the Kurmi, who worked them.<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  After the rebellion, the landowning classes, defeated but still pressed economically in the new [[British Raj]], attempted to treat their tenants and labourers as people of lowly birth and to demand unpaid labour from them.<ref name=bayly-p204-205>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=204\u2013205|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  According to historical anthropologist [[Susan Bayly]], <blockquote> In some instances these were attempts to stave off decline by reinvigorating or intensifying existing forms of customary service. Elsewhere these were wholly novel demands, many being imposed on 'clean' tillers and cattle-keepers like the Ram- and Krishna-loving Koeris, Kurmis and Ahirs ... In either case, these calls were buttressed with appeals to Sanskritic varna theory and Brahmanical caste convention. ... Kurmi and Goala/Ahir tillers who held tenancies from these 'squireens' found themselves being identified as Shudras, that is, people who were mandated to serve those of the superior Kshatriya and Brahman varnas.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/></blockquote>\n\nThe elite landowning classes, such as Rajputs and [[Bhumihar]]s, now sought to present themselves as flagbearers of the ancient Hindu tradition.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/>  At the same time, there was a proliferation of [[Brahmin|Brahmanical]] rituals in the daily life of the elite, a greater stress on pure bloodlines, more stringent conditions placed on matrimonial alliances, and, as noted by some social reformers of the day, an increase among the Rajputs of [[female infanticide]], a practice that had little history among the Kurmi.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/>\n<center>\n<div style=\"float:center; width:1000px;\">\n{{Gallery|width=200 |lines=4\n|File:India1909PrevailingRaces.JPG|The map of the prevailing \"races\" of India (now discredited) based on the 1901 Census of British India. The Kurmi are shown both in the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (UP) and the [[Central Provinces]].\n|File:Kurmi sowing.jpg|An \"ethnographic\" photograph from 1916 showing Kurmi farmers, both men and women, sowing a field\n|File:Kurmi threshing.jpg|Another ethnographic print from 1916 showing a Kurmi family employing its beasts of burden to thresh wheat\n|File:Kurmi winnowing.jpg|A third print from the same collection showing the Kurmi family winnowing\n}}\n</div>\n</center>\nThe second half of the nineteenth century also largely overlapped with the coming of age of ethnology\u2014interpreted then as the science of race\u2014in the study of societies the world over.<ref name=bayly-p126-127>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=126\u2013127|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Although later to be discredited, the methods of this discipline were eagerly absorbed and adopted in British India, as were those of the emerging science of anthropology.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/>  Driven in part by the intellectual ferment of the discipline and in part by the political compulsions in both Britain and India, two dominant views of caste emerged among the administrator-scholars of the day.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/>  According to Susan Bayly: <blockquote> Those like [[William Wilson Hunter|(Sir William) Hunter]], as well as the key figures of [[Herbert Hope Risley|H. H. Risley]] (1851\u20131911) and his prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Edgar Thurston]], who were disciples of the French race theorist Topinard and his European followers, subsumed discussions of caste into theories of biologically determined race essences, ... Their great rivals were the material or occupational theorists led by the ethnographer and folklorist [[William Crooke]] (1848\u20131923), author of one of the most widely read provincial ''Castes and Tribes'' surveys, and such other influential scholar-officials as [[Denzil Ibbetson]] and E. A. H. Blunt.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/></blockquote>\n\nSeeing caste as a fundamental force in Indian life, Risley, especially, influenced official views as expressed in both the Censuses of British India and the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer]] brought out by Hunter.<ref name=bayly-p129-132>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=129\u2013132|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Risley is best known for the now discounted attribution of all differences in caste to varying proportions of seven racial types which included \"Dravidian,\" \"Aryo-Dravidian,\" and \"Indo-Aryan\". The Kurmi fell into two such categories. In the ethnological map of India published in the 1909 Imperial Gazetteer of India and based on the 1901 Census supervised by Risley, the Kurmi of the United Provinces were classified as \"Aryo-Dravidian,\" whereas the Kurmi of the [[Central Provinces]] were counted among \"Dravidians\".<ref name=bayly-p129-132/> In the 1901 Census of India, the category of [[varna]], the four-fold graded system, was included in the official classification of caste,<ref name=\"RudolphRudolph1984\">{{cite book|last1=Rudolph|first1=Lloyd I.|last2=Rudolph|first2=Susanne Hoeber|title=The Modernity of Tradition: Political Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7guY1ut-0lwC|year=1984|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-73137-7|page=116}}</ref> the only time this was the case.{{efn|Although influential, Risley's attempt did not achieve the end which he sought: people were unable to determine in which group they should classify themselves, the localised system he adopted could not be transposed onto the national stage, and some groups took advantage of the situation deliberately to seek reclassification and therefore satisfy their aspirations. L. I. and S. H. Rudolph have commented that \"Risley's work, as a scientific effort, seemed based on mistaken premises. Varna was not a behavioral concept.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rudolph|first1=Lloyd I.|last2=Rudolph|first2=Susanne Hoeber|title=The Modernity of Tradition: Political Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7guY1ut-0lwC|year=1984|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-73137-7|page=117}}</ref>}} In the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (UP), the Kurmi were classified under \"Class VIII: Castes from whom some of the twice-born would take water and ''pakki'' (food cooked with [[ghee]]),<ref name=\"BluntBlunt1931\">Quote: \"The Hindu draws a distinction between ''kachcha'' food, which is cooked in water, and ''pakka'' food, which is cooked in ''[[ghee|ghi]]'' (clarified butter). This distinction depends on the principle that ''ghi'', like all products of the sacred cow protects from impurity ... and enables the Hindu to be less particular in the case of ''pakka'' than of ''kachcha'' food, and allows him to relax his restrictions accordingly.\" In {{cite book|last=Blunt|first=Sir Edward Arthur Henry|title=The caste system of northern India: with special reference to the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wb45AQAAIAAJ|year=1931|publisher=H. Milford, Oxford University Press|page=89}}</ref> without question;\" whereas, in [[Bihar]], they were listed under: \"Class III, Clean Sudra, Subclass (a).\"<ref name=\"CommissionerRisley1903\">{{cite book|author1=India. Census Commissioner|last2=Risley|first2=Sir Herbert Hope|title=Census of India, 1901: Volume I. India. Ethnographic appendices, being the data upon which the caste chapter of the Report is based|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8MsiAQAAMAAJ|year=1903|publisher=Office of the Supt. of Govt. Printing, India|location=Calcutta|pages=56\u201357}}</ref>{{efn|[[Census of India prior to independence|Indian censuses of the British Raj period]] are not usually considered to be particularly reliable except for overall population figures. Those for some areas of the country could be more reliable than others.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fq1MVCSqu4sC |page=60 |title=The economic development of India |first=Vera Powell |last=Anstey |edition=Reprinted |publisher=Ayer Publishing |year=1977 |origyear=1931 |isbn=978-0-405-09775-1 |quote=... a vast army of enumerators are utilized, many of whom have a very limited understanding of what is required. Hence the Indian census provides at times more food for merriment than is usually connected with statistical compilations.}}\n{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-2RP04HHopkC |pages=104\u2013116 |title=The census administration under the raj and after |first=Shriram |last=Maheshwari |publisher=Concept Publishing Company |year=1996 |isbn=978-81-7022-585-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3fxvuxjJOsC |page=124 |title=Social Sciences: The Indian Scene |first=Yogesh |last=Atal |publisher=Abhinav Publications |year=2003 |isbn=978-81-7017-042-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wBUot0-CIYUC |title=Children of Colonialism: Anglo-Indians in a Postcolonial World |first=Lionel |last=Caplan |publisher=Berg |year=2003 |pages=66\u201367 |isbn=978-1-85973-632-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Qy14yBg8Q8C |page=290 |title=Elements Of Demography |last=Sinha |first=E. Zacharia |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=978-81-7764-044-1|date=12 April 1984 }}</ref>}}  According to William Pinch, \"Risley's hierarchy (for United Provinces) was far more elaborate than that for Bihar, suggesting that contending claims of social respectability may have been more deeply entrenched in the western half of the Gangetic Plain.\"<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p84\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/84 84]}}</ref>\n\nIn the writings of the occupational theorists, the Kurmis and the Jats came to be extolled for their yeoman-like purposefulness, tirelessness, and thrift, all of which, according to writers such as Crooke, Ibbetson, and Blunt had been largely abandoned by the landed elite.<ref name=bayly-p212>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=212|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Crooke wrote about the Kurmi in 1897: <blockquote> They are about the most industrious and hard-working agricultural tribe in the Province. The industry of his wife has passed into a proverb: <br>\n''Bhali j\u00e2t Kurmin, khurpi h\u00e2t,'' <br>\n''Khet nir\u00e2w\u00ea apan p\u00ee k\u00ea s\u00e2th.'' <br>\n\"A good lot is the Kurmi woman; she takes her spud and weeds the field with her lord.\"<ref name=\"Crooke1896-p353-354\">{{cite book|last=Crooke|first=William|title=The tribes and castes of the North-western Provinces and Oudh, Volume III|url=https://archive.org/details/tribesandcastes01croogoog|year=1896|publisher=Office of the superintendent of government printing|pages=[https://archive.org/details/tribesandcastes01croogoog/page/n374 353]\u2013354}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Susan Bayly, <blockquote> By the mid-nineteenth century, influential revenue specialists were reporting that they could tell the caste of a landed man by simply glancing at his crops. In the north, these observers claimed, a field of 'second-rate barley' would belong to a Rajput or Brahman who took pride in shunning the plough and secluding his womenfolk. Such a man was to be blamed for his own decline, fecklessly mortgaging and then selling off his lands to maintain his unproductive dependents. By the same logic, a flourishing field of wheat would belong to a non-twice-born tiller, wheat being a crop requiring skill and enterprise on the part of the cultivator. These, said such commentators as Denzil Ibbetson and E. A. H. Blunt, were the qualities of the non-patrician 'peasant'&nbsp;\u2013 the thrifty Jat or canny Kurmi in upper India, .... Similar virtues would be found among the smaller market-gardening populations, these being the people known as Keoris in Hindustan, ....<ref name=bayly-p212/></blockquote>\n\n===Twentieth century===\nAs the economic pressures on the patrician landed groups continued through the remainder of the nineteenth century and into the early twentieth, there were increasing demands for unpaid labour directed at the Kurmi and other non-elite cultivators.<ref name=bayly-p205-206>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=205\u2013206|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  The landed elites' demands were couched in avowals of their ancient rights as \"twice-born\" landowners and of the Kurmi's alleged lowly, even servile, status, which required them to serve.<ref name=bayly-p205-206/>  At times encouraged by sympathetic British officials and at other times carried by the groundswell of egalitarian sentiment being espoused then by the devotional [[Vaishnavism|Vaishnava]] movements, especially those based on [[Tulsidas]]'s ''[[Ramcharitmanas]]'', the Kurmi largely resisted these demands.<ref name=bayly-p207>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=207|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Their resistance, however, did not take the form of denial of caste or of caste-based imposition, but rather of disagreement about where they stood in the caste ranking.<ref name=bayly-p205-206/>  A noteworthy attribute of the resulting Kurmi-kshatriya movement was the leadership provided by educated Kurmis who were now filling the lower and middle levels of government jobs.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p84\"/> According to William Pinch: <blockquote> The mantle of leadership in this phase befell the well-connected Ramdin Sinha, a government forester who had gained notoriety by resigning from his official post to protest a provincial circular of 1894 that included Kurmis as a \"depressed community\" and barred them therefore from recruitment into the police service. The governor\u2019s office was flooded with letters from an outraged Kurmi-kshatriya public and was soon obliged to rescind the allegation in an 1896 communique to the police department \"His Honor [the governor] is ... of the opinion that Kurmis constitute a respectable community which he would be reluctant to exclude from Government service.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/89 89]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe first Kurmi caste association had been formed in 1894 at [[Lucknow]] to protest against the police recruitment policy. This was followed by an organisation in Awadh that sought to draw other communities&nbsp;\u2014 such as the [[Patidar]]s, [[Maratha]]s, [[Kapu]]s, [[Reddy]]s and [[Naidu]]s&nbsp;\u2014 under the umbrella of the Kurmi name. This body then campaigned for Kurmis to classify themselves as Kshatriya in the 1901 census and, in 1910, led to the formation of the [[All India Kurmi Kshatriya Mahasabha]].<ref name=Jaffrelot2003p197>{{cite book |title=India's silent revolution: the rise of the lower castes in North India |page=197 |first=Christophe |last=Jaffrelot |publisher=C. Hurst & Co. |location=London |year=2003 |isbn=978-1-85065-670-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OAkW94DtUMAC}}</ref> Simultaneously, newly constituted farmers' unions, or ''Kisan Sabhas''\u2014composed of cultivators and pastoralists, many of whom were Kurmi, Ahir, and [[Yadav]] ([[Gavli|Goala]]), and inspired by Hindu mendicants, such as [[Baba Ram Chandra]] and [[Sahajanand Saraswati|Swami Sahajanand Saraswati]]\u2014denounced the Brahman and Rajput landlords as ineffective and their morality as false.<ref name=bayly-p208-209>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=208\u2013209|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  In the rural Ganges valley of Bihar and Eastern United Provinces, the [[Bhakti]] cults of [[Rama]], the incorruptible Kshatriya god-king of Hindu tradition, and [[Krishna]], the divine cowherd of Gokul, had long been entrenched among the Kurmi and Ahir.<ref name=bayly-p208-209/>  The leaders of the ''Kisan Sabhas'' urged their Kurmi and Ahir followers to lay claim to the Kshatriya mantle.<ref name=bayly-p208-209/>  Promoting what was advertised as soldierly manliness, the ''Kisan Sabhas'' agitated for the entry of non-elite farmers into the British Indian army during World War I; they formed [[cow protection movement|cow protection societies]]; they asked their members to wear the [[sacred thread]] of the [[twice-born]], and, in contrast to the Kurmis own traditions, to sequester their women in the manner of Rajputs and Brahmins.<ref name=bayly-p209-210>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=209\u2013210|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>\n\nIn 1930, the Kurmis of Bihar joined with the Yadav and [[Koeri]] agriculturalists to enter local elections. They lost badly but in 1934 the three communities formed the [[Triveni Sangh]] political party, which allegedly had a million dues-paying members by 1936. However, the organisation was hobbled by competition from the Congress-backed [[Backward Class]] Federation, which was formed around the same time, and by co-option of community leaders by the Congress party. The Triveni Sangh suffered badly in the 1937 elections, although it did win in some areas. The organisation also suffered from caste rivalries, notably the superior organisational ability of the higher castes who opposed it, as well as the inability of the Yadavs to renounce their belief that they were natural leaders and that the Kurmi were somehow inferior. Similar problems beset a later planned caste union, the ''Raghav Samaj'', with the Koeris.<ref name=Jaffrelot2003p197/>\n\nAgain in the 1970s, the India Kurmi Kshatriya Sabha attempted to bring the Koeris under their wing, but disunity troubled this alliance.<ref>{{cite news |first=Akshaya |last=Mukul |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/young-india-votes/news/Mighty-Kurmis-of-Bihar/articleshow/555124.cms |title=Mighty Kurmis of Bihar |work=The Times of India |date=12 March 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Fernandes to head Janata Dal (United) | url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/2003/10/31/stories/2003103104371100.htm | author=Gargi Parsai | date=31 October 2003 | newspaper=The Hindu | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65xylZw3k?url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/2003/10/31/stories/2003103104371100.htm | archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nMany private caste-based armies surfaced in Bihar between the 1970s and 1990s, largely influenced by landlord farmers reacting to the growing influence of left extremist groups. Among these was the [[Bhumi Sena]], the membership of which was drawn mainly from youths who had a Kurmi origin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/static/html/fl1919/19190330.htm|title=End of a terror trail|work=Frontline|date=27 September 2002|first=Kalyan |last=Chaudhuri|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC&pg=PA54|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|last=Bayly|first=Susan|authorlink=Susan Bayly|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-52179-842-6|page=347}}</ref> Bhumi Sena was much feared in the Patna region and also had influence in the districts of Nalanda, Jehanabad and Gaya.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/a-lasting-signature-on-bihar-s-most-violent-years/957421/2|title=A lasting signature on Bihar's most violent years |work=Indian Express|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Patidar]]\n*[[Patel]]\n*[[Kudumbar]]\n*[[Kochaisa]]\n*[[Lava (Ramayana)]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Bhattacharya|first1=Ranjit Kumar|last2=Das|first2=Nava Kishor|author3=Anthropological Survey of India|title=Anthropology of weaker sections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pjVdJMBeXU8C|accessdate=1 August 2011|date=1 January 1993|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=978-81-7022-491-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gooptu|first=Nandini|title=The politics of the urban poor in early twentieth-century India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRrbSzEvNCMC|accessdate=1 August 2011|date=1 July 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44366-1}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Singer|first1=Milton (editor)|last2=Cohn|first2=Bernard S. (editor)|title=Structure and Change in Indian Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC|accessdate=1 August 2011|year=2007|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-202-36138-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Yang|first=Anand A.|title=The limited Raj: agrarian relations in colonial India, Saran District, 1793-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ck4jmD7H34UC|accessdate=1 August 2011|year=1989|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-05711-1}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oDeFAAAAIAAJ|title=Daughters of The Earth|last=Jassal|first=Smita Tewari|publisher=Technical Publications|year=2001|isbn=978-8-17304-375-8|page=57}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCp0JQcFik8C&lpg=PA78&dq=awadhiya&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Anthropological Methods for Communication Research: Experiences and Encounters During SITE|last=Viswanath|first=Sashikala|date=1985|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|language=en}}\n\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Bangladesh}}\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Agricultural castes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hindu agricultural caste of India}}\n{{About|the Hindu agricultural community|the people of Greater Jharkhand|Kudumi Mahato|the district in Nigeria|Kurmi, Nigeria}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Kurmi''' is a Hindu cultivator [[caste]] of the eastern [[Gangetic plain]] in northern India.<ref name=\"Bayly2001\">{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC&pg=PA385|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6|page=385}} Quote: \"Glossary: Kurmi: caste title of non-elite 'peasants' in the eastern Gangetic plain.\"</ref><ref name=\"Bapu2013\">{{citation|last=Bapu|first=Prabhu|title=Hindu Mahasabha in Colonial North India, 1915-1930: Constructing Nation and History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iUFalxUFFWkC&pg=PR14|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-67165-1|pages=xiv\u2013}}  Quote: \"Kurmi: a peasant caste of the eastern Gangetic plain.\"</ref><ref name=\"Gupta2002\">{{citation|last=Gupta|first=C.|title=Sexuality, Obscenity and Community: Women, Muslims, and the Hindu Public in Colonial India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J0KEDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA340|date=30 May 2002|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-230-10819-6|pages=340\u2013}} Quote: \"Kurmi: a peasant caste of the eastern Gangetic plain.\"</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThere are several late-19th century theories of the etymology of ''Kurmi''. According to [[Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya]] (1896), the word may be derived from an Indian tribal language, or be a [[Sanskrit]] compound term ''krishi karmi'', \"agriculturalist.\"<ref name=\"Bhattacharya1896\">{{cite book|author=Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya|title=Hindu castes and sects: an exposition of the origin of the Hindu caste system and the bearing of the sects towards each other and towards other religious systems / Jogendra Nath Bhattacharya|url=https://archive.org/details/hinducastesands00bhatgoog|year=1896|publisher=Thacker, Spink|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hinducastesands00bhatgoog/page/n20 270]\u2013}}</ref> A theory of [[Gustav Salomon Oppert]] (1893) holds that it may be derived from ''k\u1e5b\u1e63mi'', meaning \"ploughman\".<ref name=\"Oppert1978\">{{cite book|author=Gustav Salomon Oppert|title=On the original inhabitants of Bharatavar\u1e63a or India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kDzXAAAAMAAJ|date=February 1978|publisher=Arno Press}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Eighteenth and nineteenth centuries===\nRecords from the time indicate that within western [[Bihar]], the Kurmis had cultivated an alliance with the ruling [[Ujjainiya]] [[Rajput]]s. Many leaders of the Kurmi community fought side by side with the Ujjainiya king, Kunwar Dhir when he rebelled against the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] in 1712. Among the recorded Kurmi community leaders who joined his revolt were Nima Seema Rawat and Dheka Rawat.<ref name=\"Gopal2017\">{{cite book|author=Surendra Gopal|title=Mapping Bihar: From Medieval to Modern Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCZFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT313|date=22 December 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-03416-6|page=313}}</ref>\n\nWith the continued waning of [[Mughal empire|Mughal rule]] in the early 18th century, the [[Indian subcontinent]]'s hinterland dwellers, many of whom were armed and nomadic, began to appear more frequently in settled areas and interact with townspeople and agriculturists.<ref name=bayly-p41>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=41|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Many new rulers of the 18th century came from such nomadic backgrounds.<ref name=bayly-p41/> The effect of this interaction on India's social organization lasted well into the colonial period. During much of this time, non-elite tillers and pastoralists, such as the Kurmi, were part of a social spectrum that blended only indistinctly into the elite landowning classes at one end, and the menial or ritually polluting classes at the other.<ref name=bayly-p41/>\n\nThe Kurmi were famed as market gardeners.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p478\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=478}}</ref>  In western and northern [[Awadh]], for example, for much of the eighteenth century, the Muslim gentry offered the Kurmi highly discounted rental rates for clearing the jungle and cultivating it.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=101}}</ref>  Once the land had been brought stably under the plough, however, the land rent was usually raised to 30 to 80 per cent above the going rate.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/> Although British revenue officials later ascribed the high rent to the prejudice among the elite rural castes against handling the plough, the main reason was the greater productivity of the Kurmi, whose success lay in superior manuring.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/>  According to historian [[Christopher Bayly]], <blockquote> Whereas the majority of cultivators manured only the lands immediately around the village and used these lands for growing food grains, Kurmis avoided using animal dung for fuel and manured the poorer lands farther from the village (the ''manjha''). They were able, therefore, to grow valuable market crops such as potatoes, melons and tobacco immediately around the village, sow fine grains in the ''manjha'', and restrict the poor millet subsistence crops to the periphery. A network of ''ganjs'' (fixed rural markets) and Kurmi or Kacchi settlements could transform a local economy within a year or two.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p101\"/></blockquote>\n\nCross-cultural influences were felt also.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|page=49}}</ref>  Hindu tillers worshipped at Muslim shrines in the small towns founded by their Muslim overlords.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\"/>  The Hindu Kurmis of [[Chunar]] and [[Jaunpur, Uttar Pradesh|Jaunpur]], for instance, took up the Muslim custom of [[Cousin marriage|marrying first cousins]] and of burying their dead.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-p49\"/> In some regions, the Kurmis' success as tillers led to land ownership, and to avowals of high status, as noted, for examples, by [[Francis Buchanan]] in the early 19th century among the [[Ayodhya]] Kurmis of the Awadh.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p85\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/85 85]}}</ref>  Earlier, in the late eighteenth century, when [[Asaf-Ud-Dowlah]], the fourth [[Nawab of Awadh]], attempted to grant the kshatriya title of [[Raja]] to a group of influential landed Ayodhya Kurmis, he was thwarted by a united opposition of [[Rajput]]s, who were themselves (as described by Buchanan), \"a group of newcomers to the court, who had been peasant soldiers only a few years before ...\"<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p85\"/>  According to historian William Pinch:  <blockquote> Rajputs of Awadh, who along with [[brahmin|brahman]]s constituted the main beneficiaries of what historian Richard Barnett characterizes as \"Asaf's permissive program of social mobility,\" were not willing to let that mobility reach beyond certain arbitrary socio-cultural boundaries. ... The divergent claims to status in the nineteenth century (and earlier) illustrate the point that for non-Muslims, while varna was generally accepted as the basis for identity, on the whole little agreement prevailed with respect to the place of the individual and the jati within a varna hierarchy.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-pp86-87\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/86 86]\u201387}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAlthough the free peasant farm was the mainstay of farming in many parts of north India in the 18th century, in some regions, a combination of climatic, political, and demographic factors led to the increased dependence of peasant cultivators such as the Kurmi.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\">{{cite book|last=Bayly|first=C. A.|authorlink=Christopher Bayly|title=Rulers, Townsmen and Bazaars: North Indian Society in the Age of British Expansion, 1770-1870|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xfo3AAAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-31054-3|pages=47\u201348}}</ref>  In the Benares division, which had come under the revenue purview of the [[East India Company|British East India Company]] in 1779, the [[Chalisa famine]] of 1783 and the relentless revenue demand from the Company reduced the status of many Kurmi cultivators.<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\"/>  A British revenue agent wrote in 1790, \"It unfortunately happened that during the famine aforesaid a great proportion of the Kurmis, Kacchis and Koeris were in this district as well as in others supplanted by Brahmans ... \" and bemoaned the loss of agricultural revenue in part due to, \"this unfavourable mutation amongst the cultivators ...\"<ref name=\"Bayly1988-pp47-48\"/>\n\nIn the first half of the nineteenth century, economic pressures on the large landowning classes increased noticeably.<ref name=bayly-p200-201>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=200\u2013201|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  The prices of agricultural lands fell at the same time that the East India Company, after acquiring the [[Ceded and Conquered Provinces]] (later the [[North-Western Provinces]]) in 1805, began to press landowners for more [[Company rule in India#Revenue collection|land revenue]].<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  The annexation of Awadh in 1856 created more fear and discontent among the landed elite, and may have contributed to the [[Indian rebellion of 1857]].<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  Economic pressures also opened marginal areas to intensive agriculture and turned the fortunes of the non-elite peasants, such as the Kurmi, who worked them.<ref name=bayly-p200-201/>  After the rebellion, the landowning classes, defeated but still pressed economically in the new [[British Raj]], attempted to treat their tenants and labourers as people of lowly birth and to demand unpaid labour from them.<ref name=bayly-p204-205>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=204\u2013205|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  According to historical anthropologist [[Susan Bayly]], <blockquote> In some instances these were attempts to stave off decline by reinvigorating or intensifying existing forms of customary service. Elsewhere these were wholly novel demands, many being imposed on 'clean' tillers and cattle-keepers like the Ram- and Krishna-loving Koeris, Kurmis and Ahirs ... In either case, these calls were buttressed with appeals to Sanskritic varna theory and Brahmanical caste convention. ... Kurmi and Goala/Ahir tillers who held tenancies from these 'squireens' found themselves being identified as Shudras, that is, people who were mandated to serve those of the superior Kshatriya and Brahman varnas.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/></blockquote>\n\nThe elite landowning classes, such as Rajputs and [[Bhumihar]]s, now sought to present themselves as flagbearers of the ancient Hindu tradition.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/>  At the same time, there was a proliferation of [[Brahmin|Brahmanical]] rituals in the daily life of the elite, a greater stress on pure bloodlines, more stringent conditions placed on matrimonial alliances, and, as noted by some social reformers of the day, an increase among the Rajputs of [[female infanticide]], a practice that had little history among the Kurmi.<ref name=bayly-p204-205/>\n<center>\n<div style=\"float:center; width:1000px;\">\n{{Gallery|width=200 |lines=4\n|File:India1909PrevailingRaces.JPG|The map of the prevailing \"races\" of India (now discredited) based on the 1901 Census of British India. The Kurmi are shown both in the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (UP) and the [[Central Provinces]].\n|File:Kurmi sowing.jpg|An \"ethnographic\" photograph from 1916 showing Kurmi farmers, both men and women, sowing a field\n|File:Kurmi threshing.jpg|Another ethnographic print from 1916 showing a Kurmi family employing its beasts of burden to thresh wheat\n|File:Kurmi winnowing.jpg|A third print from the same collection showing the Kurmi family winnowing\n}}\n</div>\n</center>\nThe second half of the nineteenth century also largely overlapped with the coming of age of ethnology\u2014interpreted then as the science of race\u2014in the study of societies the world over.<ref name=bayly-p126-127>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=126\u2013127|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Although later to be discredited, the methods of this discipline were eagerly absorbed and adopted in British India, as were those of the emerging science of anthropology.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/>  Driven in part by the intellectual ferment of the discipline and in part by the political compulsions in both Britain and India, two dominant views of caste emerged among the administrator-scholars of the day.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/>  According to Susan Bayly: <blockquote> Those like [[William Wilson Hunter|(Sir William) Hunter]], as well as the key figures of [[Herbert Hope Risley|H. H. Risley]] (1851\u20131911) and his prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Edgar Thurston]], who were disciples of the French race theorist Topinard and his European followers, subsumed discussions of caste into theories of biologically determined race essences, ... Their great rivals were the material or occupational theorists led by the ethnographer and folklorist [[William Crooke]] (1848\u20131923), author of one of the most widely read provincial ''Castes and Tribes'' surveys, and such other influential scholar-officials as [[Denzil Ibbetson]] and E. A. H. Blunt.<ref name=bayly-p126-127/></blockquote>\n\nSeeing caste as a fundamental force in Indian life, Risley, especially, influenced official views as expressed in both the Censuses of British India and the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India|Imperial Gazetteer]] brought out by Hunter.<ref name=bayly-p129-132>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=129\u2013132|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Risley is best known for the now discounted attribution of all differences in caste to varying proportions of seven racial types which included \"Dravidian,\" \"Aryo-Dravidian,\" and \"Indo-Aryan\". The Kurmi fell into two such categories. In the ethnological map of India published in the 1909 Imperial Gazetteer of India and based on the 1901 Census supervised by Risley, the Kurmi of the United Provinces were classified as \"Aryo-Dravidian,\" whereas the Kurmi of the [[Central Provinces]] were counted among \"Dravidians\".<ref name=bayly-p129-132/> In the 1901 Census of India, the category of [[varna]], the four-fold graded system, was included in the official classification of caste,<ref name=\"RudolphRudolph1984\">{{cite book|last1=Rudolph|first1=Lloyd I.|last2=Rudolph|first2=Susanne Hoeber|title=The Modernity of Tradition: Political Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7guY1ut-0lwC|year=1984|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-73137-7|page=116}}</ref> the only time this was the case.{{efn|Although influential, Risley's attempt did not achieve the end which he sought: people were unable to determine in which group they should classify themselves, the localised system he adopted could not be transposed onto the national stage, and some groups took advantage of the situation deliberately to seek reclassification and therefore satisfy their aspirations. L. I. and S. H. Rudolph have commented that \"Risley's work, as a scientific effort, seemed based on mistaken premises. Varna was not a behavioral concept.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rudolph|first1=Lloyd I.|last2=Rudolph|first2=Susanne Hoeber|title=The Modernity of Tradition: Political Development in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7guY1ut-0lwC|year=1984|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-73137-7|page=117}}</ref>}} In the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] (UP), the Kurmi were classified under \"Class VIII: Castes from whom some of the twice-born would take water and ''pakki'' (food cooked with [[ghee]]),<ref name=\"BluntBlunt1931\">Quote: \"The Hindu draws a distinction between ''kachcha'' food, which is cooked in water, and ''pakka'' food, which is cooked in ''[[ghee|ghi]]'' (clarified butter). This distinction depends on the principle that ''ghi'', like all products of the sacred cow protects from impurity ... and enables the Hindu to be less particular in the case of ''pakka'' than of ''kachcha'' food, and allows him to relax his restrictions accordingly.\" In {{cite book|last=Blunt|first=Sir Edward Arthur Henry|title=The caste system of northern India: with special reference to the United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wb45AQAAIAAJ|year=1931|publisher=H. Milford, Oxford University Press|page=89}}</ref> without question;\" whereas, in [[Bihar]], they were listed under: \"Class III, Clean Sudra, Subclass (a).\"<ref name=\"CommissionerRisley1903\">{{cite book|author1=India. Census Commissioner|last2=Risley|first2=Sir Herbert Hope|title=Census of India, 1901: Volume I. India. Ethnographic appendices, being the data upon which the caste chapter of the Report is based|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8MsiAQAAMAAJ|year=1903|publisher=Office of the Supt. of Govt. Printing, India|location=Calcutta|pages=56\u201357}}</ref>{{efn|[[Census of India prior to independence|Indian censuses of the British Raj period]] are not usually considered to be particularly reliable except for overall population figures. Those for some areas of the country could be more reliable than others.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fq1MVCSqu4sC |page=60 |title=The economic development of India |first=Vera Powell |last=Anstey |edition=Reprinted |publisher=Ayer Publishing |year=1977 |origyear=1931 |isbn=978-0-405-09775-1 |quote=... a vast army of enumerators are utilized, many of whom have a very limited understanding of what is required. Hence the Indian census provides at times more food for merriment than is usually connected with statistical compilations.}}\n{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-2RP04HHopkC |pages=104\u2013116 |title=The census administration under the raj and after |first=Shriram |last=Maheshwari |publisher=Concept Publishing Company |year=1996 |isbn=978-81-7022-585-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3fxvuxjJOsC |page=124 |title=Social Sciences: The Indian Scene |first=Yogesh |last=Atal |publisher=Abhinav Publications |year=2003 |isbn=978-81-7017-042-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wBUot0-CIYUC |title=Children of Colonialism: Anglo-Indians in a Postcolonial World |first=Lionel |last=Caplan |publisher=Berg |year=2003 |pages=66\u201367 |isbn=978-1-85973-632-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Qy14yBg8Q8C |page=290 |title=Elements Of Demography |last=Sinha |first=E. Zacharia |publisher=Allied Publishers |isbn=978-81-7764-044-1|date=12 April 1984 }}</ref>}}  According to William Pinch, \"Risley's hierarchy (for United Provinces) was far more elaborate than that for Bihar, suggesting that contending claims of social respectability may have been more deeply entrenched in the western half of the Gangetic Plain.\"<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p84\">{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/84 84]}}</ref>\n\nIn the writings of the occupational theorists, the Kurmis and the Jats came to be extolled for their yeoman-like purposefulness, tirelessness, and thrift, all of which, according to writers such as Crooke, Ibbetson, and Blunt had been largely abandoned by the landed elite.<ref name=bayly-p212>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=212|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Crooke wrote about the Kurmi in 1897: <blockquote> They are about the most industrious and hard-working agricultural tribe in the Province. The industry of his wife has passed into a proverb: <br>\n''Bhali j\u00e2t Kurmin, khurpi h\u00e2t,'' <br>\n''Khet nir\u00e2w\u00ea apan p\u00ee k\u00ea s\u00e2th.'' <br>\n\"A good lot is the Kurmi woman; she takes her spud and weeds the field with her lord.\"<ref name=\"Crooke1896-p353-354\">{{cite book|last=Crooke|first=William|title=The tribes and castes of the North-western Provinces and Oudh, Volume III|url=https://archive.org/details/tribesandcastes01croogoog|year=1896|publisher=Office of the superintendent of government printing|pages=[https://archive.org/details/tribesandcastes01croogoog/page/n374 353]\u2013354}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Susan Bayly, <blockquote> By the mid-nineteenth century, influential revenue specialists were reporting that they could tell the caste of a landed man by simply glancing at his crops. In the north, these observers claimed, a field of 'second-rate barley' would belong to a Rajput or Brahman who took pride in shunning the plough and secluding his womenfolk. Such a man was to be blamed for his own decline, fecklessly mortgaging and then selling off his lands to maintain his unproductive dependents. By the same logic, a flourishing field of wheat would belong to a non-twice-born tiller, wheat being a crop requiring skill and enterprise on the part of the cultivator. These, said such commentators as Denzil Ibbetson and E. A. H. Blunt, were the qualities of the non-patrician 'peasant'&nbsp;\u2013 the thrifty Jat or canny Kurmi in upper India, .... Similar virtues would be found among the smaller market-gardening populations, these being the people known as Keoris in Hindustan, ....<ref name=bayly-p212/></blockquote>\n\n===Twentieth century===\nAs the economic pressures on the patrician landed groups continued through the remainder of the nineteenth century and into the early twentieth, there were increasing demands for unpaid labour directed at the Kurmi and other non-elite cultivators.<ref name=bayly-p205-206>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=205\u2013206|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  The landed elites' demands were couched in avowals of their ancient rights as \"twice-born\" landowners and of the Kurmi's alleged lowly, even servile, status, which required them to serve.<ref name=bayly-p205-206/>  At times encouraged by sympathetic British officials and at other times carried by the groundswell of egalitarian sentiment being espoused then by the devotional [[Vaishnavism|Vaishnava]] movements, especially those based on [[Tulsidas]]'s ''[[Ramcharitmanas]]'', the Kurmi largely resisted these demands.<ref name=bayly-p207>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=207|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  Their resistance, however, did not take the form of denial of caste or of caste-based imposition, but rather of disagreement about where they stood in the caste ranking.<ref name=bayly-p205-206/>  A noteworthy attribute of the resulting Kurmi-kshatriya movement was the leadership provided by educated Kurmis who were now filling the lower and middle levels of government jobs.<ref name=\"Pinch1996-p84\"/> According to William Pinch: <blockquote> The mantle of leadership in this phase befell the well-connected Ramdin Sinha, a government forester who had gained notoriety by resigning from his official post to protest a provincial circular of 1894 that included Kurmis as a \"depressed community\" and barred them therefore from recruitment into the police service. The governor\u2019s office was flooded with letters from an outraged Kurmi-kshatriya public and was soon obliged to rescind the allegation in an 1896 communique to the police department \"His Honor [the governor] is ... of the opinion that Kurmis constitute a respectable community which he would be reluctant to exclude from Government service.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=William R. |last=Pinch|title=Peasants and monks in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc|url-access=registration |year=1996|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-20061-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/peasantsmonksinb0000pinc/page/89 89]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe first Kurmi caste association had been formed in 1894 at [[Lucknow]] to protest against the police recruitment policy. This was followed by an organisation in Awadh that sought to draw other communities&nbsp;\u2014 such as the [[Patidar]]s, [[Maratha]]s, [[Kapu]]s, [[Reddy]]s and [[Naidu]]s&nbsp;\u2014 under the umbrella of the Kurmi name. This body then campaigned for Kurmis to classify themselves as Kshatriya in the 1901 census and, in 1910, led to the formation of the [[All India Kurmi Kshatriya Mahasabha]].<ref name=Jaffrelot2003p197>{{cite book |title=India's silent revolution: the rise of the lower castes in North India |page=197 |first=Christophe |last=Jaffrelot |publisher=C. Hurst & Co. |location=London |year=2003 |isbn=978-1-85065-670-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OAkW94DtUMAC}}</ref> Simultaneously, newly constituted farmers' unions, or ''Kisan Sabhas''\u2014composed of cultivators and pastoralists, many of whom were Kurmi, Ahir, and [[Yadav]] ([[Gavli|Goala]]), and inspired by Hindu mendicants, such as [[Baba Ram Chandra]] and [[Sahajanand Saraswati|Swami Sahajanand Saraswati]]\u2014denounced the Brahman and Rajput landlords as ineffective and their morality as false.<ref name=bayly-p208-209>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=208\u2013209|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>  In the rural Ganges valley of Bihar and Eastern United Provinces, the [[Bhakti]] cults of [[Rama]], the incorruptible Kshatriya god-king of Hindu tradition, and [[Krishna]], the divine cowherd of Gokul, had long been entrenched among the Kurmi and Ahir.<ref name=bayly-p208-209/>  The leaders of the ''Kisan Sabhas'' urged their Kurmi and Ahir followers to lay claim to the Kshatriya mantle.<ref name=bayly-p208-209/>  Promoting what was advertised as soldierly manliness, the ''Kisan Sabhas'' agitated for the entry of non-elite farmers into the British Indian army during World War I; they formed [[cow protection movement|cow protection societies]]; they asked their members to wear the [[sacred thread]] of the [[twice-born]], and, in contrast to the Kurmis own traditions, to sequester their women in the manner of Rajputs and Brahmins.<ref name=bayly-p209-210>{{citation|last=Bayly|first=Susan|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=209\u2013210|isbn=978-0-521-79842-6}}</ref>\n\nIn 1930, the Kurmis of Bihar joined with the Yadav and [[Koeri]] agriculturalists to enter local elections. They lost badly but in 1934 the three communities formed the [[Triveni Sangh]] political party, which allegedly had a million dues-paying members by 1936. However, the organisation was hobbled by competition from the Congress-backed [[Backward Class]] Federation, which was formed around the same time, and by co-option of community leaders by the Congress party. The Triveni Sangh suffered badly in the 1937 elections, although it did win in some areas. The organisation also suffered from caste rivalries, notably the superior organisational ability of the higher castes who opposed it, as well as the inability of the Yadavs to renounce their belief that they were natural leaders and that the Kurmi were somehow inferior. Similar problems beset a later planned caste union, the ''Raghav Samaj'', with the Koeris.<ref name=Jaffrelot2003p197/>\n\nAgain in the 1970s, the India Kurmi Kshatriya Sabha attempted to bring the Koeris under their wing, but disunity troubled this alliance.<ref>{{cite news |first=Akshaya |last=Mukul |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/young-india-votes/news/Mighty-Kurmis-of-Bihar/articleshow/555124.cms |title=Mighty Kurmis of Bihar |work=The Times of India |date=12 March 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Fernandes to head Janata Dal (United) | url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/2003/10/31/stories/2003103104371100.htm | author=Gargi Parsai | date=31 October 2003 | newspaper=The Hindu | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65xylZw3k?url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/2003/10/31/stories/2003103104371100.htm | archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nMany private caste-based armies surfaced in Bihar between the 1970s and 1990s, largely influenced by landlord farmers reacting to the growing influence of left extremist groups. Among these was the [[Bhumi Sena]], the membership of which was drawn mainly from youths who had a Kurmi origin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/static/html/fl1919/19190330.htm|title=End of a terror trail|work=Frontline|date=27 September 2002|first=Kalyan |last=Chaudhuri|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HbAjKR_iHogC&pg=PA54|title=Caste, Society and Politics in India from the Eighteenth Century to the Modern Age|last=Bayly|first=Susan|authorlink=Susan Bayly|year=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-52179-842-6|page=347}}</ref> Bhumi Sena was much feared in the Patna region and also had influence in the districts of Nalanda, Jehanabad and Gaya.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/a-lasting-signature-on-bihar-s-most-violent-years/957421/2|title=A lasting signature on Bihar's most violent years |work=Indian Express|accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Patidar]]\n*[[Patel]]\n*[[Kudumbar]]\n*[[Kochaisa]]\n*[[Lava (Ramayana)]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Bhattacharya|first1=Ranjit Kumar|last2=Das|first2=Nava Kishor|author3=Anthropological Survey of India|title=Anthropology of weaker sections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pjVdJMBeXU8C|accessdate=1 August 2011|date=1 January 1993|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|isbn=978-81-7022-491-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gooptu|first=Nandini|title=The politics of the urban poor in early twentieth-century India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRrbSzEvNCMC|accessdate=1 August 2011|date=1 July 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-44366-1}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Singer|first1=Milton (editor)|last2=Cohn|first2=Bernard S. (editor)|title=Structure and Change in Indian Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC|accessdate=1 August 2011|year=2007|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-202-36138-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Yang|first=Anand A.|title=The limited Raj: agrarian relations in colonial India, Saran District, 1793-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ck4jmD7H34UC|accessdate=1 August 2011|year=1989|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-05711-1}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oDeFAAAAIAAJ|title=Daughters of The Earth|last=Jassal|first=Smita Tewari|publisher=Technical Publications|year=2001|isbn=978-8-17304-375-8|page=57}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QCp0JQcFik8C&lpg=PA78&dq=awadhiya&pg=PA78#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Anthropological Methods for Communication Research: Experiences and Encounters During SITE|last=Viswanath|first=Sashikala|date=1985|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|language=en}}\n\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Bangladesh}}\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Agricultural castes]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citation reduced", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurmi"}
{"title_page": "WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal", "text_new": "{{short description|All women battle royal held by WWE at WrestleMania}}\n[[File:2018-04-10 19-49-05 ILCE-6500 DSC07834 (41060747314) (cropped).jpg|thumb|The inaugural winner [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]] with the WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal Trophy]]\nThe '''WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal'''<ref name=\"namechange\"/> is a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling battle royal|battle royal]] held at [[WrestleMania]] by the [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestling promotion]] [[WWE]]. The inaugural battle royal was held during the [[WrestleMania 34]] Kickoff pre-show in 2018. The winner of the match received the WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal Trophy.\n\nThe match was originally named '''The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal''' in honor of [[The Fabulous Moolah]] \u2013 billed as a pioneer of women's wrestling. However, her name was removed from the match after backlash from fans due to the controversy surrounding Moolah's past. The match is the female counterpart to the [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal]], which was introduced at [[WrestleMania XXX]].<ref name=\"Andre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2014-03-10/wwe-raw-results-26193637|title=Raw results: Daniel Bryan occupies Raw and Triple H says 'YES!' ... with a twist|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=March 10, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2019, it was announced that the Women's Battle Royal was returning at [[WrestleMania 35]], thus establishing the match as an annual tradition.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/womens-battle-royal-confirmed-for-wrestlemania-35 Women's Battle Royal confirmed for WrestleMania 35 - 411 Mania.com]</ref> However, the match did not occur at [[WrestleMania 36]] due to concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n== History ==\nOn the March 12, 2018, episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', WWE established The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal in honor of Moolah, and that the first match would take place at [[WrestleMania 34]] on April 8, with the winner receiving The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Trophy (made in the likeness of Moolah).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/wwe/2018/03/13/wwe-fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal-announced-wrestlemania-34/|title=WWE Announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal for WrestleMania 34|first=Connor|last=Casey|work=Pop Culture|publisher=Pop Culture Media|location=[[Brentwood, Tennessee]]|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pappolla|first1=Ryan|title=The first-ever Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal to take place at WrestleMania|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-34/fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> After a [[#Name controversy|controversy]] over their decision to honor Moolah, WWE changed the name to the \"WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal\".<ref name=\"namechange\"/> The trophy was subsequently renamed, and redesigned as a simple golden cup with tassels atop the trophy's base.<ref name=\"Raw04022018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/04/02/kellers-wwe-raw-report-4-2-final-wrestlemania-34-hype-including-triple-h-stephanie-in-ring-with-angle-ronda-rousey-last-chance-for-undertaker-to-response-reigns-lesnar-hype/|title=KELLER\u2019S WWE RAW REPORT 4/2: Final WrestleMania 34 hype including Triple H & Stephanie in ring with Angle & Ronda Rousey, last chance for Undertaker to response, Reigns-Lesnar hype|date=April 2, 2018|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref> The inaugural match was won by [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]], after she last eliminated [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]. The second match was won by [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]], after she last eliminated [[Sarah Logan]].\n\nA third annual WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal would have occurred at [[WrestleMania 36]] in April 2020, but due to concerns stemming from the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], which brought many changes to WWE's programming during that time, the match was not scheduled to limit the number of wrestlers in the ring at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/wrestlemania-battle-royal-not-taking-place-coronavirus/#.Xn7gnohKg2w|title=WWE Confirms WrestleMania 36 Will Not Feature Battle Royal Matches|date=March 26, 2020|author=[[Ryan Satin|Satin, Ryan]]|work=[[Pro Wrestling Sheet]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Winners ==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=18%|Winner\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15%|Date\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=22%|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=13%|WrestleMania\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=40%|Last eliminated\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]]\n|{{dts|2018|4|8}}\n|[[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]\n|[[WrestleMania 34|34]]\n|[[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]\n|{{dts|2019|4|7}}\n|[[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n|[[WrestleMania 35|35]]\n|[[Sarah Logan]]\n|}\n\n== Participants == \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Superstar'''\n! [[WrestleMania 34|34]]\n! [[WrestleMania 35|35]]\n|-\n| [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Becky Lynch]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Bianca Belair]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Candice LeRae]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]||{{ya}}||{{won|color=gold}}\n|-\n| [[Dakota Kai]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Dana Brooke]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Ember Moon]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Kairi Sane]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Kavita Devi]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Lana (wrestler)|Lana]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Liv Morgan]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Mandy Rose]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Maria Kanellis]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Mickie James]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]]||{{won|color=gold}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Natalya Neidhart|Natalya]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Nikki Cross]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Peyton Royce]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Ruby Riott]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Sarah Logan]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Sasha Banks]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Sonya Deville]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Taynara Conti]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Zelina Vega]]||||{{ya}}\n|}\n\n==Name controversy==\n{{Main|The Fabulous Moolah#Allegations of exploitation}}\n[[File:The Fabulous Moolah circa date photograph.jpg|thumb|[[The Fabulous Moolah]], {{circa|2003}}]]\nThe decision to hold a battle royal in honor of The Fabulous Moolah drew fan outrage.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE face fans backlash after they announce the \u2018Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal\u2019|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/wrestling/wwe-received-deal-backlash-following-12179980|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Stride|first=Sam|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[London]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Tufayel Ahmed of ''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote that Moolah \"isn't quite the bastion of female empowerment she is proclaimed to be\", with \"years of allegations\" that she had \"monopolized women\u2019s wrestling in North America\", taken a large percentage of other wrestlers' pay, and \"sexually exploited women under her mentorship\".<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ahmed|first1=Tufayel|title=WWE announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal, but the wrestler has a troubling legacy|url=http://www.newsweek.com/wwe-fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal-842789|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|publisher=[[Newsweek Media Group|IBT Media/Newsweek Media Group]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Jason Powell, from ''Pro Wrestling Dot Net'', criticized the tribute as it does not \"exactly mesh with what WWE wants their women's division push to represent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/03/13/wwe-raw-hit-list-john-cena-challenges-undertaker-wrestlemania-match-no-brock-lesnar-vince-mcmahon-suspends-roman-reigns-tag-team-battle-royal-fabulous-moolah-battle-royal/|title=WWE Raw Hit List: John Cena challenges Undertaker to a WrestleMania match, no Brock Lesnar, Vince McMahon suspends Roman Reigns, tag team battle royal, Fabulous Moolah battle royal|first=Jason|last=Powell|work=ProWrestling.net|publisher=Last RowMedia, LLC|location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> David Bixenspan of ''[[Deadspin]]'' pointed out that given Moolah's alleged abuses, fans were particularly turned off by WWE personnel describing Moolah as a \"trailblazer for women\u2019s equality\". WWE also promoted Moolah as having \"challenged the gender norms of a once male-dominated sport\", but Bixenspan described that Moolah, by wrestling and teaching her students an \"in-ring style low on athleticism and heavy on hair-pulling\", relegated women's wrestling to \"much more of a sideshow\" instead of a \"legitimate headline attraction\" in the previous era.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bixenspan|first1=David|title=Fans Are Revolting Against WWE Honoring Fabulous Moolah, With Good Reason|url=https://deadspin.com/fans-are-revolting-against-wwe-honoring-fabulous-moolah-1823744298|work=[[Deadspin]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|location=United States|date=March 14, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[Mad Maxine]], a wrestler trained by Moolah, commented that Moolah was the most \"monstrous\" person she had ever met, and that wrestling is \"about generating heat. And you can't draw more heat than naming a match for The Fabulous Moolah.\"<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=Ryan Satin|last1=Satin|first1=Ryan|title=Fabulous Moolah Trainee Speaks Out Against WWE Tribute, Claims Hall Of Famer \"Pimped Women\"|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/moolah-trainee-battle-royal|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|publisher=Ryan Satin, LLC|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, a [[Change.org]] petition appeared online demanding WWE change the name of its upcoming Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal, nearing its 10,000 signature goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thewrap.com/fabulous-moolah-battle-royal-petition-wwe-wrestlemania/|title=\u2018Fabulous Moolah Battle Royal': Petition for WWE to Change Match Name Approaches Signature Goal|first=Tony|last=Maglio|work=[[TheWrap]]|publisher=The Wrap News Inc.|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=March 14, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Initially, WWE reacted by disabling the comments section of their YouTube video that announced the Moolah battle royal.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal Name Change|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/moolah-match-name-change|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|publisher=Ryan Satin, LLC|location=[[Los Angeles]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fiorvanti|first1=Tim|title=WWE changes name of WrestleMania's women's Battle Royal|url=http://kwese.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/22778917/wwe-changes-name-wrestlemania-women-battle-royal|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|location=United States|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Later, [[Snickers]], the primary sponsor of WrestleMania 34, called the decision to honor Moolah \"unacceptable\" and said they were \"engaging with the WWE to express our disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Amid controversy, WWE changes name of first WrestleMania women's battle royal|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/amid-controversy-wwe-changes-name-of-first-wrestlemania-womens-battle-royal/|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=[[CBS Broadcasting Inc.]]|location=[[New York City]]|last=Jorgensen|first=Jack|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> On March 14, WWE renamed the match \"WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal\", removing Moolah's name from the event.<ref name=\"namechange\">{{cite web|title=WWE changes name of Fabulous Moolah battle royal|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-changes-name-fabulous-moolah-battle-royal-253621|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter, Inc.|location=United States|last=Currier|first=Joseph|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women in WWE}}\n{{WWE}}\n{{WWE Championships}}\n\n[[Category:WrestleMania]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling controversies]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling battle royales]]\n[[Category:Women in WWE]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|All women battle royal held by WWE at WrestleMania}}\n[[File:2018-04-10 19-49-05 ILCE-6500 DSC07834 (41060747314) (cropped).jpg|thumb|The inaugural winner [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]] with the WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal Trophy]]\nThe '''WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal'''<ref name=\"namechange\"/> is a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling battle royal|battle royal]] held at [[WrestleMania]] by the [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestling promotion]] [[WWE]]. The inaugural battle royal was held during the [[WrestleMania 34]] Kickoff pre-show. The winner of the match received the WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal Trophy.\n\nThe match was originally named '''The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal''' in honor of [[The Fabulous Moolah]] \u2013 billed as a pioneer of women's wrestling. However, her name was removed from the match after backlash from fans due to the controversy surrounding Moolah's past. The match is the female counterpart to the [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant Memorial Battle Royal]], which was introduced at [[WrestleMania XXX]].<ref name=\"Andre\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2014-03-10/wwe-raw-results-26193637|title=Raw results: Daniel Bryan occupies Raw and Triple H says 'YES!' ... with a twist|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=March 10, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2019, it was announced that the Women's Battle Royal was returning at [[WrestleMania 35]], thus establishing the match as an annual tradition.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/womens-battle-royal-confirmed-for-wrestlemania-35 Women's Battle Royal confirmed for WrestleMania 35 - 411 Mania.com]</ref> However, the match did not occur at [[WrestleMania 36]] due to concerns over the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n== History ==\nOn the March 12, 2018, episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'', WWE established The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal in honor of Moolah, and that the first match would take place at [[WrestleMania 34]] on April 8, with the winner receiving The Fabulous Moolah Memorial Trophy (made in the likeness of Moolah).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popculture.com/wwe/2018/03/13/wwe-fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal-announced-wrestlemania-34/|title=WWE Announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal for WrestleMania 34|first=Connor|last=Casey|work=Pop Culture|publisher=Pop Culture Media|location=[[Brentwood, Tennessee]]|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pappolla|first1=Ryan|title=The first-ever Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal to take place at WrestleMania|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-34/fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=March 12, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref> After a [[#Name controversy|controversy]] over their decision to honor Moolah, WWE changed the name to the \"WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal\".<ref name=\"namechange\"/> The trophy was subsequently renamed, and redesigned as a simple golden cup with tassels atop the trophy's base.<ref name=\"Raw04022018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/04/02/kellers-wwe-raw-report-4-2-final-wrestlemania-34-hype-including-triple-h-stephanie-in-ring-with-angle-ronda-rousey-last-chance-for-undertaker-to-response-reigns-lesnar-hype/|title=KELLER\u2019S WWE RAW REPORT 4/2: Final WrestleMania 34 hype including Triple H & Stephanie in ring with Angle & Ronda Rousey, last chance for Undertaker to response, Reigns-Lesnar hype|date=April 2, 2018|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref> The inaugural match was won by [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]], after she last eliminated [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]. The second match was won by [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]], after she last eliminated [[Sarah Logan]].\n\nA third annual WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal would have occurred at [[WrestleMania 36]] in April 2020, but due to concerns stemming from the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], which brought many changes to WWE's programming during that time, the match was not scheduled to limit the number of wrestlers in the ring at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/wrestlemania-battle-royal-not-taking-place-coronavirus/#.Xn7gnohKg2w|title=WWE Confirms WrestleMania 36 Will Not Feature Battle Royal Matches|date=March 26, 2020|author=[[Ryan Satin|Satin, Ryan]]|work=[[Pro Wrestling Sheet]]|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Winners ==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=18%|Winner\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15%|Date\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=22%|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=13%|WrestleMania\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=40%|Last eliminated\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]]\n|{{dts|2018|4|8}}\n|[[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]\n|[[WrestleMania 34|34]]\n|[[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]\n|{{dts|2019|4|7}}\n|[[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n|[[WrestleMania 35|35]]\n|[[Sarah Logan]]\n|}\n\n== Participants == \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Superstar'''\n! [[WrestleMania 34|34]]\n! [[WrestleMania 35|35]]\n|-\n| [[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Becky Lynch]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Bianca Belair]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Candice LeRae]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]||{{ya}}||{{won|color=gold}}\n|-\n| [[Dakota Kai]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Dana Brooke]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Ember Moon]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Kairi Sane]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Kavita Devi]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Lana (wrestler)|Lana]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Liv Morgan]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Mandy Rose]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Maria Kanellis]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Mickie James]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]]||{{won|color=gold}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Natalya Neidhart|Natalya]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Nikki Cross]]||||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Peyton Royce]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Ruby Riott]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Sarah Logan]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Sasha Banks]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Sonya Deville]]||{{ya}}||{{ya}}\n|-\n| [[Taynara Conti]]||{{ya}}||\n|-\n| [[Zelina Vega]]||||{{ya}}\n|}\n\n==Name controversy==\n{{Main|The Fabulous Moolah#Allegations of exploitation}}\n[[File:The Fabulous Moolah circa date photograph.jpg|thumb|[[The Fabulous Moolah]], {{circa|2003}}]]\nThe decision to hold a battle royal in honor of The Fabulous Moolah drew fan outrage.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE face fans backlash after they announce the \u2018Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal\u2019|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/wrestling/wwe-received-deal-backlash-following-12179980|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Stride|first=Sam|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|location=[[London]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Tufayel Ahmed of ''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote that Moolah \"isn't quite the bastion of female empowerment she is proclaimed to be\", with \"years of allegations\" that she had \"monopolized women\u2019s wrestling in North America\", taken a large percentage of other wrestlers' pay, and \"sexually exploited women under her mentorship\".<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ahmed|first1=Tufayel|title=WWE announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal, but the wrestler has a troubling legacy|url=http://www.newsweek.com/wwe-fabulous-moolah-memorial-battle-royal-842789|magazine=[[Newsweek]]|publisher=[[Newsweek Media Group|IBT Media/Newsweek Media Group]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Jason Powell, from ''Pro Wrestling Dot Net'', criticized the tribute as it does not \"exactly mesh with what WWE wants their women's division push to represent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2018/03/13/wwe-raw-hit-list-john-cena-challenges-undertaker-wrestlemania-match-no-brock-lesnar-vince-mcmahon-suspends-roman-reigns-tag-team-battle-royal-fabulous-moolah-battle-royal/|title=WWE Raw Hit List: John Cena challenges Undertaker to a WrestleMania match, no Brock Lesnar, Vince McMahon suspends Roman Reigns, tag team battle royal, Fabulous Moolah battle royal|first=Jason|last=Powell|work=ProWrestling.net|publisher=Last RowMedia, LLC|location=[[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> David Bixenspan of ''[[Deadspin]]'' pointed out that given Moolah's alleged abuses, fans were particularly turned off by WWE personnel describing Moolah as a \"trailblazer for women\u2019s equality\". WWE also promoted Moolah as having \"challenged the gender norms of a once male-dominated sport\", but Bixenspan described that Moolah, by wrestling and teaching her students an \"in-ring style low on athleticism and heavy on hair-pulling\", relegated women's wrestling to \"much more of a sideshow\" instead of a \"legitimate headline attraction\" in the previous era.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bixenspan|first1=David|title=Fans Are Revolting Against WWE Honoring Fabulous Moolah, With Good Reason|url=https://deadspin.com/fans-are-revolting-against-wwe-honoring-fabulous-moolah-1823744298|work=[[Deadspin]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|location=United States|date=March 14, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[Mad Maxine]], a wrestler trained by Moolah, commented that Moolah was the most \"monstrous\" person she had ever met, and that wrestling is \"about generating heat. And you can't draw more heat than naming a match for The Fabulous Moolah.\"<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=Ryan Satin|last1=Satin|first1=Ryan|title=Fabulous Moolah Trainee Speaks Out Against WWE Tribute, Claims Hall Of Famer \"Pimped Women\"|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/moolah-trainee-battle-royal|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|publisher=Ryan Satin, LLC|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, a [[Change.org]] petition appeared online demanding WWE change the name of its upcoming Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal, nearing its 10,000 signature goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thewrap.com/fabulous-moolah-battle-royal-petition-wwe-wrestlemania/|title=\u2018Fabulous Moolah Battle Royal': Petition for WWE to Change Match Name Approaches Signature Goal|first=Tony|last=Maglio|work=[[TheWrap]]|publisher=The Wrap News Inc.|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=March 14, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> Initially, WWE reacted by disabling the comments section of their YouTube video that announced the Moolah battle royal.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWE Announces Fabulous Moolah Memorial Battle Royal Name Change|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/moolah-match-name-change|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|publisher=Ryan Satin, LLC|location=[[Los Angeles]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fiorvanti|first1=Tim|title=WWE changes name of WrestleMania's women's Battle Royal|url=http://kwese.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/22778917/wwe-changes-name-wrestlemania-women-battle-royal|work=[[ESPN.com]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|location=United States|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Later, [[Snickers]], the primary sponsor of WrestleMania 34, called the decision to honor Moolah \"unacceptable\" and said they were \"engaging with the WWE to express our disappointment.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Amid controversy, WWE changes name of first WrestleMania women's battle royal|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/amid-controversy-wwe-changes-name-of-first-wrestlemania-womens-battle-royal/|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=[[CBS Broadcasting Inc.]]|location=[[New York City]]|last=Jorgensen|first=Jack|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> On March 14, WWE renamed the match \"WrestleMania Women's Battle Royal\", removing Moolah's name from the event.<ref name=\"namechange\">{{cite web|title=WWE changes name of Fabulous Moolah battle royal|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-changes-name-fabulous-moolah-battle-royal-253621|work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter, Inc.|location=United States|last=Currier|first=Joseph|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women in WWE}}\n{{WWE}}\n{{WWE Championships}}\n\n[[Category:WrestleMania]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling controversies]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling battle royales]]\n[[Category:Women in WWE]]\n", "name_user": "JDC808", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WrestleMania_Women%27s_Battle_Royal"}
{"title_page": "Mau district", "text_new": "{{About|the district|its eponymous headquarters|Mau}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Mau district\n| settlement_type        = [[Districts of Uttar Pradesh|District of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| total_type             = Total\n| native_name            =\n| image_map              = India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Mau.svg\n| map_caption            = Location of Mau district in Uttar Pradesh\n| coordinates            =\n| coor_pinpoint          = Mau\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of India|Division]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Azamgarh division|Azamgarh]]\n| established_title      = Established\n| established_date       =\n| seat_type              = Headquarters\n| seat                   = [[Mau]]\n| parts_type             = [[Tehsils of India|Tehsils]]\n| parts_style            = para\n| p1                     = Mau Ghosi\n| area_total_km2         = 1,713\n| area_footnotes         =\n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_total       = 2,205,968\n| population_footnotes   =\n| population_urban       =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| demographics_type1     = Demographics\n| demographics1_title1   = [[Literacy in India|Literacy]]\n| demographics1_info1    = 75.16 per cent\n| demographics1_title2   = Sex ratio\n| demographics1_info2    = 90\n| leader_title           =\n| leader_name            =\n| leader_title1          = [[Lok Sabha]] constituencies\n| leader_name1           = [[Ghosi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghosi]]\n| leader_title2          = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituencies\n| leader_name2           = Ghosi , Madhuban, Maunath Bhanjan (Sadar), Mohammadabad Gohana\n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +05:30\n| registration_plate     =\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[Indian road network|Major highways]]\n| blank_info_sec1        = NH-29\n| blank_name_sec2        =\n| blank_info_sec2        =\n| website                = http://mau.nic.in/\n}}\n'''Mau district''' is one of the [[Districts of Uttar Pradesh|districts]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[India]], and [[Mau]] town is the district headquarters which is also one of the few remaining areas of handloom [[saree]] production in eastern Uttar Pradesh, specializing in Sadiya silk sarees.<ref>[https://mau.nic.in/about-district/culture-heritage/ Sadiya Silk Saree] [https://www.amazon.in/Sadiya-Silk-Saree-Sadiya-saree_3_Red_Free-Size/dp/B01N27N3N4] [https://www.india.com/news/india/narendra-modi-to-gift-100-banarasi-silk-sarees-to-michelle-obama-257803/]</ref> Mau was carved out as a separate district from [[Azamgarh]] on 19 November 1988. It is situated in the south-eastern part of the state with headquarters in [[Maunath Bhanjan]]. The district is surrounded by [[Ghazipur district|Ghazipur]] district on the south, [[Ballia district|Ballia]] district in the east, [[Azamgarh district|Azamgarh]] district in the west, and by [[Gorakhpur district|Gorakhpur]] and [[Deoria district|Deoria]] districts on the north.\n== History ==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=4,86,949|13=1911|14=4,64,472|15=1921|16=4,73,935|17=1931|18=4,90,052|19=1941|20=5,67,851|21=1951|22=6,54,208|23=1961|24=7,68,157|25=1971|26=9,26,263|27=1981|28=11,26,879|29=1991|30=14,46,553|31=2001|32=18,54,950|33=2011|34=22,05,968|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}From historical and archaeological point of views, [[Mau]] is one of the oldest place in the region. Ancient cultural and archaeological remains have been found at multiple places in the area giving enough evidence of long history of human habitat in the area. The known archaeological history of [[Mau]] is about 1500 years old, when the entire area was covered under thick dense forest. The nuts who used to live along [[Tamsa river]], are considered to be the oldest inhabitants and the ruler of the area.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nAs per the records on official webpage of the district, in 1028 A.D. King Syed Shalar Masood Ghazi came with a huge army to conquer the area but he went back to [[Afghanistan]], living few of his people in the area. A sufi saint Baba Malik Tahir and his brother Malik Qasim were part of the remaining group. There are places like Malik Tahir Pura and Qasim Pura in the name of these two saints in Mau city. The tomb of Malik Tahir is also present in Malik Tahir Pura and locally known as Mazaar Malik Tahir Baba.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nAround 1540\u20131545, [[Sher Shah Suri]], the emperor who defeated [[Humayun]], during his reign visited Kolhuvavan (Madhuban) to meet the great Sufi saint Syed Ahmad Wadva.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-10/lucknow/31046000_1_doharighat-mukhtar-ansari-bsp-ticket |title=Sufi saint's abode now Uttar Pradesh don's den |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-02-10 |accessdate=2015-10-05}}</ref> Mahvani, one of the daughters of Sher Shah had settled permanently near the dargah of Syed Wadva. The area also finds place in the historical book of [[Ziya'-Ud-Din Barani|Ziyaudeen Barni]] with a description that the great Mughal emperor Akbar passed through Mau on his way to Allahabad. At that time, labourer and artisans originally belonging to Iran, Afghanistan and Turkey, who had come with Mughal army settled here permanently. These artisans integrated into the society over a period of time but they kept their art alive and despite a gradual demise of the handloom industry in the eastern Uttar Pradesh, the saree industry of Mau still remains the last bastion of handicraft in the area otherwise an industrially thriving region till the end of last century. It is also believed that one of Akbar's daughters, Jahan Aara had also settled in that area where she built a mosque. The original structure of the mosque is not surviving anymore but place is known as Shahi Qatra and there is a Shahi Mosque in that locality reminding of its past glory.<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Sufi-saints-abode-now-dons-den/articleshow/11830609.cms</ref>\n\nDuring the Indian freedom struggle, the people of Mau had given full support to the movement, and Mahatma Gandhi had also made a visit to Doharighat region of the district in 1939.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nIn 1932, [[Azamgarh]] was made independent district, Mau region was a part of it until 1988 when the current area of Mau district was carved out of Azamgarh to make a separate district and on 19 November 1988, Mau became a separate district in which the then [[Ministry of Power (India)|Union Minister of State of India (Power)]] [[Kalpnath Rai]] played a pivotal role. He is also credited to start an array of developmental activities in the city including new Railway Station and a stadium.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/in-mau-a-complex-tapestry-of-caste-and-religion/article2879547.ece</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[A Passage to India]] is a 1924 novel by English author [[E. M. Forster]] set against the backdrop of the British Raj and the Indian independence movement in the 1920s. The novel was adapted in a film with same title in 1984. One of the protagonists, Aziz moved to Mau where he met a school master Cyril Fielding.\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Mau<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mau.nic.in/|title=Census 2011|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|80.23}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|19.43}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|red|0.10}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhists]]|blue|0.03}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhs]]|yellow|0.02}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.18}}\n|Founder=Bipul Singh Yadav}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Mau Nath Bhanjan district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 2,205,968, in which male and female were 1,114,888 and 1,090,782 respectively. In 2001 census, Mau had a population of 1,853,997, in which males were 933,523 and remaining 920,474 were females.<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 2011-09-30 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> roughly equal to the nation of [[Latvia]]<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 2011-10-01 | quote =\nLatvia 2,204,708 July 2011 est.\n }}</ref> or the US state of [[New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php |title=2010 Resident Population Data |publisher=U. S. Census Bureau |accessdate=2011-09-30 |quote=New Mexico \u2013 2,059,179 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118011236/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php |archivedate=2011-11-18 }}</ref> This gives it a ranking of 206th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus /> The district has a population density of {{convert|1287|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}} .<ref name=districtcensus /> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001\u20132011 was  80.94%.<ref name=districtcensus /> Mau has a [[sex ratio]] of 978 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus /> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 75.16%.<ref name=districtcensus />\n\nAt the time of the [[2011 Census of India]], 86.43% of the population in the district spoke [[Hindi]] and 13.51% [[Urdu]] as their first language.<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html 2011 Census of India, Population By Mother Tongue]</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nJharkande Rai and [[Kalpnath Rai]] were well-known faces of politics in Mau.\nNotable Politician [[Sunil Singh Chauhan]] is also from Mau.\n[[Municipal Corporation]] Chairman Mohammad Tayyab Palki is also from Mau District.\nMau sadar is the Legislative seat of politician [[Mukhtar Ansari]].\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n=== Armed Forces ===\n\n* Brigadier [[Mohammad Usman|Mohammad Usman Masoodi]] (1912-1948), born in Bibipur of Mau district, was the highest ranking officer of the [[Indian Army]] killed in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947\u20131948|Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]] and was awarded  [[Maha Vir Chakra|Maha Vir Chakra (MVC)]] posthumously.\n\n=== Literature ===\n* [[Ali Jawad Zaidi]] (1916\u20132004), born in [[Karhan]], [[Mau]], was a prolific author and scholar who wrote 80 books. He was awarded a [[Padma Shri]] for his literary achievements.\n* [[Laxmi Narayan Mishra]] (1903\u20131987), born in the village Basti, district Mau. He was a popular play writer of HINDI. He was a theatre personality of Uttar Pradesh. His works became very popular between 1930 and 1950. They were frequently staged by schools, colleges, and amateur groups. Laxmi Narayan Mishra is considered the founder of the problem play in Hindi theatre.\n* [[Fiza Ibn-e-Faizi]] (1923\u20132009) was a modern Urdu and Persian poet. He was a native of Mau district of Uttar Pradesh and was considered a 'qadir-ul-kalaam' poet and had received numerous awards within the Urdu world. At least, six poetry collections of Faizi had been published and acclaimed. In 2009, a memorial named as Faizi Gate was constructed by the then municipal head near his house.\n* [[Habib Al-Rahman Al-Azmi|Maulana Habibur Rahman Azmi]] (1900\u20131992) was a well-known Islamic Scholar, belonged to this city. He wrote under pen name of ''Abul Ma'sir''. His works on Islamic Jurisprudence is well acclaimed. He remains a well-known figure in major Islamic seminaries like Medina University, Al-Azhar and Darul-uloom Deoband. His works are cited by Muslims across the world.\n* [[Kanhaiya Lal Misra]] (1903\u20131975) was Advocate General of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India from 1952 to 1969.\n* [[Shyam Narayan Pandey]] (1907\u20131991) was a [[Hindi]] poet famous for his epic poem ''Haldighati'', which is based on the [[Battle of Haldighati]] between [[Akbar]] and [[Maharana Pratap]].\n* [[Krishna N. Sharma|Dr. Krishna N. Sharma]] is a [[List of prolific writers|prolific writer]] and researcher, working as the [[Vice-chancellor|Vice Chancellor]] at [[Victoria University Uganda|Victoria University]], [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].\n\n=== Sports ===\n* [[Kamran Khan (Indian cricketer)|Kamran Khan]], cricketer\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://mau.nic.in}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Mau district\n|North     = gorakhpur\n|Northeast = [[Deoria district]]\n|East      = [[Ballia district]]\n|Southeast = Ghazipur\n|South     = [[Ghazipur district]]\n|Southwest = Azamgarh\n|West      = [[Azamgarh district]]\n|Northwest = [[Gorakhpur district]]\n}}\n\n{{Mau district}}\n{{Districts of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Azamgarh division topics}}\n\n{{coord|25|56|N|83|34|E|region:IN-UP_type:adm2nd_source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:People from Mau]]\n[[Category:Districts of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the district|its eponymous headquarters|Mau}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Mau district\n| settlement_type        = [[Districts of Uttar Pradesh|District of Uttar Pradesh]]\n| total_type             = Total\n| native_name            =\n| image_map              = India Uttar Pradesh districts 2012 Mau.svg\n| map_caption            = Location of Mau district in Uttar Pradesh\n| coordinates            =\n| coor_pinpoint          = Mau\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[States and union territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative divisions of India|Division]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Azamgarh division|Azamgarh]]\n| established_title      = Established\n| established_date       =\n| seat_type              = Headquarters\n| seat                   = [[Mau]]\n| parts_type             = [[Tehsils of India|Tehsils]]\n| parts_style            = para\n| p1                     = Mau Ghosi\n| area_total_km2         = 1,713\n| area_footnotes         =\n| population_as_of       = 2011\n| population_total       = 2,205,968\n| population_footnotes   =\n| population_urban       =\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| demographics_type1     = Demographics\n| demographics1_title1   = [[Literacy in India|Literacy]]\n| demographics1_info1    = 75.16 per cent\n| demographics1_title2   = Sex ratio\n| demographics1_info2    = 90\n| leader_title           =\n| leader_name            =\n| leader_title1          = [[Lok Sabha]] constituencies\n| leader_name1           = [[Ghosi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Ghosi]]\n| leader_title2          = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituencies\n| leader_name2           = Ghosi , Madhuban, Maunath Bhanjan (Sadar), Mohammadabad Gohana\n| timezone1              = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1            = +05:30\n| registration_plate     =\n| blank_name_sec1        = [[Indian road network|Major highways]]\n| blank_info_sec1        = NH-29\n| blank_name_sec2        =\n| blank_info_sec2        =\n| website                = http://mau.nic.in/\n}}\n'''Mau district''' is one of the [[Districts of Uttar Pradesh|districts]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]] [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[India]], and [[Mau]] town is the district headquarters which is also one of the few remaining areas of handloom [[saree]] production in eastern Uttar Pradesh, specializing in Sadiya silk sarees.<ref>[https://mau.nic.in/about-district/culture-heritage/ Sadiya Silk Saree] [https://www.amazon.in/Sadiya-Silk-Saree-Sadiya-saree_3_Red_Free-Size/dp/B01N27N3N4] [https://www.india.com/news/india/narendra-modi-to-gift-100-banarasi-silk-sarees-to-michelle-obama-257803/]</ref> Mau was carved out as a separate district from [[Azamgarh]] on 19 November 1988. It is situated in the south-eastern part of the state with headquarters in [[Maunath Bhanjan]]. The district is surrounded by [[Ghazipur district|Ghazipur]] district on the south, [[Ballia district|Ballia]] district in the east, [[Azamgarh district|Azamgarh]] district in the west, and by [[Gorakhpur district|Gorakhpur]] and [[Deoria district|Deoria]] districts on the north.\n== History ==\n{{historical populations|11=1901|12=4,86,949|13=1911|14=4,64,472|15=1921|16=4,73,935|17=1931|18=4,90,052|19=1941|20=5,67,851|21=1951|22=6,54,208|23=1961|24=7,68,157|25=1971|26=9,26,263|27=1981|28=11,26,879|29=1991|30=14,46,553|31=2001|32=18,54,950|33=2011|34=22,05,968|percentages=pagr|footnote=source:<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/PCA/A2_Data_Table.html Decadal Variation In Population Since 1901]</ref>|align=right}}From historical and archaeological point of views, [[Mau]] is one of the oldest place in the region. Ancient cultural and archaeological remains have been found at multiple places in the area giving enough evidence of long history of human habitat in the area. The known archaeological history of [[Mau]] is about 1500 years old, when the entire area was covered under thick dense forest. The nuts who used to live along [[Tamsa river]], are considered to be the oldest inhabitants and the ruler of the area.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nAs per the records on official webpage of the district, in 1028 A.D. King Syed Shalar Masood Ghazi came with a huge army to conquer the area but he went back to Afghanistan, living few of his people in the area. A sufi saint Baba Malik Tahir and his brother Malik Qasim were part of the remaining group. There are places like Malik Tahir Pura and Qasim Pura in the name of these two saints in Mau city. The tomb of Malik Tahir is also present in Malik Tahir Pura and locally known as Mazaar Malik Tahir Baba.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nAround 1540\u20131545, [[Sher Shah Suri]], the emperor who defeated [[Humayun]], during his reign visited Kolhuvavan (Madhuban) to meet the great Sufi saint Syed Ahmad Wadva.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-10/lucknow/31046000_1_doharighat-mukhtar-ansari-bsp-ticket |title=Sufi saint's abode now Uttar Pradesh don's den |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2012-02-10 |accessdate=2015-10-05}}</ref> Mahvani, one of the daughters of Sher Shah had settled permanently near the dargah of Syed Wadva. The area also finds place in the historical book of [[Ziya'-Ud-Din Barani|Ziyaudeen Barni]] with a description that the great Mughal emperor Akbar passed through Mau on his way to Allahabad. At that time, labourer and artisans originally belonging to Iran, Afghanistan and Turkey, who had come with Mughal army settled here permanently. These artisans integrated into the society over a period of time but they kept their art alive and despite a gradual demise of the handloom industry in the eastern Uttar Pradesh, the saree industry of Mau still remains the last bastion of handicraft in the area otherwise an industrially thriving region till the end of last century. It is also believed that one of Akbar's daughters, Jahan Aara had also settled in that area where she built a mosque. The original structure of the mosque is not surviving anymore but place is known as Shahi Qatra and there is a Shahi Mosque in that locality reminding of its past glory.<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Sufi-saints-abode-now-dons-den/articleshow/11830609.cms</ref>\n\nDuring the Indian freedom struggle, the people of Mau had given full support to the movement, and Mahatma Gandhi had also made a visit to Doharighat region of the district in 1939.<ref>https://mau.nic.in/about-district/history/</ref>\n\nIn 1932, [[Azamgarh]] was made independent district, Mau region was a part of it until 1988 when the current area of Mau district was carved out of Azamgarh to make a separate district and on 19 November 1988, Mau became a separate district in which the then [[Ministry of Power (India)|Union Minister of State of India (Power)]] [[Kalpnath Rai]] played a pivotal role. He is also credited to start an array of developmental activities in the city including new Railway Station and a stadium.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/in-mau-a-complex-tapestry-of-caste-and-religion/article2879547.ece</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[A Passage to India]] is a 1924 novel by English author [[E. M. Forster]] set against the backdrop of the British Raj and the Indian independence movement in the 1920s. The novel was adapted in a film with same title in 1984. One of the protagonists, Aziz moved to Mau where he met a school master Cyril Fielding.\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Mau<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mau.nic.in/|title=Census 2011|accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|80.23}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|19.43}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|red|0.10}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhists]]|blue|0.03}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhs]]|yellow|0.02}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.01}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.18}}\n|Founder=Bipul Singh Yadav}}\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India|2011 census]] Mau Nath Bhanjan district has a [[Demographics of India|population]] of 2,205,968, in which male and female were 1,114,888 and 1,090,782 respectively. In 2001 census, Mau had a population of 1,853,997, in which males were 933,523 and remaining 920,474 were females.<ref name=districtcensus>{{cite web | url = http://www.census2011.co.in/district.php | title = District Census 2011 | accessdate = 2011-09-30 | year = 2011 | publisher = Census2011.co.in}}</ref> roughly equal to the nation of [[Latvia]]<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web | author = US Directorate of Intelligence | title = Country Comparison:Population | url = https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2119rank.html | accessdate = 2011-10-01 | quote =\nLatvia 2,204,708 July 2011 est.\n }}</ref> or the US state of [[New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php |title=2010 Resident Population Data |publisher=U. S. Census Bureau |accessdate=2011-09-30 |quote=New Mexico \u2013 2,059,179 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118011236/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php |archivedate=2011-11-18 }}</ref> This gives it a ranking of 206th in India (out of a total of [[Districts of India|640]]).<ref name=districtcensus /> The district has a population density of {{convert|1287|PD/sqkm|PD/sqmi}} .<ref name=districtcensus /> Its [[Family planning in India|population growth rate]] over the decade 2001\u20132011 was  80.94%.<ref name=districtcensus /> Mau has a [[sex ratio]] of 978 [[Women in India|females]] for every 1000 males,<ref name=districtcensus /> and a [[Literacy in India|literacy rate]] of 75.16%.<ref name=districtcensus />\n\nAt the time of the [[2011 Census of India]], 86.43% of the population in the district spoke [[Hindi]] and 13.51% [[Urdu]] as their first language.<ref>[http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-16.html 2011 Census of India, Population By Mother Tongue]</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nJharkande Rai and [[Kalpnath Rai]] were well-known faces of politics in Mau.\nNotable Politician [[Sunil Singh Chauhan]] is also from Mau.\n[[Municipal Corporation]] Chairman Mohammad Tayyab Palki is also from Mau District.\nMau sadar is the Legislative seat of politician [[Mukhtar Ansari]].\n\n== Notable people ==\n\n=== Armed Forces ===\n\n* Brigadier [[Mohammad Usman|Mohammad Usman Masoodi]] (1912-1948), born in Bibipur of Mau district, was the highest ranking officer of the [[Indian Army]] killed in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947\u20131948|Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]] and was awarded  [[Maha Vir Chakra|Maha Vir Chakra (MVC)]] posthumously.\n\n=== Literature ===\n* [[Ali Jawad Zaidi]] (1916\u20132004), born in [[Karhan]], [[Mau]], was a prolific author and scholar who wrote 80 books. He was awarded a [[Padma Shri]] for his literary achievements.\n* [[Laxmi Narayan Mishra]] (1903\u20131987), born in the village Basti, district Mau. He was a popular play writer of HINDI. He was a theatre personality of Uttar Pradesh. His works became very popular between 1930 and 1950. They were frequently staged by schools, colleges, and amateur groups. Laxmi Narayan Mishra is considered the founder of the problem play in Hindi theatre.\n* [[Fiza Ibn-e-Faizi]] (1923\u20132009) was a modern Urdu and Persian poet. He was a native of Mau district of Uttar Pradesh and was considered a 'qadir-ul-kalaam' poet and had received numerous awards within the Urdu world. At least, six poetry collections of Faizi had been published and acclaimed. In 2009, a memorial named as Faizi Gate was constructed by the then municipal head near his house.\n* [[Habib Al-Rahman Al-Azmi|Maulana Habibur Rahman Azmi]] (1900\u20131992) was a well-known Islamic Scholar, belonged to this city. He wrote under pen name of ''Abul Ma'sir''. His works on Islamic Jurisprudence is well acclaimed. He remains a well-known figure in major Islamic seminaries like Medina University, Al-Azhar and Darul-uloom Deoband. His works are cited by Muslims across the world.\n* [[Kanhaiya Lal Misra]] (1903\u20131975) was Advocate General of [[Uttar Pradesh]], India from 1952 to 1969.\n* [[Shyam Narayan Pandey]] (1907\u20131991) was a [[Hindi]] poet famous for his epic poem ''Haldighati'', which is based on the [[Battle of Haldighati]] between [[Akbar]] and [[Maharana Pratap]].\n* [[Krishna N. Sharma|Dr. Krishna N. Sharma]] is a [[List of prolific writers|prolific writer]] and researcher, working as the [[Vice-chancellor|Vice Chancellor]] at [[Victoria University Uganda|Victoria University]], [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].\n\n=== Sports ===\n* [[Kamran Khan (Indian cricketer)|Kamran Khan]], cricketer\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://mau.nic.in}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Mau district\n|North     = gorakhpur\n|Northeast = [[Deoria district]]\n|East      = [[Ballia district]]\n|Southeast = Ghazipur\n|South     = [[Ghazipur district]]\n|Southwest = Azamgarh\n|West      = [[Azamgarh district]]\n|Northwest = [[Gorakhpur district]]\n}}\n\n{{Mau district}}\n{{Districts of Uttar Pradesh}}\n{{Azamgarh division topics}}\n\n{{coord|25|56|N|83|34|E|region:IN-UP_type:adm2nd_source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:People from Mau]]\n[[Category:Districts of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Districts of India]]\n", "name_user": "Gdrged", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Afghanistan interlinked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mau_district"}
{"title_page": "Saeed Murtaza", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=April 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Saeed Murtaza\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = [[Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar]]\n| term_start = March 1977\n| term_end = August 1979\n| predecessor = [[Vijaypal Singh Tomar]]\n| successor = Ghayoor Ali Khan\n| party =\n| religion =  \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source =  http://164.100.47.194/loksabha/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/2555.htm\n}}\n\n'''Saeed Murtaza'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://164.100.47.194/loksabha/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/2555.htm |title=Members : Lok Sabha |publisher=164.100.47.194 |date= |accessdate=2017-06-25}}</ref> was an [[List of political parties in India|Indian politician]]. He was from a SYED ZAMIDAAR family, his full name was Syed Saeed Murtaza. His elder brother \"Syed Saeed Mustafa\" was the main zamidar, but died early. Syed Saeed Mustafa handed over the leadership to Syed Saeed Murtaza. Syed Saeed Mustafa had one son \"Syed Zahoor mustafa\" and four grand sons \"Syed javed Mustafa\", \"Syed Parvez mustafa kazmi\", \"Syed Tariq mustafa\" and \"Syed Khalid Mustafa\". His great grand sons are \"Syed Nidal Mustafa\", \"Syed Danyal Mustafa\" and \"Syed Saqib Mustafa\". Saeed murtaza's sons are S.Saiduzzaman and Syed Saeed Qamruzzaman, S. Saiduzzaman was Member of parliament in 1999 at muzaffarnagar constituency from Indian national congress.\n\nSaeed Murtaza was a member of 6th [[Lok Sabha]] from [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar constituency]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]].\n\nHis family is Iraqi biradri Syed and are direct descendants of Husayn ibn Ali (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Husayn_ibn_Ali). During the reign of Tulagh Dynasty, Firoz Shah tughlaq invited Syed Masud Al Husseini descendant of Husayn ibn Ali to fight the local raja. Syed Masud came with 40 warriors and his 9 sons to defeat the local raja. After defeating the local raja Syed masud al Husseini was rewarded with 746 villages and qaziat of 8 places, his lineage is called Iraqi biradri.\n\nSaeed murtaza's family are direct descendant of Syed Masud Al husseini.\n\nSaeed Murtaza died on 30 September 1996 by natural causes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loksabha.nic.in/members/lokaralpha.aspx?lsno=6&search=S|title=Members : Lok Sabha|website=loksabha.nic.in|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Positions held==\n* Vice-Chairman - District Board, [[Muzaffarnagar]] \n* Chairman - Town  Area, Purqazi \n* Member - [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] 1969-74\n* Member - 6th Lok  Sabha, 1977\u201379 \n* Deputy Minister of Irrigation, Uttar Pradesh\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Vijaypal Singh Tomar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar]] |years=1977 \u2013 1979}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ghayoor Ali Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murtaza, Saeed}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:6th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Lok Dal politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Muzaffarnagar]]\n[[Category:Members of the Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradesh MLAs 1969\u20131974\u200e\u200e]]\n[[Category:Janata Party politicians]]\n\n{{UttarPradesh-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=April 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Saeed Murtaza\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| office = [[Lok Sabha|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar]]\n| term_start = March 1977\n| term_end = August 1979\n| predecessor = [[Vijaypal Singh Tomar]]\n| successor = Ghayoor Ali Khan\n| party =\n| religion =  \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source =  http://164.100.47.194/loksabha/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/2555.htm\n}}\n\n'''Saeed Murtaza'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://164.100.47.194/loksabha/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/2555.htm |title=Members : Lok Sabha |publisher=164.100.47.194 |date= |accessdate=2017-06-25}}</ref> was an [[List of political parties in India|Indian politician]]. He was from a SYED ZAMIDAAR family, his full name was Syed Saeed Murtaza. His elder brother \"Syed Saeed Mustafa\" was the main zamidar, but died early. Syed Saeed Mustafa handed over the leadership to Syed Saeed Murtaza. Syed Saeed Mustafa had one son \"Syed Zahoor mustafa\" and four grand sons \"Syed javed Mustafa\", \"Syed Parvez mustafa kazmi\", \"Syed Tariq mustafa\" and \"Syed Khalid Mustafa\". His great grand sons are \"Syed Nidal Mustafa\", \"Syed Danyal Mustafa\" and \"Syed Saqib Mustafa\". Saeed murtaza's sons are S.Saiduzzaman and Syed Saeed Qamruzzaman, S. Saiduzzaman was Member of parliament in 1999 at muzaffarnagar constituency from Indian national congress.\n\nSaeed Murtaza was a member of 6th [[Lok Sabha]] from [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar constituency]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]].\n\nHis family is Iraqi biradri Syed and are direct descendants of Husayn ibn Ali (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Husayn_ibn_Ali). During the reign of Tulagh Dynasty, Firoz Shah tughlaq invited Syed Masud Al Husseini descendant of Husayn ibn Ali to fight the local raja. Syed Masud came with 40 warriors and his 9 sons to defeat the local raja. After defeating the local raja Syed masud al Husseini was rewarded with 746 villages and qaziat of 8 places, his lineage is called Iraqi biradri.\n\nSaeed murtaza's family are direct descendant of Syed Masud Al husseini.\n\nSaeed Murtaza died on 30 September 1996 by natural causes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loksabha.nic.in/members/lokaralpha.aspx?lsno=6&search=S|title=Members : Lok Sabha|website=loksabha.nic.in|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Positions held==\n* Vice-Chairman - District Board, [[Muzaffarnagar]] \n* Chairman - Town  Area, Purqazi \n* Member - [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] 1969-74\n* Member - 6th Lok  Sabha, 1977\u201379 \n* Deputy Minister of Irrigation, Uttar Pradesh\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Vijaypal Singh Tomar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Muzaffarnagar (Lok Sabha constituency)|Muzaffarnagar]] |years=1977 \u2013 1979}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ghayoor Ali Khan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murtaza, Saeed}}\n[[Category:6th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n\n\n{{UttarPradesh-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saeed_Murtaza"}
{"title_page": "James Worthy (record producer)", "text_new": "{{notability|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = James Worthy\n| image              = Unnamed james 2.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption      = Worthy in 2015\n| background   = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name   = James Allen Worthy\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1992|3|28}}\n| birth_place  = [[Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US\n| genre           = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[R&B]]\n| occupation      = Record Producer, Songwriter, Singer, Artist\n| instrument      = Vocals, Keyboards, Guitar\n| years_active    = 2010\u2013present\n| label           = [[Sony]], [[Empire Distribution]], [[Bad Boy Records]]\n| associated_acts =  [[Robin S]], [[Truth Hurts (singer)|Truth Hurts]], [[Fetty Wap]], [[6LACK]], [[Tony Terry]], [[Bobby Brown]], [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], [[PM Dawn]], [[Jaden Smith]], [[Kalenna Harper]]\n| website         = {{URL|www.Kingjamesworthy.com}}\n}}\n'''James Allen Worthy''' (born March 28, 1992), professionally known as '''James Worthy''', is an American [[R&B]] singer, songwriter, and record producer. Worthy is responsible for his work with musical artists including [[Fetty Wap]], [[6LACK]], [[T-Pain]], [[Truth Hurts (singer)|Truth Hurts]], [[Robin S]], [[Tony Terry]], and [[PM Dawn]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Queens]], New York, he moved with his family to Atlanta as a teenager.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Francis |first1=Kera |title=James Worthy, not the basketball player, is making moves in the music industry |url=https://theundefeated.com/features/james-worthy-not-the-basketball-player-is-making-moves-in-the-music-industry/ |website=theundefeated.com}}</ref> His parents were both in the entertainment and travel industry. At age 16 he began self teaching himself how to craft music production which led him to his first publishing contract with [[Sony]]. Shortly after he attended [[Art Institute of Atlanta]] where he earned a bachelors degree in audio production.\n\n== Career ==\nWorthy came to prominence with producing, and writing for artists such as [[Lil Zane]], [[Kalenna Harper]], [[Sammie]], [[Yung Berg]], [[Fetty Wap]], and many others.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whaley|first1=Kacie|title=James Worthy is the next breakout music producer|url=http://rollingout.com/2015/08/25/james-worthy-next-breakout-music-producer/|website=Rollingout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Burton |first1=Brittany |title=RESPECT. Magazine Catches Up with James Worthy |url=https://respect-mag.com/2018/10/respect-mag-catches-up-with-james-worthy/ |website=respect-mag.com}}</ref> His most notable production work include \"Fight 4 Love\" by [[Truth Hurts (singer)|Truth Hurts]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=JusMusic|first1=DJ|title=Dr Dre\u2019s Former Artist Truth Hurts Drops New Single, \"Fight 4 Love\"|url=http://singersroom.com/content/2015-08-10/Dr-Dres-Former-Artist-Truth-Hurts-Drops-New-Single-Fight-4-Love/|website=Singersroom.com}}</ref> \"1 & Only\" by Jhonni Blaze, \"Blessing Me\" by [[Robin S]], \"Drip\" by [[Sammie]] & J Young MDK. In 2017, Worthy has also pursued acting, and has been featured on ''Access Hollywood'', and appeared on BET's docu series ''From the Bottom Up'' Season 1.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yohance|first1=Kyles|title=EXCLUSIVE: James Worthy Discusses His Production Work, Appearing On Centric\u2019s \u2018From The Bottom Up\u2019 & More|url=http://allhiphop.com/2016/01/15/exclusive-james-worthy-producer-atlanta-sara-stokes-from-the-bottom-up/|website=Allhiphop.com}}</ref> In 2017 he joined the duo group Kings X2 where they released their debut single \"Wine For Me\". The song peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Hot Singles Chart.\n\n===Solo===\nWorthy embarked on a career as a performer. His debut EP, ''Blu Leisure'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Samone |first1=Its K |title=Music Producer and Artist James Worthy Talks The Release Of His EP Blu Leisure, Cardi B\u2019s Grammy Win and His Respect For Kayne West |url=https://hotspotatl.com/3745703/music-producer-and-artist-talks-cardi-bs-grammy-win-his-respect-for-kayne-and-ep-blu-leisure/ |website=hotspotatl.com}}</ref> was released January 11, 2019 through [[Empire Distribution]]. Worthy's debut single was entitled \"Move\" which featured [[Whodini]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Oktane |title=James Worthy \u2013 Move Ft. Ecstacy |url=http://hiphopsince1987.com/2018/music/james-worthy-move-ft-ecstacy/ |website=hiphopsince1987.com}}</ref> In January 2020, Worthy released his sophomore EP ''Kaleidoscopes''<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rossow |first1=Andrew |title=Looking at the Music Industry Through 'Kaleidoscopes' |url=http://editors.people.msnbc.com/_news/2020/02/12/38816687-looking-at-the-music-industry-through-kaleidoscopes |website=MSNBC.com}}</ref> which was co executive produced by [[PM Dawn]]. The lead single for Worthy's 2020 release was titled ''Higher & Higher''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=2Bees |first1=Miss |title=ACTOR-SINGER JAMES WORTHY TALKS WORKING WITH 90S LEGENDS, GRAMMYS, KALEIDOSCOPES, & MORE |url=https://thesource.com/2020/02/18/actor-singer-james-worthy-talks-working-with-90s-legends-grammys-kaleidoscopes-more/ |website=thesource.com}}</ref>\n\n== Production discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Song title !! Year !! Artist !! Single/Album !! Co-producer\n|-\n| Electric Disco || 2012 || [[Yung Berg]] || Twitter Music Vol 2\n|-\n| Coolin || 2012 || Bobby Brown Jr || Single\n|-\n| Deja Vu || 2012 || Elise 5000, [[Petey Pablo]] || Single\n|-\n| Everybody Else || 2012 || Elise 5000, [[T-Pain]] || Single\n|-\n| Inked Up || 2013 || [[Markice Moore]], Kwony Cash || Single\n|-\n| Nobody's Safe || 2014 || Bobby Brown Jr, [[Bobby Brown]] || Single\n|-\n| Sneak Peek || 2015 || Sara Stokes, Babs || Single || Wala Beatz\n|-\n| Fight 4 Love || 2015 || [[Truth Hurts (singer)|Truth Hurts]] || Single\n|-\n| Con