f\n| Guest, credited as James Worthy \n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[USA Network]]'' [[Chrisley Knows Best]] Season 5 EP 6\n| Himself\n| Guest\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n* 2017: ''Love By Chance''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.kingjamesworthy.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worthy, James}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Diddy\u2192Sean Combs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Worthy_(record_producer)"}
{"title_page": "Robert Trujillo", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Robert Trujillo\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = TrujilloFantsticFest2103.jpg\n| caption = Trujillo in September 2013\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=y|1964|10|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Monica, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[funk metal]]\n* [[crossover thrash]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument = Vocals, Bass, Guitar<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| label = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Elektra Records|Elektra]], [[Megaforce Records|Megaforce]], Blackened\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Metallica]]\n* [[Suicidal Tendencies]]\n* [[Infectious Grooves]]\n* [[Mass Mental]]\n* [[Black Label Society]]\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n* Medication\n* [[Jerry Cantrell]]\n* [[Glenn Tipton]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|metallica.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Trujillo''' ({{IPAc-en|t|r|u\u02d0|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|j|o\u028a}} {{respell|troo|HEE|yoh}}, {{IPA-es|ro\u02c8\u03b2e\u027eto t\u027eu\u02c8xi\u028eo|lang}}; born October 23, 1964)<ref name=\"metcom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metallica.com/band/band-bio-robert.asp |title=Robert Trujillo |publisher=Metallica |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> is an American musician and songwriter. He has been the bassist of the American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Metallica]] since 2003. He was also a member of [[crossover thrash]] band [[Suicidal Tendencies]], [[funk metal]] supergroup [[Infectious Grooves]], heavy metal band [[Black Label Society]], and has worked with [[Jerry Cantrell]] and [[Ozzy Osbourne]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nRoberto Agust\u00edn Miguel Santiago Samuel Juan Pablo Gonzalo Fernando Gabriel P\u00e9rez De La Santa Concepci\u00f3n Trujillo Veracruz Bautista was born in [[Santa Monica, California]] on October 23, 1964. He is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://juicemagazine.com/home/metallica/ |title=METALLICA \u2013 ROBERT TRUJILLO interview by JEFF HO|quote= Growing up on the West Side (LA), where people kill each other for being from the wrong zip code, Robert has managed to stay focused on family and music. He is one of the world's leading bass guitarists. Hard playing kick ass is his style. Metallica is his main focus and number one priority. Surfing is one of his passions. He says music goes hand in hand with surfing. THIS IS ROBERT TRUJILLO |publisher=Juicemagazine.com |date= |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}.</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Lucas H. Gordon\n | year = 2014\n | title = Discover Hetfield, Ulrich and Hammett's Personalities Thru the Eyes of Trujillo\n | medium = Interview\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SmIa4K8Wv-c\n | time = 4:00\n | publisher = Lucas H. Gordon\n}}</ref> He grew up in [[Culver City, California]],<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/top-posts/robert-trujillo-my-life-story/ Accessed on June 24, 2013.</ref> where his father was a teacher at [[Culver City High School]].{{Citation needed|reason= here|date=June 2019}} Trujillo garnered interest in music during his childhood; his mother was a huge fan of [[Motown]], particularly musicians like [[Marvin Gaye]], [[James Brown]], and [[Sly and the Family Stone]].<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/> Trujillo stated that \"[[Jaco Pastorius|Jaco]] [Pastorius] was my hero growing up\", and that the iconic jazz bassist changed his view of what the instrument could play: \"Hearing him was like hearing [[Eddie Van Halen]] doing \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\" for the first time: You thought, 'What instrument is that?' I loved jazz fusion and branched out from there. But Jaco had an edge that far exceeded his jazz persona. He was funk, he was rock, he was soul. And his whole attitude was punk.\"<ref>Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo Funding Jaco Pastorius Biopic\nPosted April 6, 2012 at 11:09am | by Damian Fanelli http://www.guitarworld.com/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillo-funding-jaco-pastorius-biopic Accessed on June 24, 2013.</ref> He began playing in \"a lot of backyard party bands\", playing music by [[Black Sabbath]], [[Ozzy Osbourne|Ozzy]], [[Rush (band)|Rush]], and [[Led Zeppelin]].<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/> He went to jazz school when he was 19 with the intention of becoming a studio musician, but he maintained his passion for rock and metal.<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Career===\nTrujillo first gained prominence when he replaced [[Bob Heathcote]] as the bassist for California [[crossover thrash]] band [[Suicidal Tendencies]]. Initially billed as \"Stymee\" on the 1989 album ''[[Controlled by Hatred/Feel Like Shit...D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]'', Trujillo remained in the band until the mid-1990s. Concurrent to his work with Suicidal Tendencies, Trujillo was also a member of the band's side project, [[Infectious Grooves]], along with vocalist [[Mike Muir]].\n\nTrujillo was a member of Ozzy Osbourne's band for a number of years starting in the late 1990s. In contrast to his earlier jazz and funk inspired playing, Osbourne's band was more straightforward to hard rock and metal.<ref name=\"Jeff Ho, Juice interview\">Jeff Ho, ''Juice'' interview.</ref> Trujillo also co-wrote several songs on the ''[[Down to Earth (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Down to Earth]]'' album.<ref name=\"Jeff Ho, Juice interview\"/> He was the subject of controversy for re-recording [[Bob Daisley]]'s bass tracks for reissued versions of Osbourne's first two solo albums ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' (1980) and ''[[Diary of a Madman (album)|Diary of a Madman]]'' (1981) after Daisley claimed that he was not paid proper royalties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/osbourneozzy-blizzard/ |title=Ozzy Osbourne \u2013 Blizzard of Ozz / Diary of a Madman |last=Begrand |first=Adrien |publisher=[[PopMatters]] |date=25 June 2002 |accessdate=24 October 2015 }}</ref> During this time, Trujillo formed an experimental supergroup, [[Mass Mental]], with then [[Dub War]] singer [[Benji Webbe]], whose \"ragga-punk-metal\" outfit had just disbanded. The band released one studio album (released exclusively in Japan) and one live album of their performance in Tokyo before disbanding.<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://askearache.blogspot.com/2009/09/rob-trujillo-benji-webbe-mass-mental.html|title=ASK EARACHE: Rob Trujillo & Benji Webbe = Mass Mental|publisher=askearache.blogspot.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Zakk Wylde, a personal friend and bandmate from the Ozzy days, also recruited him to play with Black Label Society for a few shows.\n\nTrujillo joined [[Metallica]] on February 24, 2003, two years after [[Jason Newsted]] resigned. He had previously met and befriended his future bandmates when [[Suicidal Tendencies]] supported Metallica during the [[Nowhere Else to Roam]] tour in 1993, and again during the [[Shit Hits the Sheds Tour|Shit Hits the Sheds]] tour one year later. Trujillo received one million dollars from the band as an advance for joining Metallica. His audition and hiring as well as his million dollar payment offer appeared in the documentary film ''[[Metallica: Some Kind of Monster]]''. As the current bassist for Metallica, he was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] alongside all current members of the band, as well previous bassists Jason Newsted and the late [[Cliff Burton]].\n\n===Personal life===\nTrujillo is married and has a son, Tye, and daughter, Lullah.<ref name=\"metcom\" /><ref name=\"rebwil\">{{cite web|url=http://punkglobe.com/chloetrujillointerview409.html |title=Seeing Through the Heart \u2013 an afternoon interview with artist Chole Trujillo |first=Rebecca G. |last=Wilson |publisher=Punk Globe |accessdate=May 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313161515/http://punkglobe.com/chloetrujillointerview409.html |archivedate=March 13, 2012 }}</ref> In April 2017, Tye performed with [[Korn]] during their South American tour, filling in for longtime bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Childers|first=Chad|title=Watch 12-year-old Tye Trujillo Make His Korn Debut in Colombia|url=http://loudwire.com/watch-12-year-old-tye-trujillo-korn-debut-colombia/|publisher=loudwire|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> Trujillo's wife, Chlo\u00e9, has also created a [[pyrography]] design of the [[Aztec calendar]] on one of his basses.<ref name=\"photobucket\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo5.jpg|date=January 29, 2009|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo5.jpg, (682 \u00d7 1023 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"photobucket2\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo6.jpg|date=February 9, 2009|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo6.jpg, (768 \u00d7 1024 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"photobucket3\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo7.jpg|date=October 5, 2008|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo7.jpg, (1024 \u00d7 768 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nIn 2012, Trujillo began producing a documentary about jazz bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]] entitled ''[[Jaco (film)|Jaco]]'', directed by [[Stephen Kijak]] and Paul Marchand. The film was named Official Film of Record Store Day 2014 and was released in November 2014.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/story/2012-05-23/metallica-trujillo-movie-jaco-pastorius/55178046/1|title=Trujillo swings from Metallica to jazz biopic \u2013 USATODAY.com|publisher=usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"loudwire\">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/metallica-robert-trujillo-show-jaco-pastorius-film-clip-bass-player-event/|title=Metallica&#8217;s Robert Trujillo to Show Jaco Pastorius Film Clip at Bass Player Event|publisher=loudwire.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillos-jaco-documentary-named-official-film-of-record-store-day/|title=Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo&#x27;s &#x27;Jaco&#x27; Documentary Named Official Film Of &#x27;Record Store Day&#x27; - Blabbermouth.net|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Technique==\n[[File:Robert Trujillo by Gage Skidmore.jpg|170px|thumb|right|upright|Trujillo at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic Con International]] in San Diego.]]\nTrujillo is primarily a finger-style player, but has been well documented playing with a [[Plectrum|pick]]. Trujillo's predecessor in Metallica, Jason Newsted, was almost exclusively a pick-style player, while [[Cliff Burton]], Newsted's predecessor and bassist on Metallica's [[Kill 'Em All|first]] [[Ride The Lightning|three]] [[Master Of Puppets|albums]], played finger-style exclusively. Trujillo is known for playing \"massive chords\"<ref>{{cite web|author=G.M. Jameson|title=Robert Trujillo Demands Something Solid|url=http://www.rottenbass.com/warwick-robert-trujillo-signature-bass-57|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622112825/http://www.rottenbass.com/warwick-robert-trujillo-signature-bass-57|archivedate=June 22, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> and \"chord-based harmonics\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo Funding Jaco Pastorius Biopic\n|date=April 6, 2012|author=Damian Fanelli|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillo-funding-jaco-pastorius-biopic|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> on the bass.\n\nTrujillo also uses the [[slap bass]] technique, seen mostly in his work with Suicidal Tendencies and especially Infectious Grooves. At many of the shows during Metallica's 2004 [[Madly in Anger with the World Tour]], Trujillo would often play an extended bass solo (dubbed \"Jungle Essence\" on recordings), which made extensive use of slap bass and other techniques and effects.\n\nFor recording purposes, Trujillo uses his own code for writing down bass arrangements. Inspired by an article by [[Pino Palladino]], he developed this during the recording sessions for Jerry Cantrell's ''[[Degradation Trip]]'', which, according to Trujillo, had him working from \"little hoodrat demos\" with nearly inaudible bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bassguitarmagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=156:robert-trujillo-metallica-bgm-issue-32&catid=43:artist-interviews&Itemid=70|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132808/http://www.bassguitarmagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=156:robert-trujillo-metallica-bgm-issue-32&catid=43:artist-interviews&Itemid=70|archivedate=April 2, 2012|title=Robert Trujillo \u2013 Metallica|publisher=[[Bass Guitar (magazine)|Bass Guitar]]|date=September\u2013October 2007|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===Bass guitars===\nWith Metallica, Trujillo has primarily been playing [[Warwick (bass guitar)|Warwick]] Streamer bass guitars, both 5 and 4-strings. His signature model Streamer bass was released in March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/Magazine/Issue/Daily/News/Warwick_Debuts_Robert_Trujillo_Signature_Bass.aspx|title=Warwick Debuts Robert Trujillo Signature Streamer Bass|date=March 1, 2010|accessdate=May 17, 2010|newspaper=[[Premier Guitar]]}}</ref> He also often plays [[Fernandes Guitars|Fernandes]] Gravity 5-string basses, particularly a model with a silver finish, blue flame decals, and [[EMG, Inc.|EMG]] pickups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emginc.com/artists/featuredArtist/231 |title=Electric Guitar Pickups & Accessories \u2013 EMG Pickups &#124; Robert Trujillo |publisher=Emginc.com |date=February 24, 2003 |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}</ref>   In addition to his signature Warwick basses, [[Zon Guitars]] also produce a signature bass model, the Sonus RT. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zonguitars.com/zonguitars/trujillo_bio.html |title=Robert Trujillo |publisher=Zon Guitars |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> Prior to Metallica, he was most often seen playing [[Tobias (bass guitar company)|Tobias]], [[ESP Guitars|ESP]] and [[Music Man StingRay 5|MusicMan]] basses (all 5-strings), as well as a [[Fender Precision Bass]] with Black Label Society<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QAodnkz6AI4 |title=Black Label Society \u2013 Born To Lose |publisher=YouTube |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}</ref> and Ozzy Osbourne. Trujillo has been seen in concert playing a [[Yamaha]] TRB5-P2 5-string bass, a customized green [[Rickenbacker]] 4001/4003 4-string bass modified with EMG pickups, various Nash P-Bass Copy guitars,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uthmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg |title=Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg (image) |publisher=uthmag.com |accessdate=April 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919055253/http://uthmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg |archivedate=September 19, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=http://ipolitics_assets.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/8882116.jpg|title=Image: 8882116.jpg, (2338 \u00d7 1704 px) \u2013 Bass guitarist Robert Trujillo of the American heavy metal band Metallica performs during their Sonisphere festival concert in Warsaw, Poland, Wednesday, June 16, 2010.(AP Photo/Alik Keplicz)|publisher=ipolitics_assets.s3.amazonaws.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> and both a classic Fender Precision Bass<ref>http://img534.imageshack.us/img534/2184/fenderprecisionbass1blk.jpg</ref> and [[Fender Jazz Bass]].<ref name=\"last\">{{cite web|url=http://userserve-ak.last.fm/serve/_/9480747/Robert%2BTrujillo%2B1058734310587346large.jpg|title=Image: Robert%2BTrujillo%2B1058734310587346large.jpg, (387 \u00d7 580 px)|publisher=userserve-ak.last.fm|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Trujillo is also the custodian of [[Jaco Pastorius]]' legendary \"Bass Of Doom\" (the sunburst fretless 1962 [[Fender Jazz Bass|Jazz Bass]] used by Pastorius on most of his recordings and live appearances). <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicgearreview.com/article-display/3410.html|title=Metallica's Trujillo buys Jaco's 'Bass of Doom'|website=www.musicgearreview.com|access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> He has performed onstage with Metallica with the instrument. \n\nFor amplification, he uses [[Ampeg]] amplifiers and cabinets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ampeg.com/artists/artist.php?artistID=109 |title=Artist Profile \u2013 Robert Trujillo |publisher=Ampeg |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504074347/http://www.ampeg.com/artists/artist.php?artistID=109 |archivedate=May 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trujillo recently collaborated with [[Dunlop Manufacturing|Jim Dunlop]] to create his new Icon signature bass strings \u2013 these strings are taper-core stainless steel, with a non-tapered B string in gauges 45\u2013130 (5-string).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimdunlop.com/index.php?page=products/strings_pip&id=385&pmh=products/strings |title=Robert Trujillo Icon Series Bass Strings Stainless Steel Taper Core |publisher=Dunlop |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Effects===\nTrujillo's pedal board consists of an [[Electro Harmonix]] Q-Tron, a Tech 21 [[Tech 21|SansAmp]] Bass Driver DI, a Tech 21 XXL, an [[MXR]] m-135 SmartGate, a [[Morley Pedals|Morley]] [[Mark Tremonti]] wah pedal, and a [[Boss Corporation|Boss]] OC-2 Octave Pedal; all powered by a Voodoo Lab Pedal Power.<ref>Bass Player Magazine \u2013 November 2008</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Jerry Cantrell===\n* ''[[Degradation Trip]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Degradation Trip Volumes 1 & 2]] (2002)\n\n===Black Label Society===\n* ''[[1919 Eternal]]'' (2002)\n\n===Infectious Grooves===\n* ''[[The Plague That Makes Your Booty Move...It's the Infectious Grooves]]'' (1991)\n* ''Encino Man Soundtrack'' (1992)\n* ''[[Sarsippius' Ark]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Groove Family Cyco]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Mas Borracho]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Year of the Cycos]]'' (2008)\n* ''Funk It Up \u2013 Live in France 1995'' (2010)\n* ''Mad Mad Muir Musical Tour'' (2011)\n\n===Suicidal Tendencies===\n* ''[[Lights...Camera...Revolution!]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[The Art of Rebellion]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Still Cyco After All These Years]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Suicidal for Life]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Freedumb]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Year of the Cycos]]'' (2008)\n* ''Mad Mad Muir Musical Tour'' (2011)\n\n===Glenn Tipton===\n* ''[[Baptizm of Fire]]'' (1997)\n\n===Mass Mental?===\n* ''[[How To Write Love Songs]]'' (1999)\n* ''Live in Tokyo'' (2001)\n\n===Ozzy Osbourne===\n* ''[[Down to Earth (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Down to Earth]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' (reissue) (2002)\n* ''[[Diary of a Madman (album)|Diary of a Madman]]'' (reissue) (2002)\n* ''[[Live at Budokan (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Live at Budokan]] (2002)\n\n===Metallica===\n{{main|Metallica discography}}\n<!-- Rob was credited as performing on the album so it can be listed regardless and I have added a note that he does not play so what's the problem? Someone could see his name in the booklet and believe that he performs on the album so this would inform people that he doesn't in fact play, he is just credited! -->\n* ''[[St. Anger]]'' (2003) <small>(Credited but does not play. Features on the deluxe edition, live DVD and music videos)</small>\n* ''[[Death Magnetic]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' (with [[Lou Reed]]) (2011)\n* ''[[Beyond Magnetic]]'' (EP) (2011)\n* ''[[Hardwired... to Self-Destruct]]'' (2016)\n\n===Various artists===\n* \"The Blackest Box \u2013 The Ultimate Metallica Tribute\" (2002)\n* \"[[A Song for Chi]]\" (2009)\n* A.N.I.M.A.L. - \"Poder Latino\" (guest in song track 6)\n* Farmikos - \"Farmikos\" (2015)\n\n==Videography==\n* ''[[Live at Budokan (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Live at Budokan]]'' live album with accompanying live DVD\n* ''[[St. Anger]]'' live bonus DVD \u2013 2003\n* ''[[Metallica: Some Kind of Monster]]'' Metallica documentary\n* ''[[The Videos 1989\u20132004]]'' video compilation DVD\n* ''[[Fran\u00e7ais Pour Une Nuit]]'' live DVD from the concert in N\u00eemes\n* ''[[Orgullo, Pasi\u00f3n, y Gloria: Tres Noches en la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico]]'' live DVD from the concerts in Mexico City\n* ''[[The Big Four: Live from Sofia, Bulgaria|The Big Four]]'' live DVD from Sofia, Bulgaria\n* ''[[Metallica Through the Never]]'' 2013 movie\n* ''[[Boozed, Broozed, and Broken-Boned]]'' live DVD from Detroit, Michigan\n\n==Video game appearances==\n\nTrujillo is in the ''[[Metallica]]'' exclusive adaptation of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' video game series known as ''[[Guitar Hero: Metallica]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n| before=[[Bob Rock]] (Sessions)\n| title=[[Metallica]] bassist\n| years=2003\u2013present\n| after=''Current''\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|874235}}\n\n{{Metallica}}\n{{Black Label Society}}\n{{SuicidalTendencies}}\n{{Ozzy Osbourne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trujillo, Robert}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Metallica members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:Native American musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:Suicidal Tendencies members]]\n[[Category:The Ozzy Osbourne Band members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Black Label Society members]]\n[[Category:Mass Mental members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Robert Trujillo\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image = TrujilloFantsticFest2103.jpg\n| caption = Trujillo in September 2013\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=y|1964|10|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Monica, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n* [[funk metal]]\n* [[crossover thrash]]\n* [[hardcore punk]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument = Vocals, Bass, Guitar<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| label = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Elektra Records|Elektra]], [[Megaforce Records|Megaforce]], Blackened\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Metallica]]\n* [[Suicidal Tendencies]]\n* [[Infectious Grooves]]\n* [[Mass Mental]]\n* [[Black Label Society]]\n* [[Ozzy Osbourne]]\n* Medication\n* [[Jerry Cantrell]]\n* [[Glenn Tipton]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|metallica.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Trujillo''' ({{IPAc-en|t|r|u\u02d0|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|j|o\u028a}} {{respell|troo|HEE|yoh}}, {{IPA-es|ro\u02c8\u03b2e\u027eto t\u027eu\u02c8xi\u028eo|lang}}; born October 23, 1964)<ref name=\"metcom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metallica.com/band/band-bio-robert.asp |title=Robert Trujillo |publisher=Metallica |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> is an American musician and songwriter. He has been the bassist of the American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Metallica]] since 2003. He was also a member of [[crossover thrash]] band [[Suicidal Tendencies]], [[funk metal]] supergroup [[Infectious Grooves]], heavy metal band [[Black Label Society]], and has worked with [[Jerry Cantrell]] and [[Ozzy Osbourne]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nTrujillo was born in [[Santa Monica, California]] on October 23, 1964. He is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://juicemagazine.com/home/metallica/ |title=METALLICA \u2013 ROBERT TRUJILLO interview by JEFF HO|quote= Growing up on the West Side (LA), where people kill each other for being from the wrong zip code, Robert has managed to stay focused on family and music. He is one of the world's leading bass guitarists. Hard playing kick ass is his style. Metallica is his main focus and number one priority. Surfing is one of his passions. He says music goes hand in hand with surfing. THIS IS ROBERT TRUJILLO |publisher=Juicemagazine.com |date= |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}.</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Lucas H. Gordon\n | year = 2014\n | title = Discover Hetfield, Ulrich and Hammett's Personalities Thru the Eyes of Trujillo\n | medium = Interview\n | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SmIa4K8Wv-c\n | time = 4:00\n | publisher = Lucas H. Gordon\n}}</ref> He grew up in [[Culver City, California]],<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/top-posts/robert-trujillo-my-life-story/ Accessed on June 24, 2013.</ref> where his father was a teacher at [[Culver City High School]].{{Citation needed|reason= here|date=June 2019}} Trujillo garnered interest in music during his childhood; his mother was a huge fan of [[Motown]], particularly musicians like [[Marvin Gaye]], [[James Brown]], and [[Sly and the Family Stone]].<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/> Trujillo stated that \"[[Jaco Pastorius|Jaco]] [Pastorius] was my hero growing up\", and that the iconic jazz bassist changed his view of what the instrument could play: \"Hearing him was like hearing [[Eddie Van Halen]] doing \"[[Eruption (instrumental)|Eruption]]\" for the first time: You thought, 'What instrument is that?' I loved jazz fusion and branched out from there. But Jaco had an edge that far exceeded his jazz persona. He was funk, he was rock, he was soul. And his whole attitude was punk.\"<ref>Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo Funding Jaco Pastorius Biopic\nPosted April 6, 2012 at 11:09am | by Damian Fanelli http://www.guitarworld.com/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillo-funding-jaco-pastorius-biopic Accessed on June 24, 2013.</ref> He began playing in \"a lot of backyard party bands\", playing music by [[Black Sabbath]], [[Ozzy Osbourne|Ozzy]], [[Rush (band)|Rush]], and [[Led Zeppelin]].<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/> He went to jazz school when he was 19 with the intention of becoming a studio musician, but he maintained his passion for rock and metal.<ref name=\"metalhammer.co.uk\"/>\n\n===Career===\nTrujillo first gained prominence when he replaced [[Bob Heathcote]] as the bassist for California [[crossover thrash]] band [[Suicidal Tendencies]]. Initially billed as \"Stymee\" on the 1989 album ''[[Controlled by Hatred/Feel Like Shit...D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]'', Trujillo remained in the band until the mid-1990s. Concurrent to his work with Suicidal Tendencies, Trujillo was also a member of the band's side project, [[Infectious Grooves]], along with vocalist [[Mike Muir]].\n\nTrujillo was a member of Ozzy Osbourne's band for a number of years starting in the late 1990s. In contrast to his earlier jazz and funk inspired playing, Osbourne's band was more straightforward to hard rock and metal.<ref name=\"Jeff Ho, Juice interview\">Jeff Ho, ''Juice'' interview.</ref> Trujillo also co-wrote several songs on the ''[[Down to Earth (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Down to Earth]]'' album.<ref name=\"Jeff Ho, Juice interview\"/> He was the subject of controversy for re-recording [[Bob Daisley]]'s bass tracks for reissued versions of Osbourne's first two solo albums ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' (1980) and ''[[Diary of a Madman (album)|Diary of a Madman]]'' (1981) after Daisley claimed that he was not paid proper royalties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/osbourneozzy-blizzard/ |title=Ozzy Osbourne \u2013 Blizzard of Ozz / Diary of a Madman |last=Begrand |first=Adrien |publisher=[[PopMatters]] |date=25 June 2002 |accessdate=24 October 2015 }}</ref> During this time, Trujillo formed an experimental supergroup, [[Mass Mental]], with then [[Dub War]] singer [[Benji Webbe]], whose \"ragga-punk-metal\" outfit had just disbanded. The band released one studio album (released exclusively in Japan) and one live album of their performance in Tokyo before disbanding.<ref name=\"blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://askearache.blogspot.com/2009/09/rob-trujillo-benji-webbe-mass-mental.html|title=ASK EARACHE: Rob Trujillo & Benji Webbe = Mass Mental|publisher=askearache.blogspot.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Zakk Wylde, a personal friend and bandmate from the Ozzy days, also recruited him to play with Black Label Society for a few shows.\n\nTrujillo joined [[Metallica]] on February 24, 2003, two years after [[Jason Newsted]] resigned. He had previously met and befriended his future bandmates when [[Suicidal Tendencies]] supported Metallica during the [[Nowhere Else to Roam]] tour in 1993, and again during the [[Shit Hits the Sheds Tour|Shit Hits the Sheds]] tour one year later. Trujillo received one million dollars from the band as an advance for joining Metallica. His audition and hiring as well as his million dollar payment offer appeared in the documentary film ''[[Metallica: Some Kind of Monster]]''. As the current bassist for Metallica, he was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] alongside all current members of the band, as well previous bassists Jason Newsted and the late [[Cliff Burton]].\n\n===Personal life===\nTrujillo is married and has a son, Tye, and daughter, Lullah.<ref name=\"metcom\" /><ref name=\"rebwil\">{{cite web|url=http://punkglobe.com/chloetrujillointerview409.html |title=Seeing Through the Heart \u2013 an afternoon interview with artist Chole Trujillo |first=Rebecca G. |last=Wilson |publisher=Punk Globe |accessdate=May 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313161515/http://punkglobe.com/chloetrujillointerview409.html |archivedate=March 13, 2012 }}</ref> In April 2017, Tye performed with [[Korn]] during their South American tour, filling in for longtime bassist [[Reginald Arvizu]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Childers|first=Chad|title=Watch 12-year-old Tye Trujillo Make His Korn Debut in Colombia|url=http://loudwire.com/watch-12-year-old-tye-trujillo-korn-debut-colombia/|publisher=loudwire|date=April 18, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> Trujillo's wife, Chlo\u00e9, has also created a [[pyrography]] design of the [[Aztec calendar]] on one of his basses.<ref name=\"photobucket\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo5.jpg|date=January 29, 2009|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo5.jpg, (682 \u00d7 1023 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"photobucket2\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo6.jpg|date=February 9, 2009|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo6.jpg, (768 \u00d7 1024 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"photobucket3\">{{cite web|url=http://i211.photobucket.com/albums/bb141/openloveknot/april%20punkglobe/ChloeTrujillo7.jpg|date=October 5, 2008|title=Image: ChloeTrujillo7.jpg, (1024 \u00d7 768 px)|publisher=i211.photobucket.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nIn 2012, Trujillo began producing a documentary about jazz bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]] entitled ''[[Jaco (film)|Jaco]]'', directed by [[Stephen Kijak]] and Paul Marchand. The film was named Official Film of Record Store Day 2014 and was released in November 2014.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/story/2012-05-23/metallica-trujillo-movie-jaco-pastorius/55178046/1|title=Trujillo swings from Metallica to jazz biopic \u2013 USATODAY.com|publisher=usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"loudwire\">{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/metallica-robert-trujillo-show-jaco-pastorius-film-clip-bass-player-event/|title=Metallica&#8217;s Robert Trujillo to Show Jaco Pastorius Film Clip at Bass Player Event|publisher=loudwire.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillos-jaco-documentary-named-official-film-of-record-store-day/|title=Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo&#x27;s &#x27;Jaco&#x27; Documentary Named Official Film Of &#x27;Record Store Day&#x27; - Blabbermouth.net|publisher=blabbermouth.net|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Technique==\n[[File:Robert Trujillo by Gage Skidmore.jpg|170px|thumb|right|upright|Trujillo at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic Con International]] in San Diego.]]\nTrujillo is primarily a finger-style player, but has been well documented playing with a [[Plectrum|pick]]. Trujillo's predecessor in Metallica, Jason Newsted, was almost exclusively a pick-style player, while [[Cliff Burton]], Newsted's predecessor and bassist on Metallica's [[Kill 'Em All|first]] [[Ride The Lightning|three]] [[Master Of Puppets|albums]], played finger-style exclusively. Trujillo is known for playing \"massive chords\"<ref>{{cite web|author=G.M. Jameson|title=Robert Trujillo Demands Something Solid|url=http://www.rottenbass.com/warwick-robert-trujillo-signature-bass-57|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622112825/http://www.rottenbass.com/warwick-robert-trujillo-signature-bass-57|archivedate=June 22, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> and \"chord-based harmonics\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Metallica Bassist Robert Trujillo Funding Jaco Pastorius Biopic\n|date=April 6, 2012|author=Damian Fanelli|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/metallica-bassist-robert-trujillo-funding-jaco-pastorius-biopic|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> on the bass.\n\nTrujillo also uses the [[slap bass]] technique, seen mostly in his work with Suicidal Tendencies and especially Infectious Grooves. At many of the shows during Metallica's 2004 [[Madly in Anger with the World Tour]], Trujillo would often play an extended bass solo (dubbed \"Jungle Essence\" on recordings), which made extensive use of slap bass and other techniques and effects.\n\nFor recording purposes, Trujillo uses his own code for writing down bass arrangements. Inspired by an article by [[Pino Palladino]], he developed this during the recording sessions for Jerry Cantrell's ''[[Degradation Trip]]'', which, according to Trujillo, had him working from \"little hoodrat demos\" with nearly inaudible bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bassguitarmagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=156:robert-trujillo-metallica-bgm-issue-32&catid=43:artist-interviews&Itemid=70|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132808/http://www.bassguitarmagazine.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=156:robert-trujillo-metallica-bgm-issue-32&catid=43:artist-interviews&Itemid=70|archivedate=April 2, 2012|title=Robert Trujillo \u2013 Metallica|publisher=[[Bass Guitar (magazine)|Bass Guitar]]|date=September\u2013October 2007|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\n\n===Bass guitars===\nWith Metallica, Trujillo has primarily been playing [[Warwick (bass guitar)|Warwick]] Streamer bass guitars, both 5 and 4-strings. His signature model Streamer bass was released in March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierguitar.com/Magazine/Issue/Daily/News/Warwick_Debuts_Robert_Trujillo_Signature_Bass.aspx|title=Warwick Debuts Robert Trujillo Signature Streamer Bass|date=March 1, 2010|accessdate=May 17, 2010|newspaper=[[Premier Guitar]]}}</ref> He also often plays [[Fernandes Guitars|Fernandes]] Gravity 5-string basses, particularly a model with a silver finish, blue flame decals, and [[EMG, Inc.|EMG]] pickups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emginc.com/artists/featuredArtist/231 |title=Electric Guitar Pickups & Accessories \u2013 EMG Pickups &#124; Robert Trujillo |publisher=Emginc.com |date=February 24, 2003 |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}</ref>   In addition to his signature Warwick basses, [[Zon Guitars]] also produce a signature bass model, the Sonus RT. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zonguitars.com/zonguitars/trujillo_bio.html |title=Robert Trujillo |publisher=Zon Guitars |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref> Prior to Metallica, he was most often seen playing [[Tobias (bass guitar company)|Tobias]], [[ESP Guitars|ESP]] and [[Music Man StingRay 5|MusicMan]] basses (all 5-strings), as well as a [[Fender Precision Bass]] with Black Label Society<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QAodnkz6AI4 |title=Black Label Society \u2013 Born To Lose |publisher=YouTube |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=April 26, 2011}}</ref> and Ozzy Osbourne. Trujillo has been seen in concert playing a [[Yamaha]] TRB5-P2 5-string bass, a customized green [[Rickenbacker]] 4001/4003 4-string bass modified with EMG pickups, various Nash P-Bass Copy guitars,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uthmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg |title=Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg (image) |publisher=uthmag.com |accessdate=April 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919055253/http://uthmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Robert-Trujillo-from-Metallica-getting-his-rock-on.jpg |archivedate=September 19, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=http://ipolitics_assets.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/8882116.jpg|title=Image: 8882116.jpg, (2338 \u00d7 1704 px) \u2013 Bass guitarist Robert Trujillo of the American heavy metal band Metallica performs during their Sonisphere festival concert in Warsaw, Poland, Wednesday, June 16, 2010.(AP Photo/Alik Keplicz)|publisher=ipolitics_assets.s3.amazonaws.com|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> and both a classic Fender Precision Bass<ref>http://img534.imageshack.us/img534/2184/fenderprecisionbass1blk.jpg</ref> and [[Fender Jazz Bass]].<ref name=\"last\">{{cite web|url=http://userserve-ak.last.fm/serve/_/9480747/Robert%2BTrujillo%2B1058734310587346large.jpg|title=Image: Robert%2BTrujillo%2B1058734310587346large.jpg, (387 \u00d7 580 px)|publisher=userserve-ak.last.fm|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Trujillo is also the custodian of [[Jaco Pastorius]]' legendary \"Bass Of Doom\" (the sunburst fretless 1962 [[Fender Jazz Bass|Jazz Bass]] used by Pastorius on most of his recordings and live appearances). <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicgearreview.com/article-display/3410.html|title=Metallica's Trujillo buys Jaco's 'Bass of Doom'|website=www.musicgearreview.com|access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> He has performed onstage with Metallica with the instrument. \n\nFor amplification, he uses [[Ampeg]] amplifiers and cabinets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ampeg.com/artists/artist.php?artistID=109 |title=Artist Profile \u2013 Robert Trujillo |publisher=Ampeg |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504074347/http://www.ampeg.com/artists/artist.php?artistID=109 |archivedate=May 4, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trujillo recently collaborated with [[Dunlop Manufacturing|Jim Dunlop]] to create his new Icon signature bass strings \u2013 these strings are taper-core stainless steel, with a non-tapered B string in gauges 45\u2013130 (5-string).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimdunlop.com/index.php?page=products/strings_pip&id=385&pmh=products/strings |title=Robert Trujillo Icon Series Bass Strings Stainless Steel Taper Core |publisher=Dunlop |accessdate=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Effects===\nTrujillo's pedal board consists of an [[Electro Harmonix]] Q-Tron, a Tech 21 [[Tech 21|SansAmp]] Bass Driver DI, a Tech 21 XXL, an [[MXR]] m-135 SmartGate, a [[Morley Pedals|Morley]] [[Mark Tremonti]] wah pedal, and a [[Boss Corporation|Boss]] OC-2 Octave Pedal; all powered by a Voodoo Lab Pedal Power.<ref>Bass Player Magazine \u2013 November 2008</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Jerry Cantrell===\n* ''[[Degradation Trip]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Degradation Trip Volumes 1 & 2]] (2002)\n\n===Black Label Society===\n* ''[[1919 Eternal]]'' (2002)\n\n===Infectious Grooves===\n* ''[[The Plague That Makes Your Booty Move...It's the Infectious Grooves]]'' (1991)\n* ''Encino Man Soundtrack'' (1992)\n* ''[[Sarsippius' Ark]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Groove Family Cyco]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Mas Borracho]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Year of the Cycos]]'' (2008)\n* ''Funk It Up \u2013 Live in France 1995'' (2010)\n* ''Mad Mad Muir Musical Tour'' (2011)\n\n===Suicidal Tendencies===\n* ''[[Lights...Camera...Revolution!]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[The Art of Rebellion]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Still Cyco After All These Years]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Suicidal for Life]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Freedumb]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Year of the Cycos]]'' (2008)\n* ''Mad Mad Muir Musical Tour'' (2011)\n\n===Glenn Tipton===\n* ''[[Baptizm of Fire]]'' (1997)\n\n===Mass Mental?===\n* ''[[How To Write Love Songs]]'' (1999)\n* ''Live in Tokyo'' (2001)\n\n===Ozzy Osbourne===\n* ''[[Down to Earth (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Down to Earth]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Blizzard of Ozz]]'' (reissue) (2002)\n* ''[[Diary of a Madman (album)|Diary of a Madman]]'' (reissue) (2002)\n* ''[[Live at Budokan (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Live at Budokan]] (2002)\n\n===Metallica===\n{{main|Metallica discography}}\n<!-- Rob was credited as performing on the album so it can be listed regardless and I have added a note that he does not play so what's the problem? Someone could see his name in the booklet and believe that he performs on the album so this would inform people that he doesn't in fact play, he is just credited! -->\n* ''[[St. Anger]]'' (2003) <small>(Credited but does not play. Features on the deluxe edition, live DVD and music videos)</small>\n* ''[[Death Magnetic]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Lulu (Lou Reed and Metallica album)|Lulu]]'' (with [[Lou Reed]]) (2011)\n* ''[[Beyond Magnetic]]'' (EP) (2011)\n* ''[[Hardwired... to Self-Destruct]]'' (2016)\n\n===Various artists===\n* \"The Blackest Box \u2013 The Ultimate Metallica Tribute\" (2002)\n* \"[[A Song for Chi]]\" (2009)\n* A.N.I.M.A.L. - \"Poder Latino\" (guest in song track 6)\n* Farmikos - \"Farmikos\" (2015)\n\n==Videography==\n* ''[[Live at Budokan (Ozzy Osbourne album)|Live at Budokan]]'' live album with accompanying live DVD\n* ''[[St. Anger]]'' live bonus DVD \u2013 2003\n* ''[[Metallica: Some Kind of Monster]]'' Metallica documentary\n* ''[[The Videos 1989\u20132004]]'' video compilation DVD\n* ''[[Fran\u00e7ais Pour Une Nuit]]'' live DVD from the concert in N\u00eemes\n* ''[[Orgullo, Pasi\u00f3n, y Gloria: Tres Noches en la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico]]'' live DVD from the concerts in Mexico City\n* ''[[The Big Four: Live from Sofia, Bulgaria|The Big Four]]'' live DVD from Sofia, Bulgaria\n* ''[[Metallica Through the Never]]'' 2013 movie\n* ''[[Boozed, Broozed, and Broken-Boned]]'' live DVD from Detroit, Michigan\n\n==Video game appearances==\n\nTrujillo is in the ''[[Metallica]]'' exclusive adaptation of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' video game series known as ''[[Guitar Hero: Metallica]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|\n| before=[[Bob Rock]] (Sessions)\n| title=[[Metallica]] bassist\n| years=2003\u2013present\n| after=''Current''\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|874235}}\n\n{{Metallica}}\n{{Black Label Society}}\n{{SuicidalTendencies}}\n{{Ozzy Osbourne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trujillo, Robert}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Metallica members]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:Native American musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Culver City, California]]\n[[Category:Suicidal Tendencies members]]\n[[Category:The Ozzy Osbourne Band members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Black Label Society members]]\n[[Category:Mass Mental members]]\n", "name_user": "186.139.116.90", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Trujillo"}
{"title_page": "God in Islam", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Muslim views of divinity}}{{Allah|related}}{{Islam |beliefs}}\nIn [[Islam]], [[God]] ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647|[[Allah|All\u0101h]]}}, contraction of {{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0652\u0625\u0650\u0644\u0670\u0647}} ''al-il\u0101h'', lit. \"the God\") is the [[Monotheism|absolute one]], the [[Omnipotence|all-powerful]] and [[Omniscience|all-knowing]] ruler of the universe, and the creator of everything in existence. Islam emphasizes that God is strictly singular (''[[tawhid|{{transl|ar|ALA|taw\u1e25\u012bd&#x202f;}}]]''); unique (''{{transl|ar|ALA|w\u0101\u1e25id&#x202f;}}''); inherently One (''{{transl|ar|ALA|a\u1e25ad&#x202f;}}'');<ref>John L. Esposito, ''Islam: The Straight Path'', Oxford University Press, 1998, p.88</ref> and also all-merciful and omnipotent.<ref name=\"Britannica\">\"Allah.\" [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]. 2007. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica</ref> According to Islam, God is neither a material nor a [[spirit]]ual being.<ref>Benjamin W. McCraw, Robert Arp ''Philosophical Approaches to Demonology'' Taylor & Francis 2017 {{ISBN|9781315466767}} page 138</ref> According to Islamic teachings, beyond the [[Throne_of_God#Islam|Throne]]<ref name=\"Britannica p3\">Britannica Encyclopedia, ''Islam'', p. 3</ref> and according to the [[Quran]], \"No vision can grasp him, but His grasp is over all vision: He is above all comprehension, yet is acquainted with all things.\"<ref>{{Cite Quran|6|103|t=y|s=ns}}</ref>\n\nIn Islam there is only one God and there are [[Names of God in Islam|99 names]] of that one God (''{{transl|ar|ALA|al-asm\u0101\u02bc al-\u1e25usn\u00e1}}'' lit. meaning: \"The best names\"), each of which evokes a distinct attribute of God.<ref name=\"Bentley\">{{cite book |last=Bentley |first=David |coauthors= |title=The 99 Beautiful Names for God for All the People of the Book |publisher=William Carey Library |date=September 1999 |isbn=0-87808-299-9 }}</ref><ref name=\"EncMMENA\">Encyclopedia of the Modern Middle East and North Africa, ''Allah''</ref> All these names refer to Allah, the supreme and all-comprehensive god.<ref name=\"Tao-Islam\">Annemarie Schimmel,''The Tao of Islam: A Sourcebook on Gender Relationships in Islamic'', SUNY Press, p.206</ref> Among the 99 names of God, the most familiar and frequent are \"the Compassionate\" (''{{transl|ar|ALA|Ar-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n}}'') and \"the Merciful\" (''{{transl|ar|ALA|Ar-Ra\u1e25\u012bm}}'').<ref name=\"Bentley\"/><ref name=\"EncMMENA\"/> Creation and ordering of the universe is seen as an act of prime mercy for which all creatures praise God's attributes and bear witness to God's unity.\n\n==Etymology==\n{{main|Allah}}\n''Allah'' is the [[Arabic language|Arabic]] word referring to [[God in Abrahamic religions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/empires/islam/faithgod.html |title=God |work=Islam: Empire of Faith |publisher=PBS|accessdate=18 December 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327034958/http://www.pbs.org/empires/islam/faithgod.html|archivedate=2014-03-27}}</ref><ref>\"Islam and Christianity\", ''Encyclopedia of Christianity'' (2001): Arabic-speaking Christians and Jews also refer to God as ''All\u0101h''.</ref><ref name=\"gardet-allah\">{{cite encyclopedia | url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/allah-COM_0047| title=Allah | encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Islam Online | first=L.|last=Gardet | accessdate=2 May 2007 |editor1-first=P.|editor1-last=Bearman|editor2-first=Th.|editor2-last=Bianquis|editor3-first=C.E.|editor3-last=Bosworth|editor4-first=E.|editor4-last=van Donzel|editor5-first=W.P.|editor5-last=Heinrichs|publisher=Brill Online}}</ref>\nIn the English language, the word generally refers to God in Islam. The word is thought to be derived by [[Contraction (grammar)|contraction]] from ''[[Arabic definite article|al]]-[[Ilah|il\u0101h]]'', which means \"the god\", and is related to ''[[El (deity)|El]]'' and ''[[Names of God in Judaism#Elah|Elah]]'', the [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] and [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] words for God.<ref>\n{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=isDgI0-0Ip4C&q=ilah#v=snippet&q=ilah&f=false |author=Zeki Saritoprak|title=Allah|editor=Oliver Leaman|encyclopedia=The Qur'an: An Encyclopedia|publisher=Routledge|year=2006|page=34}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|author=Vincent J. Cornell|title=God: God in Islam|editor=Lindsay Jones|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion|edition=2nd|publisher=MacMillan Reference USA|volume=5|year=2005|page=724}}</ref>  It is distinguished from ''{{transl|ar|ALA|il\u0101h}}'' ({{lang-ar|\u0625\u0644\u0647}}), the Arabic word meaning ''[[deity]]'', which could refer to any of the [[Pre-Islamic Arabian gods|gods worshipped in pre-Islamic Arabia]] or to any other deity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/empires/islam/faithgod.html |title=God |work=Islam: Empire of Faith |publisher=PBS|accessdate=2010-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Other names==\n{{main|Names of God in Islam}}\nGod is described and referred to in the Quran and ''[[hadith]]'' by 99 names that reflect his attributes.<ref name=\"Bentley22\">{{Cite book|title=The 99 Beautiful Names for God for All the People of the Book|last=Bentley|first=David|date=September 1999|publisher=William Carey Library|isbn=0-87808-299-9|coauthors=}}</ref> The Quran refers to the attributes of God as  \"most beautiful names\".<ref>{{cite quran|7|180|style=ns}}, {{cite quran|17|110|style=ns}}, {{cite quran|20|8|style=ns}}, {{cite quran|59|24|style=ns}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/article/opr/t125/e1708|title=Names of God - Oxford Islamic Studies Online|website=oxfordislamicstudies.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13|quote=Encouraged by the Quran (7:180; 17:110; 20:8), Muslims selected ninety-nine attributes of God, describing His perfection, from the Quran and traditions. Referred to as \u201cthe most beautiful names of God,\u201d they describe a range of characteristics that balances the power of God (the Creator, the Sovereign, and the All-Knowing) with His love and mercy (the All-Loving, the Most Gracious, and the All-Forgiving). The names are frequently memorized and used in supplications. Preceded by the words Abd or Amat (male or female servant), they are often used in proper names (e.g., Abd al-Rahman, \u201cservant of the Merciful\u201d).}}</ref> According to [[Gerhard B\u00f6wering]],\n\n{{quote|They are traditionally enumerated as 99 in number to which is added as the highest Name (al-ism al-\u02bea\u02bf\u1e93am), the Supreme Name of All\u0101h. The [[Wiktionary:locus classicus|locus classicus]] for listing the Divine Names in the literature of Qur\u02be\u0101nic commentary is [[Al-Isra|17:110]]<ref>{{Cite quran|17|110|s=ns}}</ref> \u201cCall upon Allah, or call upon The Merciful; whichsoever you call upon, to Allah belong the most beautiful Names,\u201d and also [[Al-Hashr|59:22-24]],<ref>{{Cite quran|59|22|e=24|s=ns}}</ref> which includes a cluster of more than a dozen Divine epithets.\"|Gerhard B\u00f6wering|''God and God's Attributes''<ref name=\"EoQ\">B\u00f6wering, Gerhard. \"God and God Attributes\". Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n.</ref>}}\n\nSome Muslims may use different names as much as Allah, for instance \"God\" in [[English language|English]].\n\n==Phrases and expressions==\nThere are numerous conventional phrases and expressions invoking God.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name || style=\"width:50%;\"| Phrase || style=\"width:30%;\"| Citation <br />(Quran or ''Sunnah'')\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Takbir|''Takb\u012bra'']]\n|-\n|''all\u0101hu \u02beakbar{{smallsup|u}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|9:72, 29:45, 40:10\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0623\u064e\u0644\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u064f \u0623\u064e\u0643\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0631\u064f }}\n|-\n|God is greater (than anything you see, hear, or do)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Subhan Allah|''Tasb\u012b\u1e25a'']]\n|-\n|''sub\u1e25\u0101na ll\u0101h{{smallsup|i}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|23:91, 28:68, 37:159, 52:43, 59:23\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0633\u064f\u0628\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0627\u0646\u064e \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u0650 }}\n|-\n|Glory to God\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Alhamdulillah|''Ta\u1e25m\u012bda'']]\n|-\n|''al-\u1e25amdu li-ll\u0101h{{smallsup|i}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|1:2, 6:1, 29:63, 31:25, 34:1, 35:1, 35:34, 39:29, 39:74, 39:75, 40:65\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0623\u064e\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064e\u0645\u0652\u062f\u064f \u0644\u0650\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u0650 }}\n|-\n|Praise be to God\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Shahada|''Tahl\u012bl'']]\n|-\n| ''l\u0101 \u02beil\u0101ha \u02beill\u0101 ll\u0101h{{smallsup|u}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|37:38, 47:19\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0644\u064e\u0627 \u0625\u0650\u0644\u064e\u0670\u0647\u064e \u0625\u0650\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u064f }}\n|-\n|(There is) no god but God\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Shahada]]''\n|-\n|''mu\u1e25ammadun ras\u016blu ll\u0101h{{smallsup|i}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|48:29\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0645\u064f\u062d\u064e\u0645\u064e\u0651\u062f\u064c \u0631\u064e\u0633\u064f\u0648\u0644\u064f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u0650 }}\n|-\n|Muhammad is the messenger of God \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Basmala]]''\n|-\n|''bi-smi ll\u0101hi r-ra\u1e25m\u0101ni r-ra\u1e25\u012bm{{smallsup|i}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|1:1\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar|  \u0628\u0650\u0633\u0652\u0645\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0651\u0670\u0647\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0670\u0646\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u064a\u0645 }} <ref>The phrase is encoded at [[Unicode]] code point [[Arabic Presentation Forms-A|U+FDFD]]  \ufdfd</ref>\n|-\n|in the name of God, the Beneficent, the Merciful\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|''[[Insha'Allah]]''\n\n|-\n|''\u02bein sh\u0101\u02bea ll\u0101h{{smallsup|u}}''||rowspan=\"3\"|2:70, 12:99, 18:69, 28:27, 48:27\n|-\n|{{rtl-lang|ar| \u0625\u0650\u0646\u0652 \u0634\u064e\u0627\